on with *Fangoria* magazine. When *Castle of Frankenstein* ceased publication in 1975, it merged with *Fangoria*, which continued the tradition of covering horror films, special effects, and related genres. This merger allowed readers to continue enjoying the content and expertise associated with *Castle of Frankenstein*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Print Format' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Castle of Frankenstein* was primarily a print magazine, providing readers with a tangible publication that they could collect and enjoy. The magazine featured high-quality printing and artwork, enhancing the reading experience and visually capturing the essence of the horror, science fiction, and fantasy genres.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After its merger with *Fangoria*, the legacy of *Castle of Frankenstein* lived on in the continued coverage of horror films, science fiction, and fantasy genres. The magazine played a significant role in nurturing a community of enthusiasts, providing insightful analysis, and celebrating the artistry and creativity within these genres.{{Category Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

