VALUES ( N'BattleTechnology', N'battletechnology', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Monthly publication covering futuristic military technology advancements and sci-fi entertainment in the BattleTech universe.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*BattleTechnology* is a magazine that was published irregularly between 1987 and 1995 by Pacific Rim Publishing Company. It was dedicated to *BattleTech*, a tabletop game of futuristic combat that was published at the time by FASA Corporation. The magazine includes game scenarios, optional rules, technical specifications for *BattleMechs* and other units, historical and current events in the fictional *BattleTech* universe, and short fiction. All of these components were approved by FASA, thus making the magazine an official source of optional materials for the game.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*BattleTechnology* follows an 8.5" x 11" format and generally includes about 60 pages per issue. It carries the subtitle: “the magazine of combat in the 31st century".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'There were twenty-one issues of *BattleTechnology* published, as well as two special editions, namely *The Lost Issues* and *The Early Years*. The first six issues, printed in 1987 and 1988, carried unique numbers: 0101, 0102, 0201, 0202, 0203, and 0204. The subsequent issues used normal sequential numbering, from 7 to 21. The first twelve issues were collected into a set known as *BattleTechnology: The War Years*. Issues 13 through 21 were compiled into *BattleTechnology: The Time of The Clans*.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Belt Pulley
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Belt Pulley', N'belt-pulley', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Magazine covering the latest developments in farm equipment, including belt and pulley machinery for agricultural operations.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*__Belt Pulley__* was a U.S.-based periodical that dedicated itself to the niche of antique farm tractors across all brands and makes. For over two decades, it thrived as one of the most well-regarded titles in this unique category. Run initially by the Aumann family, and later by the Elmore family, this publication was a testament to the enduring passion for the preservation and appreciation of agrarian history.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was not only a business venture but also a family affair, showcasing the concerted efforts of these families in nurturing a shared interest in the historical and mechanical facets of farming machinery. This focus on familial involvement imbued *Belt Pulley* with a distinct character, setting it apart in the landscape of niche publications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2009, a change of hands saw the magazine sold to a new proprietor. This ushered in a new era and a new identity, as the magazine was rechristened as *Vintage Tractor Digest*. This marked the end of *Belt Pulley*’s journey, but its legacy in celebrating and documenting the history of antique farm tractors continues to inspire enthusiasts to this day.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Berg's Review of Games
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Berg''s Review of Games', N'bergs-review-of-games', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Monthly publication featuring critical reviews and analysis of board games, video games, and tabletop gaming culture.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Italicized:* _Berg''s Review of Games_{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Berg''s Review of Games_, colloquially known as _BROG_, was a publication birthed from the creative mind of game designer Richard Berg. The magazine, which graced the world with its presence starting from the year 1991, was a testament to the designer''s passion for games, offering its readership insightful reviews of video wargames and board wargames alike.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication''s origins can be traced back to 1980, when Richard Berg, then plying his trade as a game designer for Simulations Publications Inc. (SPI), began crafting and curating reviews of wargames. These reviews were disseminated by SPI in the form of _Richard Berg''s Review of Games_. What started as a modest two-page mimeographed newsletter published twice a month for 25 issues eventually found a place in the pages of SPI''s _Strategy & Tactics_ until late 1985.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the autumn of 1991, Berg undertook the role of editor for a self-published fanzine, the eponymously titled _Berg''s Review of Games_, or _BROG_. To distinguish this new venture from his previous one, Berg appended "Vol. 2" to the issue number of the magazine. _BROG_ was published six times a year, its journey ending with Issue 28.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In his original _Richard Berg''s Review of Games_, Berg had initiated a humorous annual feature titled the “Little Mac Awards” in honor of the not-so-illustrious American Civil War general, George McClellan. These awards were given for dubious achievements in the realm of gaming. Continuing this tradition in Issue #2 of _BROG_, Berg distributed "Little Macs" to various companies and industry personalities as a playful rebuke for perceived errors and injustices.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its existence, _Berg''s Review of Games_ was met with considerable acclaim. It was bestowed the title of Best Amateur Adventure Gaming Magazine at the Origins Awards on three separate occasions: in 1992, 1993, and 1995. After its cessation, the publication''s legacy lived on, as it was posthumously inducted into the Academy of Adventure Gaming Arts & Design''s Hall of Fame in 1997. Despite its eventual end, _Berg''s Review of Games_ left an indelible mark on the gaming industry, serving as a testament to the importance of critique and analysis in the world of wargames.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Best Life
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Best Life', N'best-life', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Lifestyle magazine catering to affluent men, covering topics such as health, wealth, relationships, and career advice.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Best Life* was a luxury service magazine for men that originated in the United States and was published by Rodale, Inc. in Emmaus, Pennsylvania. It held a substantial circulation exceeding 500,000, and was actively in circulation between 2004 and May 2009. This publication was an offshoot of *Men''s Health*, commencing its individual journey in 2004. Published ten times a year, *Best Life* held a comprehensive coverage of health and fitness, finance, fatherhood, relationship issues, and fashion and grooming for men aged 35 and above. It placed a high emphasis on literary writing, humor, and in-depth research. Under the guidance of editorial director David Zinczenko and editor-in-chief Stephen Perrine, the magazine was named to Adweek''s Hot List in both 2007 and 2008. Notably, it was also nominated for a US National Magazine Award for its investigative feature “Our Oceans Are Turning to Plastic...Are We?”{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Best Life* sponsored various events such as the Best Life Vail Film Festival and the Best Life Classic Yacht Regatta in Newport, Rhode Island. However, the magazine ceased publication after its May 2009 issue. In 2012, it was announced that *Best Life* would return as a special interest publication in October 2012. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A notable feature of *Best Life* was its literary section. In 2005, it established its literary credentials by being the first to publish the “lost” manuscript by Jack Kerouac, entitled “Beat Generation”. The magazine became the literary home of writer-at-large David Mamet and columnists Mark Leyner and Billy Goldberg, Jr. Other contributing authors included Jay McInerney, Denis Johnson, Jim Harrison, and Anthony Bourdain. As of 2023, *Best Life* appears to be active as an online publication, continuing its mission to provide quality content for its readership.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Beyond Investigation Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Beyond Investigation Magazine', N'beyond-investigation-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Paranormal magazine covering supernatural phenomenon, unexplained mysteries, and investigations into the unknown.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Beyond Investigation Magazine* (BIM) is an American publication that spotlights *Beyond Investigation*, a group dedicated to the exploration of paranormal and conspiracy theory claims. Founded by Patrick Wheelock in 2004, *Beyond Investigation* was established with the mission of investigating alleged paranormal activities and publishing those investigations and related research in a periodical format. Due to the costs associated with publishing a limited circulation periodical, *Beyond Investigation Magazine* shifted its distribution formats to web and DVD after the first issue, which was the only one distributed in print form. In 2005, the magazine began webcasting audio programming, with the most notable show being *The Pat & Brian Show*.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Beyond Investigation* differentiates itself from most other paranormal investigation groups in its approach. Although they have occasionally collaborated with psychics, they neither attempt to purge nor explain paranormal activity. Instead, they focus on objectively documenting and analyzing data.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has gained visibility through its features on popular media. In 2006, *Beyond Investigation* was showcased on an episode of *Scariest Places on Earth*, which documented their paranormal investigation of the USS Hornet (CV-12), a World War II U.S. Navy aircraft carrier that had been transformed into a historical museum. In 2009, the group was selected as the "employer" for Tiffany Pollard, who tried her hand as a "ghost hunter" on her VH1 reality television series *New York Goes to Work*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Patrick Wheelock, the founder of *Beyond Investigation*, started investigating the paranormal in 1977. By 1994, he began conducting investigations with his friends, Steve Sonntag and Chris Brown. He formed *Beyond Investigation* in 2000, and added "Magazine" to the name in 2004. Wheelock felt that there was a lack of published, consumer-oriented, yet scientific research on the paranormal. The first edition of the magazine recapped some of the investigations done by Wheelock, Sonntag, and Brown, and introduced more recent members of the BIM team. The magazine also established a sense of self-deprecating humor, as evidenced by a cover that prominently called Brown "Chris, the scared mortician".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2005, BIM began using a web-based system that allowed individuals to observe and, in theory, participate in live investigations. This system is a simple chat client that also displays still captures from various video cameras connected on location. BIM also webcasts live audio from the site and displays real-time temperature data for online participants to monitor. BIM refers to an online participant as a "Virtual Paranormal Investigator", or "VPI".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2006, BIM conducted its first investigation of the RMS Queen Mary, with the aim of documenting and refuting some of the claims made on the Sci Fi Channel series *Ghost Hunters*. Following this investigation, the Queen Mary granted BIM unprecedented access to parts of the ship not normally available for such groups, and allowed BIM to conduct paranormal investigations on a regular basis. Since then, the ship and BIM have produced the paranormal exhibition called *Ghost Fest Expo*. In 2008, BIM hosted weekly paranormal investigations of the ship, led by Wheelock, where guests could pay to participate in the investigations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Pat & Brian Show* is a weekly webcast talk show featuring Patrick Wheelock and Brian Patton. Their show blends irreverent insult comedy, paranormal news from around the world, listener phone calls, and interviews with guests that' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Beyond Investigation Magazine* (BIM) is an American publication dedicated to the exploration of paranormal and conspiracy theory claims. The entity behind the magazine, Beyond Investigation, was established by Patrick Wheelock in 2004 with the express purpose of investigating allegations of paranormal activity and disseminating the findings and related research in a periodical format. Owing to the high costs of printing a limited circulation magazine, BIM transitioned its distribution formats to web and DVD after its first print issue. The year 2005 marked the commencement of BIM''s webcasting of audio programming, most notably a weekly talk show titled “The Pat & Brian Show”.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'What distinguishes *Beyond Investigation Magazine* from many other paranormal investigative groups is its approach towards the paranormal. While the team has occasionally worked with psychics, they do not seek to cleanse or explain paranormal activity. Instead, they endeavor to objectively document and analyze the data they collect.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2006, Beyond Investigation was showcased in an episode of “Scariest Places on Earth,” where they undertook a paranormal investigation of the USS Hornet (CV-12), a World War II U.S. Navy aircraft carrier that has since been converted into a historical museum. Then, in 2009, Beyond Investigation was selected as the "employer" for Tiffany Pollard to try her hand as a "ghost hunter" on her VH1 reality television series “New York Goes to Work”.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Patrick Wheelock''s journey into paranormal investigation began in 1977, and he started conducting investigations with his friends, Steve Sonntag and Chris Brown, in 1994. In 2000, Wheelock created Beyond Investigation. It wasn''t until 2004 that the "Magazine" was appended to the name, when Wheelock felt a void in the market for consumer-oriented but scientific research on the paranormal. The inaugural edition of the magazine provided a recap of some investigations conducted by Wheelock, Sonntag, and Brown, introduced more recent members of the BIM team, and highlighted investigations carried out as a larger group. The magazine also seemed to establish a sense of self-deprecating humor, with a cover that playfully referred to Brown as "Chris, the scared mortician".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2005, BIM began utilizing a web-based system that allows individuals to observe and ostensibly participate in live investigations. This system, a simple chat client, also displays still captures from various video cameras connected on location. BIM also broadcasts live audio from the site and displays real-time temperature data for online participants to monitor. These online participants are referred to by BIM as "Virtual Paranormal Investigators," or "VPIs".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2006, BIM conducted its initial investigation of the RMS Queen Mary as an "impartial third party" to document and refute some of the claims made on the Sci Fi Channel series “Ghost Hunters”. Following BIM''s first investigation of the Queen Mary, the ship granted unprecedented access to parts of the ship typically off-limits to such groups, enabling BIM to conduct paranormal investigations on a regular basis. Since then, the ship and BIM have jointly produced the paranormal exhibition called “Ghost Fest Expo.” Starting in 2008, BIM began hosting weekly paranormal investigations of the ship, led by Pat Wheelock, where guests can pay to participate in the investigations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'“The Pat & Brian Show” is the weekly webcast talk show featuring Patrick Wheelock and Brian Patton. Their show blends irreverent insult comedy, paranormal news from around the world, listener phone calls, and' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# Beyond Investigation Magazine' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Beyond Investigation Magazine* (BIM) is an American publication primarily concerned with documenting and discussing investigations into paranormal and conspiracy theory claims. The magazine was launched as a vehicle to publish the results of investigations conducted by the group known as Beyond Investigation, which was established by Patrick Wheelock in 2004. The aim of the magazine was to address the lack of consumer-oriented but still scientific research on the paranormal.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the original intention was to publish BIM as a printed periodical, financial constraints related to producing a limited circulation print magazine led to a shift in the distribution format. After the first issue, which was distributed in print, BIM transitioned to web and DVD formats. In 2005, the magazine expanded its offerings to include webcast audio programming. This notably featured a weekly talk show called “The Pat & Brian Show.”' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The founding of *Beyond Investigation Magazine* followed a long history of paranormal investigations by its founder, Patrick Wheelock. Wheelock began his explorations into the paranormal in 1977 and started conducting investigations with his friends, Steve Sonntag and Chris Brown, in 1994. The first edition of the magazine recounted some of the investigations conducted by this original trio and introduced newer members of the BIM team along with the investigations conducted by the expanded group.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Beyond Investigation, and by extension BIM, distinguished itself from other paranormal investigative groups in its approach to paranormal activity. While they occasionally worked with psychics, the group made no attempt to purge or explain paranormal phenomena. Instead, they focused on objectively documenting and analyzing data.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its web and DVD content, BIM developed a web-based system in 2005 to allow individuals to observe and potentially participate in live investigations. This system, which consisted of a simple chat client and live camera feeds, also provided live audio from the site and real-time temperature data for online participants to monitor. These online participants were dubbed “Virtual Paranormal Investigators” or “VPIs.”' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Beyond Investigation and BIM gained notable attention for their investigations of the RMS Queen Mary. After their first investigation of the ship in 2006, the ship’s management granted the group unprecedented access to parts of the ship not normally available to such groups. This enabled BIM to conduct regular paranormal investigations on the ship. These investigations eventually evolved into a paranormal exhibition called the Ghost Fest Expo, which was jointly produced by the ship and BIM.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Ghost Fest Expo offered a wide range of seminars and guest speakers on various topics. It featured special tours and investigations of the ship and provided a showroom for the sale of paranormal products and services. Notable guest speakers at the expo have included personalities such as George Noory, Dr. Andrew Nichols, Jeff Belanger, Loyd Auerbach, among others.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s weekly webcast talk show, “The Pat & Brian Show,” features Patrick Wheelock and Brian Patton. Their show blends irreverent insult comedy, paranormal news from around the world, listener phone calls, and interviews with guests that have some connection, often tangential, to the paranormal. A recurring theme of the show is Brian''s lack of political correctness, which usually prompts a response from Pat. In 2009, “The Pat & Brian Show” was syndicated on the Haunted Voices Radio Network and rebroadcast on Sirius Satellite Radio.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'From its inception, *Beyond Investigation Magazine* has contributed significantly to the discourse on paranormal and conspiracy theory investigations, providing a platform for not only documenting these investigations but also for engaging the public in the ongoing dialogue about the unexplained and unknown.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Big Brother
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Big Brother', N'big-brother', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Skateboarding and counterculture magazine featuring irreverent content, humor, and interviews with alternative icons.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Big Brother* was a notable American magazine in the realm of skateboarding. It was conceived in 1992 by Steve Rocco and Rodney Mullen, co-owners of the World Industries skateboarding company. The publication was an unorthodox blend of skateboarding content, humor, and daring exploits, designed to appeal to its youthful and rebellious audience. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was a significant platform for many prominent personalities, including Jeff Tremaine, who would later helm the successful Jackass franchise. *Big Brother* became an integral part of the Jackass narrative, as it was through the magazine that Tremaine met Johnny Knoxville, a collaboration that eventually led to the creation of the *Jackass* television series and subsequent films. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was notable for its uninhibited content, often pushing boundaries and courting controversy. Its pages were filled with irreverent humor and audacious stunts, reflecting the adventurous spirit of skateboarding culture. The magazine was also known for its distinctive style of journalism, featuring interviews, editorials, and articles that were as much about the writers and their exploits as they were about skateboarding. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its influence on skateboarding culture and its role as a springboard for numerous careers, *Big Brother* faced criticism and controversy. Its freewheeling style and often explicit content drew scrutiny, and it experienced issues with censorship and distribution. Despite these challenges, the magazine continued to be a significant voice in skateboarding culture until its eventual demise in 2004.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The legacy of *Big Brother* extends beyond its printed pages. In 2016, a documentary titled “Dumb: The Story of Big Brother Magazine” was released, providing an in-depth look at the magazine’s history. The documentary featured interviews with many of the key figures involved with the magazine, offering a glimpse into the ethos and culture that defined *Big Brother*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Big Brother* has left an indelible mark on skateboarding culture. Through its unique blend of irreverent humor, daring stunts, and unfiltered commentary, it captured the spirit of a generation and left a lasting legacy that continues to influence today’s skateboarding scene.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Billboard Radio Monitor
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Billboard Radio Monitor', N'billboard-radio-monitor', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Music industry trade magazine providing information and analysis on radio airplay and music charts for artists, labels, and industry professionals.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Billboard Radio Monitor* was a weekly music trade publication. The magazine followed the radio industry and tracked the monitoring of current songs by format, station, and audience cumulations. It was a spinoff of the renowned *Billboard* magazine, catering primarily to those who work in the radio industry and music chart enthusiasts. The magazine was developed in Columbia, Maryland, indicating a strong tie to the music and radio industries present in the area.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Billboard Radio Monitor* was not just a magazine, but also a significant tool for those involved in the radio and music industries, serving as a comprehensive source of information and updates. The unique focus on monitoring current songs by format, station, and audience allowed industry professionals and enthusiasts to keep a pulse on the ever-evolving landscape of music and radio.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In its operational years, the magazine was mostly available through subscription, indicating its primary audience was professionals in the radio industry and those with a keen interest in music charts. Its in-depth coverage and weekly publication schedule provided timely information and insights, making it an invaluable resource for its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, all good things come to an end. *Billboard Radio Monitor* and *R&R* ceased publication as separate trades, with *Monitor* issuing its last edition on July 14, 2006, after 13 years of service. This marked the end of a significant chapter in the intersection of music and radio industries, leaving a lasting impact on its readers and the industry at large. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While *Billboard Radio Monitor* may no longer be in circulation, its legacy continues to resonate within the industry, serving as a testament to the dynamic relationship between music and radio.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Bird Talk
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Bird Talk', N'bird-talk', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Monthly publication providing information and advice on bird care, behavior, and health for pet owners and bird enthusiasts.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Bird Talk* was a bi-monthly publication intended for bird owners and enthusiasts, first published in 1982 by Thomas A. Bell. The magazine was initially released under Parrot Publications, Inc., with Dave Bonnot serving as the "Fledgling Editor" and Dianne Shannon as the "Fledgling Art Director". Despite experiencing early publishing difficulties, the magazine was offered to Fancy Publications, a small publishing company known for other animal-themed magazines like *Dog Fancy*, *Cat Fancy*, and *Horse Fancy*. Under Fancy Publications, *Bird Talk* underwent a design overhaul, and in April 1984, it was published with a renewed focus on providing bird care information to pet bird owners. This revamped issue introduced new columns such as "Watch the Birdie" and "Causes and Cures", with the motto "Dedicated To Better Care For Pet Birds". Laura Doering, the magazine''s long-standing editor since 1998, continued to helm the magazine through its various iterations.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the early 1990s, *Bird Talk* flourished with issues containing as many as 172 pages. However, over time, the magazine struggled, and by the late 2000s, issues were reduced to around 50 pages. In an effort to keep up with the digital age, *Bird Talk* launched a website, BirdChannel.com, in November 2006, which included features like interactive contests. One such contest, the "World''s First Bird Dance-Off", saw bird owners submitting videos of their birds dancing, with visitors voting on the "Top Bird Dancer".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its efforts to adapt, *Bird Talk* ceased its print publication abruptly with the September 2012 issue, to the disappointment of its loyal readership. Subscribers were directed to the magazine''s related site, BirdChannel.com, as the sole source of the publication''s information. However, the cessation of the print version was not well-received by all, with some subscribers voicing discontent at the publisher''s decision to send them copies of *Dog Fancy* in lieu of *Bird Talk*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In early 2018, Parrot Publications, Inc. purchased the trademark for *Bird Talk* with plans to revive the magazine. The company was successful in publishing new issues, with the latest issue released in May 2018. Unfortunately, no new issues were released after the January 2019 edition, and the magazine appears to have ceased operations entirely. As of now, the subscription page is inactive, and there have been no responses to email or Facebook posts, leading to the belief that the magazine is no longer in business.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Birding Business
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Birding Business', N'birding-business', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Trade publication catering to birding industry professionals, featuring news, advice, and analysis on birdwatching trends and products.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Birding Business* was a free business publication that served as the trade news source for the wild bird and nature products industry. Based in O''Lakes, Florida, the magazine was published five times each year by Longdown Management, Inc. The inaugural issue of *Birding Business* was released in 1995. The publication provided industry-related updates and insights for 20 years, with its final issue being published in September 2015.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Black Film Review
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Black Film Review', N'black-film-review', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription African-American film magazine exploring contemporary and classic movies, with reviews, interviews, and insightful commentary.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Black Film Review* was an international magazine, dedicated to focusing on films and filmmakers from the African Diaspora. Its emphasis was largely on independent cinema. The publication was headquartered in Washington D.C., United States. The magazine made its debut in 1984 and continued to be published until 1995.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The foundation of *Black Film Review* was laid by David Nicholson in 1984. The inaugural issue of the magazine was an undated, one-page newsletter that Nicholson created on his PC, photocopied, and circulated among his friends. The magazine was initially published by Sojourner Productions on a quarterly basis. After the first three issues, which included a 24-page issue with the magazine''s earliest coverage of the Festival of Pan African Cinema Ouagadougou (FESPACO), an interview with Hollywood star Denzel Washington, and poetry by Amiri Baraka, a significant development took place. In 1985, Nicholson entered into a co-publishing agreement with Anthony Gittens, who was the director of the Black Film Institute of the University of the District of Columbia. With the help of funding from the National Endowment for the Arts, the magazine was revamped and published in a new format—printed on glossy paper and including photographs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1986, Nicholson joined the editorial team of The Washington Post Book World as an editor and book reviewer. However, he continued to maintain his role as the editor and publisher of *Black Film Review* for another year before handing over the responsibility to Jacquie Jones. Under the stewardship of Jones, the publication broadened its coverage of Panafrican film and filmmakers, and earned significant acclaim. It was used as a text at numerous film schools in the United States and abroad. Notable contributors to the publication included eminent film scholars such as Donald Bogle, Phyllis Klotman, Pat Aufderheide, Manthia Diawara, and Clyde Taylor.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its last two years in publication, *Black Film Review* was co-published by Eric Easter and edited by historian Leasa Farrar Frazer. The magazine left a lasting legacy in its exploration and coverage of independent cinema and filmmakers from the African Diaspora, serving as a significant resource for students, scholars, and film enthusiasts alike.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Black Flame
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Black Flame', N'the-black-flame', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine of the occult and Left-Hand Path philosophy, featuring articles delving into mystical practices and alternative spiritualities.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Black Flame* was a periodical known for its association with the Church of Satan. Published for nearly a decade, this magazine served as a platform for discourse on Satanic philosophy and practice. However, the comprehensive details about its inception, key contributors, and the reasons behind its cessation are yet to be fully gathered.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Black Inches
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Black Inches', N'black-inches', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription US-based monthly gay magazine based in New York City}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'# *Black Inches*{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Black Inches* was a US-based monthly gay pornographic magazine that featured African-American men. The magazine was established in 1993 by publisher Tony DeStefano under the company Mavety Media Group Ltd., based in New York City. The final issue of *Black Inches* was published in 2009, making its run approximately 16 years long. The magazine was published in English and had the ISSN number 1084-2462.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s content was sourced from various places. Some images were obtained from companies that produce gay pornographic films, although most layouts depicted individual men rather than simulated action scenes. Notable photographers whose work appeared in *Black Inches* include Anneli Adolfsson, Ken Kavanagh, Brian Lantelme, and Abednego, who was formerly associated with Mansurf.com. The magazine also carried film reviews, erotic stories, cartoons, and advertisements.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The influence of *Black Inches* extended beyond its pages, playing a significant role in gay culture. It was mentioned in various novels, including D. J. Murphy''s *Sons Like Me*, where it was referenced in the very first lines, as well as John Weir''s *What I Did Wrong* and Jim Norton''s *Happy Ending*. *Black Inches* also played a pivotal role in the careers of many gay black porn stars. It featured every major figure in the field in photo shoots and interviews, from Bobby Blake and Tyson Cane to Tiger Tyson, J. C. Carter, and T-Malone. For example, Bobby Blake spoke of his relationship with the magazine, stating, “*Black Inches* was always very supportive of me. They reviewed every film I made, did photo-shoots, interviewed me, and gave me my own column.”' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In popular culture, *Black Inches* was also referenced in various forms of media. In the webcomic *Homestuck*, the character Clubs Deuce carries a copy of the magazine, humorously reimagined as being about licorice rather than human pornography. In the adventure game *Problem Sleuth*, the character Pickle Inspector finds a copy of *Black Inches* on a table alongside a fictional gay pornographic magazine called *Hunk Rump*.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Black Market Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Black Market Magazine', N'black-market-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Urban culture magazine covering art, fashion, music, and lifestyle, with a focus on underground and emerging trends and talent.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Black Market Magazine* was a music, film, art, and comic zine that existed from 1984 to 1996, based in San Diego. Initially, the publication predominantly featured reviews and interviews of punk rock and other alternative bands such as Samhain, The Cramps, D.O.A., Tex and the Horseheads, G.B.H., New Order, Christian Death, Bad Religion, Ramones, Murphy''s Law, Butthole Surfers, Wasted Youth, Danzig, Marilyn Manson, among others. However, over its 13-issue and 10-year lifespan, film and art began to fill the majority of its pages. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s scope broadened to include interviews with figures such as sci-fi film historian and former editor of *Famous Monsters of Filmland*, Forrest J. Ackerman, as well as actors and directors such as Bill Paxton, Adam Rifkin, Wayne Newton, and Jeffrey Levy. Each issue showcased work by artists including R.K. Sloane, Jeff Gaither, Pizz, Lee Ellingson, Drew Elliot, Roman Dirge (creator of *Lenore Comix*), GUF, Peter Bagge (creator of *Hate Comix*), Michael Gilbert (creator of *Mr. Monster*), and many others. *Black Market Magazine* was edited and published by Carl Schneider of Black Market Productions.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Black Sports
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Black Sports', N'black-sports', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Specialized publication covering African American athletes, teams, and sports culture, with news, interviews, and historical features.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Black Sports* was an American monthly sports magazine that was first launched in April 1971 in New York City. The publication held the distinction of being the first major sports magazine that specifically targeted African Americans. Allan P. Barron, who conceived the idea for the magazine, served as its president and editor. He collaborated with William L. Doneghy, who assumed the roles of vice-president and controller. In its initial year, the role of editor was taken up by Bryant Gumbel, who departed from the magazine the following year.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s debut issue, *Black Sports Magazine, Vol. 1 No. 1*, prominently featured Oscar Robertson and Lew Alcindor (later known as Kareem Abdul-Jabbar), who were both donning Milwaukee Bucks jerseys on the cover. The cover was set against a white background and included text in red and black ink. The text contained headlines and teases of articles inside the issue such as "Oscar and Lew / NBA''s Winning Buck$ / Matt Snell''s / Recovery Toss-up / Mississippi Sports / Revolution / Willye White''s / Fifth Team / NFL''s Buddy Young / Rappin'' with John Carlos & Willie Davis / SPECIAL: Johnny Sample''s Confessions of a Dirty Ballplayer / EXCLUSIVE: Ron Johnson''s Own Story." The issue ran for 64 pages and was populated with numerous photographs and illustrations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its unique position in the market, *Black Sports* struggled to achieve a high circulation and was only moderately successful. The final issue of the magazine was published in June 1978, marking the end of its seven-year run. The publication is remembered for its pioneering role in creating a platform for sports journalism dedicated to African American athletes and audiences.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Sneaker Freaker
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Sneaker Freaker', N'sneaker-freaker', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine focused on providing fans of sneaker culture with news, reviews and features on both new and classic designs.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Sneaker Freaker* is an independent magazine and website that meticulously covers sneakers, streetwear, and sneaker culture on a global scale. Established in Melbourne, the magazine has grown to have a truly international reach, with its content available both in print and online. The magazine was launched in October 2002, originally conceived as a means for its founder and editor, Simon ‘Woody’ Wood, to acquire free shoes. It is sold in over 40 countries and maintains offices in Melbourne, London, and Berlin. It has grown from its humble roots as a DIY-style fanzine to a renowned international footwear magazine, documenting every collaboration, custom, limited edition, retro reissue, Quickstrike, Hyperstrike, and Tier Zero sneaker released over the past decade and a half.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Sneaker Freaker* has been successful in publishing its 40th issue in 2018. The same year, it produced *The Ultimate Sneaker Book* in collaboration with Taschen. This comprehensive 700-page anthology serves as a collection of *Sneaker Freaker* magazine’s content, detailing the last 100 years of collaborations, key releases, and significant events that have influenced the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its regular publishing, *Sneaker Freaker* has worked in collaboration with a number of popular brands. These collaborative endeavors have resulted in the creation of books with renowned names such as Nike, Globe, Adidas, New Balance, Reebok, G-SHOCK, PONY, and Puma. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s contribution to the sneaker culture extends beyond the realm of print. *Sneaker Freaker* has been involved in numerous collaborations over the years, creating unique, limited-edition products. The following list details a selection of these collaborations:' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2006: *Sneaker Freaker* x Lacoste Missouri 85 ''Minty Fresh''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2007: *Sneaker Freaker* x Nike x Medicom ''Bearbrick''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2008: *Sneaker Freaker* x PUMA Blaze of Glory ''Great White'' and ''Black Beast''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2009: *Sneaker Freaker* x AIAIAI Earbuds' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2010: *Sneaker Freaker* x PUMA R698 ''Geography Teacher''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2012: *Sneaker Freaker* x Supra Skytop III ''Goldenballs and Blueballs''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2013: *Sneaker Freaker* x adidas Torsion Integral' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2014: *Sneaker Freaker* x ASICS GEL-Kayano ''Melvin, Son of Alvin''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2015: *Sneaker Freaker* x G-SHOCK DW-6900SF-1D ''NIGHTOWL''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2016: *Sneaker Freaker* x New Balance 997.5 ''Tassie Tiger''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- 2017: *Sneaker Freaker* x pinqponq' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Sneaker Freaker''s* story is one of passion, ingenuity, and a keen eye for style. The publication’s commitment to the sneaker community, as well as the dedication of its staff and contributors, has allowed it to consistently deliver in-depth content that is both informative and visually compelling. As it continues to evolve and expand, *Sneaker Freaker* remains a vital resource and an influential voice in global sneaker culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Desert Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Desert Magazine', N'desert-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Magazine capturing the beauty and mystery of the desert with articles on culture, history, ecology, geology, and tourist destinations.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Desert Magazine** was a distinguished monthly periodical, which was primarily based in the Colorado Desert, within the charming Coachella Valley town of Palm Desert near Palm Springs, California. The inaugural issue graced the public in 1937 under the meticulous stewardship of its founder, editor, and publisher, Randall Henderson. His tenure at the helm spanned until 1958, after which a succession of new editors took the reins until the magazine ceased print publication in 1985.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With a discerning focus on the arid regions of the Southwestern United States and Northwestern Mexico, *Desert Magazine* delved into an eclectic array of desert-related subjects. It was an illustrious medium for the exploration and celebration of the desert’s multifaceted offerings. Regional travel and exploration were prominently featured, guiding readers through the vast landscapes, elucidating the natural wonders, and inspiring adventures in these often underappreciated regions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Additionally, *Desert Magazine* was a bastion for the arts, featuring exquisite visual artistry including paintings, drawings, and photographs that captured the essence of the desert''s ethereal beauty. Through its pages, the magazine became an advocate for the art community, showcasing both established and burgeoning talents.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Prose and literature found a venerable home within *Desert Magazine*. The written word breathed life into the stories of the desert, with pieces ranging from fiction to historical essays. The magazine''s literary section was a tribute to the oral traditions and storytelling that are so deeply ingrained in desert cultures.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another facet of the magazine was its examination of the cultural history of the desert regions. Through detailed articles and captivating storytelling, *Desert Magazine* chronicled the rich tapestry of histories, traditions, and peoples that have shaped the desert through the ages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In its nearly five-decade run, *Desert Magazine* was more than a periodical; it was a tribute to the complexity and richness of desert life. Through its dedication to exploration, art, literature, and cultural history, it painted a comprehensive and enduring portrait of the desert’s allure and mystique, and in doing so, secured its place as an invaluable resource and treasure in American periodical history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Blueboy
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Blueboy', N'blueboy', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American gay magazine that was pioneering in the representation of the gay community and helping to create gay culture in the late 20th century.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Blueboy* was a men’s lifestyle magazine that made its debut in 1974. Originally, it was a small black and white journal before being purchased and rebranded by Donald N. Embinder, a former advertising manager for the arts magazine *After Dark*. Embinder transformed *Blueboy* into “The National Magazine About Men”, a tagline that the magazine maintained for decades. The inaugural cover of *Blueboy* was a playful parody of the painting "Blue Boy" by the 18th-century master, Thomas Gainsborough.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Blueboy* swiftly rose to prominence as a men''s monthly magazine, catering particularly to the LGBTQ community. It boasted a glossy finish and featured some of the LGBTQ community’s most prestigious writers and artists. The magazine was inspired by "Blue Boy", a character that had become an unlikely gay icon in the 1970s after being mocked as effeminate by *MAD Magazine* and *Dennis the Menace*. The debut issue of *Blueboy* featured a model dressed as "Blue Boy" without breeches, with his plumed hat strategically placed between his legs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Blueboy* holds the distinction of being the first nationally distributed gay men’s magazine in the United States and was also available internationally in countries such as France, Australia, England, and Spain. It was published for 33 years, making it one of the most prolific gay magazines. The magazine continued publishing until December 2007 and advertised products and services, often employing “Blue Boy” as a recurrent symbol. Throughout its tenure, *Blueboy* was celebrated for its contributions to the LGBTQ community, and its artful and provocative content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With its rich history, *Blueboy* remains an iconic publication, emblematic of a significant era in LGBTQ culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Bluff
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Bluff', N'bluff', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine devoted to poker, covering the latest news, interviews, and strategy, as well as live event coverage and rankings of the game''s top players.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Bluff* was a distinguished American periodical dedicated to the game of poker. The magazine was an exemplar in its domain, and its illustrious journey began as a bimonthly publication in October 2004. In less than a year, the magazine evolved into a monthly publication by August 2005. With its pages adorned by the captivating world of poker, *Bluff* became an integral part of the poker enthusiast’s collection, ultimately reaching an impressive circulation of 250,000 copies nationwide. Of these, 191,000 copies graced newsstands, while the remainder was disseminated through events, select locations, and subscriptions. The magazine achieved the status of being America’s largest poker magazine, catering to an audience eager to keep abreast with the dynamic and thrilling poker lifestyle.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of *Bluff*’s noteworthy accomplishments was the acquisition of thepokerdb.com, an online tournament database, in December 2006. This acquisition expanded *Bluff*’s foray into the digital realm. The magazine, in its pages, annually bestowed honors upon the influential figures in the poker industry through its “Poker Power 20”, highlighting the 20 most eminent personalities.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Bluff*’s success was not confined to the United States; it transcended borders with separate editions being published for Europe, Latin America, South Africa, and Australasia. In particular, the Southern African edition, known as *Bluff Magazine South Africa*, was published by Maverick Publishing Corp. on a monthly basis and focused predominantly on the poker industry in Southern Africa. *Bluff* continued to be a treasure trove of information and entertainment for poker aficionados until its production was regrettably ceased in February 2015.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2012, *Bluff* Media was acquired by Churchill Downs, a signifier of the magazine’s significance in the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though no longer in production, *Bluff* magazine remains an iconic name in the world of poker, its pages having been a testament to the game’s rich history, influential personalities, and the unwavering excitement that is synonymous with poker.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Blunt
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Blunt', N'blunt', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine catering to snowboard enthusiasts, providing coverage and reviews of the latest gear, tips on improving skills, and insights from top-level riders.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Blunt* was an American publication that galvanized the snowboarding community during the 1990s. The magazine was brought into existence in the year 1993 under the aegis of Ken Block, who is renowned as the founder. The initial publishing of *Blunt Snowboard Magazine* was carried out by DC Shoes, and it predominantly featured advertisements tailored for burgeoning, small, and independent companies. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As a publication devoted to snowboarding, *Blunt Snowboard Magazine* played a significant role in the snowboarding culture of the 1990s. The magazine’s emphasis on nascent companies and independent ventures demonstrated a commitment to fostering innovation and creativity within the snowboarding industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Unfortunately, as of the time of my last knowledge update in September 2021, *Blunt Snowboard Magazine* is no longer in publication. It holds a place in the annals of snowboarding history as an early pioneer in snowboarding media, capturing the essence and evolution of the sport during a time of rapid growth and transformation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Blunt Snowboard Magazine*’s legacy as an early chronicler and promoter of snowboarding culture continues to be celebrated by enthusiasts and historians of the sport.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- BNET
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'BNET', N'bnet', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Online magazine that enlightened the business world from 2007 to 2012.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*__BNET__* was an august online periodical, adroitly dedicated to the intricate realm of business management. Established in the year 2007, it held its esteemed headquarters in the vibrant city of San Francisco, California, in the United States. *BNET* was enveloped within the corporate umbrella of CBS Interactive and shared its prestigious lineage with other notable entities such as ZDNet, TechRepublic, and SmartPlanet.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The sagacious Editor-in-Chief of *BNET* was Eric Schurenberg, whose stewardship guided the magazine in its quest to illuminate the multifarious aspects of business management.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*BNET* carved a niche for itself in the digital realm by proffering an eclectic array of e-newsletters, whitepapers, and an engaging platform for discourse through comments. The esteemed readership could register on the *BNET* site and partake in the abundant resources it offered.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s unyielding dedication to quality and insight was acknowledged when it ascended to be one of the top 10 financial news and research sites on the Internet from May 2007 to May 2008, as per the esteemed comScore’s rankings.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The illustrious journey of *BNET* reached its culmination in the year 2012, when it gracefully merged into CBS MoneyWatch.com, leaving behind an indelible mark in the annals of business journalism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*BNET* served not only the United States but extended its erudite outreach globally, enlightening minds and shaping perspectives in the business world.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Boardgamer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Boardgamer', N'the-boardgamer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine for board game enthusiasts, providing reviews, strategy tips, and news on the latest games and events in the industry.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Boardgamer* was an American magazine that emerged in the milieu of the board gaming community as an exquisite purveyor of content and insights pertaining to the realm of board games. It was founded by Bruce Monnin in the wake of Avalon Hill’s acquisition by Hasbro, which left many enthusiasts uncertain about the future of Avalon Hill''s beloved board games. The magazine''s inception took place in 1996 and it continued to grace the shelves of board game aficionados until 2004.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A distinguishing aspect of *The Boardgamer* was its quarterly publication schedule. It primarily focused on Avalon Hill and Victory Games titles, but did not limit itself solely to these. It also encompassed a broader perspective on the diverse and ever-evolving world of board gaming.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A noteworthy characteristic of *The Boardgamer* was its divergence in content from Avalon Hill''s house magazine, *The General*. While *The General* was more focused on new releases, *The Boardgamer* carved its niche by devoting ample coverage to classic Avalon Hill games that were no longer featured in *The General*. This distinguished *The Boardgamer* as a publication dedicated to the preservation and celebration of the rich heritage and history of board games.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Thus, through its pages, *The Boardgamer* served as both a sentinel and a torchbearer, preserving the legacy of past classics and illuminating the multifaceted world of board gaming for a community whose passion for this pastime is both fervent and enduring.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Body Play
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Body Play', N'body-play', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine that celebrates athletic bodies and the stories of the athletes behind them, featuring captivating photography and exclusive features.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Body Play* is an avant-garde publication that focuses on body modification and its associated subcultures. The magazine’s inception dates back to the early 1990s, and its pages have been graced by a plethora of articles, interviews, and images exploring the myriad ways in which individuals manipulate and modify their physical forms.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The term “body play” is an umbrella phrase that encompasses a wide array of practices including tattooing, piercing, scarification, and branding. *Body Play* magazine, being a torchbearer of this culture, provides an intimate insight into the minds and motivations of those who choose to engage in these practices. The content within its pages, often raw and unfiltered, examines not only the aesthetic aspects of body modification but also delves into the spiritual, psychological, and sociological dimensions that underlie these expressions of individuality.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the signature elements of *Body Play* is its evocative imagery. The photographs and illustrations that adorn its pages are often both provocative and poignant, capturing the essence of the transformative experience that is central to the culture of body modification. Through these images, the magazine transcends the barriers of language and culture, speaking to a universal human impulse to create meaning through the alteration of physical form.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A noteworthy facet of *Body Play* is its unflinching commitment to giving voice to the individuals and communities engaged in body modification. Through in-depth interviews and first-person accounts, the magazine humanizes a subculture that is often marginalized or misunderstood by mainstream society. It sheds light on the personal journeys of self-discovery and empowerment that are inextricably linked to the process of modifying one’s body.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In an era where digital media increasingly eclipse traditional print publications, *Body Play* stands as a testament to the enduring power of the printed page. Through its rich tapestry of words and images, it fosters a sense of community among its readers, many of whom see in its content reflections of their own experiences and aspirations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As a chronicle of a subculture that is as diverse as it is vibrant, *Body Play* occupies a unique niche in the annals of publishing. It is more than a magazine; it is a celebration of the boundless capacity of the human spirit to reinvent itself through the canvas of the body.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Boing Boing
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Boing Boing', N'boing-boing', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A weblog founded in 1988 that features tech, science, art, and culture news with a focus on the unusual and bizarre.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Boing Boing* commenced its journey as a zine in 1988, initially titled *bOING bOING*. It was the brainchild of Mark Frauenfelder and his wife Carla Sinclair, who began the publication on paper. The magazine was subtitled “The World’s Greatest Neurozine”. In the initial days, the publication primarily focused on cyberculture and was influential in the development of cyberpunk. It garnered a reputation for its eclectic content which was at times quirky and cerebral, and its associate editors included Gareth Branwyn, Jon Lebkowsky, Paco Nathan, and David Pescovitz.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As the digital era beckoned, *Boing Boing* embraced the change and transitioned into a website in 1995. Eventually, in the year 2000, it was relaunched as a group blog, going by *Boing Boing*, and it described itself as “a directory of wonderful things”. The platform''s content evolved to encompass a broader range of topics including technology, futurism, science fiction, gadgets, intellectual property, Disney, and left-wing politics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Boing Boing* has been acknowledged for its contribution to the digital landscape, earning accolades such as the Bloggies for Weblog of the Year in 2004 and 2005. Today, it continues to thrive as a website and is renowned for its diverse and engaging content.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Boink
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Boink', N'boink', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Daring college magazine launched in 2005 that explored human sexuality through candid articles and real student models.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Boink* was a magazine created by a group of undergraduates at Boston University. The first issue made its debut in February 2005. *Boink* exclusively featured articles and photographs related to sexuality, and it distinguished itself by using real college students as models in its pictorials. The magazine was a quarterly publication, with an aim to strike a balance between artistic aesthetics and candid exploration of human sexuality. The founders of the magazine, Alecia Oleyourryk and Christopher Anderson, strived to create a publication that was both visually stimulating and intellectually engaging.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s content was a medley of provocative photos, fiction, advice columns, and profiles of college students, with a particular focus on candid discussions about various aspects of sexuality. The choice to use real college students as models gave the magazine an authentic feel and resonated with its primary target audience — college students and young adults. The magazine''s tagline, “For the inner student in all of us,” reflected its mission to connect with the youthful and inquisitive nature of its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the seminal pieces in *Boink* was an article by a Boston University student who shared her experience working in the adult film industry. This piece exemplified the magazine’s ethos of open dialogue and exploration. Other features included interviews with authors and experts in the field of human sexuality, as well as personal essays and fiction that delved into themes of desire, love, and relationships.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though predominantly a print publication, *Boink* did make several of its issues available online. The magazine also produced a book titled “Boink: College Sex by the People Having It,” which was a compilation of the best content from its initial issues. This book was published in 2008 and provided a broader audience with insight into the provocative and candid nature of the magazine’s content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In its time, *Boink* garnered attention from a myriad of media outlets. The frankness with which it approached topics of sexuality, combined with its unique aesthetic choices, made it a noteworthy addition to the landscape of college and lifestyle publications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As of the late 2000s, *Boink* ceased publication. Its legacy, however, persists as a daring and innovative endeavor that pushed the boundaries of what a college magazine could be. It serves as an exemplar of student-driven media that was unafraid to tackle taboo subjects with both earnestness and artistry.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Bomb Rack
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Bomb Rack', N'bomb-rack', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Mid-20th century periodical that celebrated aviation history, technology, and the human stories behind flight.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Bomb Rack_ was a periodical publication that epitomized the quintessence of aviation ephemera. It was conceived in the mid-20th century as a tribute to the aviation marvels and the men and women who contributed to their creation and operation. The magazine, with its meticulously curated content, explored the boundless skies through the lens of history, technology, and human endeavor.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The earliest issues of _Bomb Rack_ were predominantly in black and white, a testament to the technological constraints of the time. As the pages were turned, the readers were transported into an enthralling world of aircraft, where tales of valor intertwined with technical schematics and historic photographs. From the majestic flights of early biplanes to the supersonic marvels of the jet age, _Bomb Rack_ chronicled the relentless pursuit of conquering the skies.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Bomb Rack_ was recognized for its acute attention to detail. The editors and contributors, many of whom were veterans or aviation enthusiasts, painted a vivid tapestry of aviation history. The magazine not only explored the triumphs but also delved into the tragedies and sacrifices. The articles were frequently adorned with first-hand accounts, interviews, and memoirs, which added a personal dimension to the stories.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As the decades passed, _Bomb Rack_ embraced color printing, which further elevated the visual appeal of the magazine. The photographs of aircraft soaring through azure skies or resting on tarmacs, now in vibrant hues, were no less than works of art. The magazine also expanded its repertoire to include articles on model aircraft, a nod to the hobbyists and collectors who formed a significant part of its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to aviation, _Bomb Rack_ often featured articles on related fields such as aerospace, defense, and navigation. This holistic approach to content creation ensured that the magazine catered to a wide audience, ranging from professionals in the aviation sector to history buffs and hobbyists.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the crowning glories of _Bomb Rack_ was its cover art. Each issue’s cover was meticulously designed, often featuring a captivating illustration or photograph of an aircraft, accompanied by a tantalizing headline that beckoned the reader to explore the pages within. The cover art was often a labor of love for the artists, many of whom were accomplished illustrators and photographers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In conclusion, _Bomb Rack_ was a beacon for those enchanted by the marvels of aviation. Through its pages, it immortalized the triumphs, tragedies, and sheer audacity of those who dared to reach for the skies. Though it may have been bound by the physical confines of paper and ink, its spirit soared unfettered, much like the aircraft it so lovingly chronicled.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Books & Culture
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Books & Culture', N'books-and-culture', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine offering insightful commentary on literature, the arts, and contemporary thought from a Christian perspective.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Books & Culture* was a bimonthly American publication that was an eminent voice in the world of literature and intellectual engagement. Founded in 1995 by John Wilson, who remained as editor until the magazine''s cessation, *Books & Culture* was an affiliate of *Christianity Today*. The magazine''s mission was to engage in erudite discourse and provide discerning criticism of literature and culture through the lens of Christian thought.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In its nascent stage, *Books & Culture* was a refuge for literary and intellectual Christians who longed for a publication that transcended denominational boundaries and grappled with broader cultural and societal themes. The magazine carved a niche for itself as a unique platform for Christian scholars, writers, and readers to discuss literature, history, art, and current affairs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The bimonthly issues of *Books & Culture* were replete with reviews of books from an array of genres, essays on historical and contemporary issues, poetry, and visual arts. It ardently endeavored to foster an understanding of the interplay between Christian thought and culture. The articles, penned by eminent scholars and critics, were characterized by rigorous analysis, eloquence, and incisive wit.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its association with *Christianity Today*, *Books & Culture* prided itself on editorial independence. It assiduously avoided dogmatism and eschewed partisan politics. The ethos of the publication was an amalgamation of intellectual curiosity, cultural engagement, and Christian faith. It was a beacon for those who sought to navigate the confluence of faith and intellect without relinquishing either.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its lifespan, *Books & Culture* garnered accolades and was held in high regard by both Christian and secular readerships. It was lauded for its incisive criticism, intellectual depth, and commitment to ecumenical dialogue.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The announcement of *Books & Culture*’s termination was made in 2016, citing financial difficulties. Its lamented departure left an intellectual void in Christian literary circles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In summary, *Books & Culture* was not merely a magazine; it was an intellectual odyssey that epitomized the confluence of faith, literature, and culture. Its pages were suffused with erudition, insight, and a fervent quest for understanding. The legacy of *Books & Culture* continues to resonate with all who cherish the pursuit of knowledge and the enrichment of the human spirit.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Bop
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Bop', N'bop', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A teen entertainment magazine covering music, TV, movies, and celebrities with exclusive interviews and behind-the-scenes content.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Bop_ was an American teen magazine that enjoyed prominence from the early 1980s through the early 2000s. The magazine made its debut in 1983, and was founded by Laufer Media. It originally surfaced as a bi-monthly publication and later transitioned to a monthly format. The magazine’s headquarters were located in Los Angeles, California. _Bop_ primarily catered to teenage girls, with its content focusing on music, television, and film celebrities.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A quintessential piece of teenage pop culture, _Bop_ was heralded for its lush, vivid posters of popular celebrities, which were a mainstay in many a teenager’s bedroom. The magazine''s content predominantly consisted of interviews, quizzes, and articles about the latest trends in fashion, beauty, and entertainment. The pages of _Bop_ often featured heartthrobs and popular bands of the time, making it a beloved source of celebrity gossip and entertainment news.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the distinguishing features of _Bop_ was its friendly and conversational tone. The magazine’s editors and writers adeptly captured the youthful exuberance and vernacular of its target audience. This, coupled with the magazine’s keen eye on the pulse of popular culture, contributed to its widespread appeal among teenagers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'_Bop_’s readership also had the opportunity to engage with the magazine through reader polls and contests. These interactive elements fostered a sense of community and involvement among its audience, allowing them to feel connected to the glamorous world of celebrities.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As the landscape of media consumption evolved in the 21st century, the popularity of print magazines began to wane. This shift in consumer behavior, coupled with the rise of the internet and social media, presented challenges for traditional print publications like _Bop_. In response, the magazine increased its online presence, but this shift was not enough to counter the changing tides.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ultimately, _Bop_ ceased publication in 2014, leaving behind a legacy as one of the most iconic teen magazines of its time. It remains a nostalgic piece of memorabilia for those who grew up during its heyday, symbolizing an era where print media played a significant role in shaping the tastes and interests of young pop culture enthusiasts.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Boston (1783–1786)
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Boston (1783–1786)', N'boston-1783-1786', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly publication featuring articles and reviews about local news, politics, arts, culture, and lifestyle topics in Boston, Massachusetts.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Boston Magazine* (1783–1786) was a distinguished periodical, a harbinger of American literary culture during its nascent years. Launched in 1783, the inception of *Boston Magazine* coincided with the end of the Revolutionary War, a period pregnant with the hope of building a new nation.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'This magazine’s pages were graced with an assemblage of essays, poems, and engravings that illuminated the intellectual discourse of the time. The readership found solace and enlightenment in the periodical’s riveting content, which elucidated an array of subjects ranging from politics and philosophy to science and the arts. The prose was imbued with a sense of gravitas, reflecting the sentiments and aspirations of a people rebuilding their land from the ashes of war.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The literary offerings of *Boston Magazine* were penned by an eclectic cadre of contributors. Amongst them, Phillis Wheatley, the first published African-American female poet, is perhaps the most illustrious. Her verses were a testament to the power of the human spirit, and her presence within the pages of *Boston Magazine* attested to the periodical’s commitment to inclusivity and diversity.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Boston Magazine* was an exemplar of an 18th-century American periodical, characterized by its fervent dedication to intellectualism and literary refinement. The engravings and illustrations that adorned its pages were evocative and thought-provoking, offering visual narratives that complemented the textual content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the hallmarks of *Boston Magazine* was its editorial sagacity. The content was meticulously curated to foster a sense of intellectual camaraderie among its readers. It was a vessel through which individuals could partake in the collective journey of nation-building, not just through political means but through the cultivation of a shared cultural and intellectual heritage.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1786, the illustrious journey of *Boston Magazine* met its denouement. Though its life was ephemeral, its impact was indelible. It occupies an exalted place in the annals of American literary history, not only as a chronicle of its time but as a standard-bearer for the ideals that would shape a fledgling nation. *Boston Magazine* was a tribute to the potency of the written word, and to the indomitable spirit of a people in pursuit of enlightenment and progress.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Boston Monthly Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Boston Monthly Magazine', N'boston-monthly-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Delve into Boston Monthly Magazine, an 1825-1826 periodical showcasing literary talent and cultural commentary in early 19th-century Boston.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Boston Monthly Magazine* was a renowned publication that played an instrumental role in the literary and cultural milieu of early 19th-century Boston. Commencing in 1825, this periodical distinguished itself as a beacon of erudition and cultural commentary.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The pages of *Boston Monthly Magazine* were adorned with a rich tapestry of content, encompassing essays, poetry, fiction, and astute observations on societal trends. These diverse literary offerings were delivered in a prose that was both eloquent and intellectually stimulating.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the notable aspects of *Boston Monthly Magazine* was its commitment to providing a platform for nascent authors. This periodical’s embrace of emerging literary talent cultivated a burgeoning literary community in Boston, and its patronage played a vital role in giving voice to authors who would later ascend to acclaim.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Not just a literary journal, *Boston Monthly Magazine* was also a repository for discerning critique and social commentary. Its pages offered a lens through which the readers could gaze upon the societal and cultural landscape of the time. The periodical’s dedication to the exploration of diverse perspectives rendered it a conduit for the exchange of ideas and intellectual discourse.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The visual aesthetics of *Boston Monthly Magazine* were commensurate with the richness of its content. The illustrations and engravings that festooned its pages were rendered with meticulous care, and they served as visual complements to the textual narratives.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As a periodical, *Boston Monthly Magazine* was not just a collection of pages bound together; it was a vessel through which the yearnings, aspirations, and reflections of an era were given form. Through its commitment to literary excellence and insightful commentary, it contributed to the intellectual and cultural fabric of early 19th-century Boston.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The sun set on *Boston Monthly Magazine* in 1826, but its legacy endures. As a compendium of literature and culture, it remains an invaluable artifact, a window into the soul of a city at a defining juncture in its history. Through its pages, the whispers of the past continue to reverberate, a testament to the timeless power of the written word.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Boston Rock
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Boston Rock', N'boston-rock', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A music publication that covers the Boston rock music scene. It features extensive interviews with local artists, reviews of their music and live shows, and more.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Boston Rock* magazine was an illustrious publication that served as the pulsating heartbeat of Boston’s vibrant rock music scene during the late 20th century. Inaugurated in 1980, *Boston Rock* was a harbinger of the burgeoning alternative and indie rock movements that would come to define the era.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The pages of *Boston Rock* were suffused with an eclectic array of content that captured the essence of the rock music scene. From incisive interviews with emerging and established bands to astute reviews of albums and live performances, *Boston Rock* was an indispensable guide for aficionados of the genre. The magazine’s prose was electric, mirroring the raw energy and spirit of the music it chronicled.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Beyond its coverage of music, *Boston Rock* also served as a forum for broader cultural discourse. The magazine’s features often delved into the sociopolitical undercurrents that informed the music of the time, reflecting the indelible link between art and the zeitgeist.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The aesthetic sensibilities of *Boston Rock* mirrored the rebellious spirit of rock music. The magazine’s design was characterized by bold visuals and striking typography, capturing the reader’s eye much as a power chord captures the ear. The illustrations and photographs that adorned its pages were evocative, offering visual tributes to the pantheon of rock.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'An important aspect of *Boston Rock* was its dedication to the local music scene. By shining a spotlight on Boston’s homegrown talent, it played a pivotal role in fostering a sense of community among musicians and fans alike. This commitment to local music was not only a testament to the magazine’s authenticity but also a reflection of its understanding that the roots of great art are often found in one’s own backyard.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As the years progressed, the landscape of music underwent a sea change, and with it, the pages of *Boston Rock* evolved. However, the magazine’s commitment to chronicling the rock music scene with passion and verve remained unwavering.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though *Boston Rock* ceased publication in the 1990s, its legacy is indelible. It remains a cherished artifact of a time when music was a revolution, and when the notes of a guitar could echo the cries of a generation. For those who lived through the era, and for those who wish to understand it, *Boston Rock* serves as a window into the soul of a musical movement.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Bowling Digest
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Bowling Digest', N'bowling-digest', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly magazine featuring in-depth coverage of bowling news, events, and techniques, as well as product reviews and interviews with top bowlers.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Bowling Digest* was a revered publication that served as an authoritative voice in the world of tenpin bowling for over four decades. Founded in 1969, *Bowling Digest* catered to both ardent enthusiasts and professionals within the sport, offering a compendium of insights, news, and features until its cessation in 2013.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The pages of *Bowling Digest* were graced with a plethora of content that encompassed various aspects of bowling. From profiles of eminent players and explorations of bowling techniques to in-depth analyses of tournaments and coverage of the latest equipment, the magazine was a treasure trove for aficionados of the sport.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the distinguishing facets of *Bowling Digest* was its commitment to journalistic excellence. The prose within its pages was incisive and illuminating, reflecting a dedication to thorough research and a deep understanding of the sport. The magazine’s contributors were often experts in the field, lending credibility and gravitas to the content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its textual offerings, *Bowling Digest* also included vivid photographs and illustrations that captured the spirit and dynamism of bowling. These visuals served not only as complements to the articles but also as standalone pieces that conveyed the emotion and excitement inherent in the sport.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As the sport of bowling evolved, so too did the content of *Bowling Digest*. The magazine keenly observed and documented the shifting trends and developments in the sport, and its pages became a historical record of bowling’s trajectory over the years.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Bowling Digest* also played a significant role in fostering a sense of community among bowling enthusiasts. Through its coverage of leagues and tournaments at various levels, it encouraged participation and engagement within the sport. Furthermore, its instructional pieces and equipment reviews were instrumental in aiding bowlers in honing their skills and making informed choices.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though *Bowling Digest* bade farewell in 2013, its legacy as a stalwart in the realm of bowling journalism endures. The magazine is remembered with fondness and respect by those who were privileged to turn its pages. It remains an exemplar of dedication to a sport and serves as a testament to the enduring allure of bowling. Through the pages of *Bowling Digest*, the echoes of pins falling and the cheers of triumphant bowlers continue to resound.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Bowling This Month
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Bowling This Month', N'bowling-this-month', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A comprehensive bowling magazine that covers all aspects of the sport, including technique, product reviews, tournament coverage, and interviews with top players.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Bowling This Month* is a distinguished publication that has served as a veritable fount of knowledge and insight for the bowling community since its inception in 1994. With its focus on tenpin bowling, the magazine caters to a wide audience, ranging from the amateur enthusiast to the seasoned professional.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The content of *Bowling This Month* is both varied and comprehensive, encompassing an array of topics that are integral to the sport. The magazine is renowned for its incisive analysis of bowling techniques, and its pages are often graced with meticulously detailed guides that aid bowlers in refining their skills.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to technique, *Bowling This Month* places a significant emphasis on equipment. The magazine’s reviews and insights into the latest bowling balls, shoes, and accessories are highly regarded within the community. Through its rigorous examination of equipment, the publication empowers its readership to make informed choices that can enhance their performance.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, *Bowling This Month* serves as a chronicle of the competitive bowling landscape. The magazine offers astute coverage of tournaments, profiling both established and emerging talents within the sport. Through its reportage, it brings the thrills and triumphs of the lanes to its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the defining characteristics of *Bowling This Month* is the caliber of its contributors. Many of the writers and analysts are esteemed figures in the world of bowling, and their expertise imbues the magazine’s content with authority and depth.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Beyond the technical and competitive aspects of the sport, *Bowling This Month* is also a conduit for the cultural elements of bowling. Through features and interviews, the magazine delves into the rich history and community that underpin bowling as both a sport and a pastime.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As an enduring publication, *Bowling This Month* has evolved alongside the sport it covers. Embracing the digital age, the magazine has expanded its presence online, making its wealth of content accessible to a global audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In sum, *Bowling This Month* is an indispensible resource for those who are drawn to the lanes. With its commitment to excellence and its comprehensive coverage of the multifaceted world of bowling, the magazine holds a revered place within the hearts of bowlers the world over.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Bradley, His Book
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Bradley, His Book', N'bradley-his-book', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A literary magazine that published poetry, essays, fiction, and other works by prominent British writers of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Bradley, His Book* is an esteemed periodical from the late 19th century that stands as a testament to the Art Nouveau movement and the burgeoning world of American graphic design. Launched in 1896, this quarterly publication was the brainchild of William H. Bradley, an American artist and designer who is often heralded as the “Dean of American Designers.” The magazine was published for a brief period until 1897, but its impact on the world of art and design has been lasting.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Bradley, His Book* showcased the prodigious talents of its creator. William H. Bradley’s work was heavily influenced by European Art Nouveau, and he was adept at integrating typography, illustration, and layout into harmonious designs. *Bradley, His Book* was emblematic of this prowess and served as a canvas for Bradley to experiment with fonts, ornamental designs, and visual storytelling.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The content within *Bradley, His Book* was an amalgamation of art, literature, and advertising. The magazine featured original illustrations and typography by Bradley, as well as literary contributions, including poetry and prose, from contemporary writers. It also featured advertisements, which were designed by Bradley himself, thus ensuring that even the commercial aspects of the magazine were imbued with aesthetic value.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the defining characteristics of *Bradley, His Book* was its meticulous attention to detail. The magazine was printed on high-quality paper, and the level of craftsmanship in the typography and illustrations was exquisite. The visual elements were characterized by sinuous lines, ornate patterns, and an interplay of type and image that was both innovative and captivating.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, *Bradley, His Book* was also an homage to the Chap-Book style, which harkens back to the pamphlets and small books of the 16th and 17th centuries. Bradley''s reinterpretation of this style integrated the Art Nouveau sensibilities, thereby bridging the gap between historical forms and modern aesthetics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though its tenure was brief, *Bradley, His Book* remains a significant chapter in the annals of American graphic design. It was not only a repository of William H. Bradley’s boundless creativity but also an embodiment of a moment in time when art and design were undergoing profound transformation. In retrospect, *Bradley, His Book* is a luminous beacon that continues to inspire and inform generations of artists and designers.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Brandweek
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Brandweek', N'brandweek', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A weekly American marketing and advertising trade publication focused on news, insights and industry developments in brand advertising and marketing.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Brandweek* is a renowned periodical that serves as an invaluable resource for marketing professionals and brand strategists. First published in 1986 as a weekly trade magazine, *Brandweek* occupied a niche in the industry by providing in-depth analysis, news, and insights related to branding and marketing. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The pages of *Brandweek* are replete with a plethora of articles that span a vast gamut of topics pertinent to branding. This includes, but is not limited to, brand strategies, consumer trends, marketing innovations, and case studies of successful branding campaigns. By offering incisive and well-researched content, *Brandweek* has established itself as an authoritative voice in the realm of brand management.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the distinguishing features of *Brandweek* is its commitment to staying abreast of the evolving landscape of marketing. The magazine has astutely recognized and adapted to the technological advancements that have revolutionized the industry. Consequently, its coverage encompasses not only traditional marketing channels but also digital and social media platforms.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to news and articles, *Brandweek* is celebrated for its proprietary reports and rankings, which are eagerly anticipated by industry professionals. These reports often provide a benchmark for the performance of brands and serve as a barometer for emerging trends in the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, *Brandweek* has been instrumental in fostering a community of marketing professionals through its events and conferences. These gatherings serve as a crucible for the exchange of ideas and facilitate networking among industry peers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2011, *Brandweek* underwent a significant transition when it merged with two other publications, *MediaWeek* and *Adweek*, to form an integrated platform under the *Adweek* banner. This consolidation was emblematic of the converging facets of the marketing industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Brandweek*, in its essence, was more than a magazine; it was an indispensable compendium for marketing professionals. Its legacy endures through its continued influence on the industry and the myriad professionals whose careers were shaped by the insights and knowledge disseminated through its pages.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Broadside
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Broadside', N'broadside', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An underground newspaper that served as an important platform for countercultural voices and social activism during the 1960s and 1970s.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Broadside* is a storied magazine that has carved its niche in the annals of American music history. The publication was established in 1962 by Agnes “Sis” Cunningham and her husband Gordon Friesen. *Broadside* was conceived as a platform for the burgeoning folk and protest music movement that was gaining momentum during the tumultuous 1960s in the United States.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine took its name from the historical “broadsides”, which were single sheets of paper printed on one side, often containing ballads or political commentary. True to its namesake, *Broadside* became a repository for songs that were imbued with social and political messages, reflecting the zeitgeist of the era. The pages of the magazine were adorned with lyrics and music, often accompanied by the earnest illustrations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Broadside* was instrumental in launching the careers of a pantheon of iconic musicians. These included the likes of Bob Dylan, Phil Ochs, and Janis Ian, who were among the litany of artists that found their voices amplified through the magazine. The magazine’s commitment to fostering new talent was manifest in its ethos, as it avowedly provided an unadulterated platform for musicians to share their artistry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notably, *Broadside* eschewed commercial interests and was resolutely independent in its editorial stance. The magazine was often produced in the modest environs of the founders’ apartment, with contributors often engaging in the process of assembling the publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Broadside* remained in circulation until 1988. However, its legacy was indelibly etched in the annals of American music. The magazine was not only a reflection of the times but also a catalyst that propelled the folk and protest music movement. Its pages were a tapestry of songs that were emblematic of the dreams, struggles, and aspirations of a generation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Even though *Broadside* has ceased publication, its spirit endures in the pantheon of music it nurtured and the indelible mark it left on American culture. It remains a cherished artifact, a testament to the power of music as a vehicle for social change.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Bronzeman
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Bronzeman', N'the-bronzeman', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A pulp magazine that primarily focused on publishing short stories related to adventure, romance, and heroism during the early 20th century in the United States.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Bronzeman* is an eminent publication with a legacy that occupies an august position in the chronicles of African American history. Conceived in the 20th century, it was a magazine that sought to provide a platform for African American voices, narratives, and perspectives.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The pages of *The Bronzeman* were adorned with a rich tapestry of articles, stories, poetry, and illustrations that reflected the African American experience. It was a crucible for cultural expression, where the written word and visual art coalesced to create a dynamic tableau. Through its medium, *The Bronzeman* illuminated the aspirations, struggles, and triumphs of the African American community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the distinctive aspects of *The Bronzeman* was its commitment to education. It was not merely a magazine; it was an instrument for enlightenment, fostering knowledge and understanding among its readership. It sought to instill pride in African heritage and to engender a sense of community among African Americans.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Bronzeman* was not just a reflection of the times, but also an agent of change. At a time when the voices of African Americans were often marginalized, *The Bronzeman* stood as a bastion, championing the ideals of equality, justice, and empowerment.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also provided a forum for emerging African American writers and artists, thus playing a seminal role in nurturing talent. The stories and illustrations that graced its pages were often evocative, drawing from a wellspring of shared history and culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The legacy of *The Bronzeman* is one of profound cultural significance. It was a harbinger of change and a chronicle of history in the making. Through its pages, it rendered the African American narrative with depth and nuance, capturing the essence of a people’s journey.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As a historical artifact, *The Bronzeman* continues to be held in high regard by scholars and enthusiasts alike. It serves as a window into a bygone era and as a reminder of the transformative power of the printed word.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Broom: An International Magazine of the Arts
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Broom: An International Magazine of the Arts', N'broom-an-international-magazine-of-the-arts', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An avant-garde literary magazine that published experimental poetry, prose, and artwork from prominent modernist artists and writers of the 1920s and 1930s.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Broom: An International Magazine of the Arts* was an avant-garde publication that carved a niche for itself as a vanguard of modernist art and literature. Founded in 1921, it was published until 1924, and in its brief existence, it left an indelible mark on the world of arts.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Broom* was an epitome of eclecticism, with its pages adorned by a diverse array of content that spanned various art forms and genres. From poetry and prose to visual arts and critical essays, *Broom* traversed a broad spectrum of creative expression. The magazine was not constrained by geographical boundaries; it embraced works from artists and writers from around the globe. This internationalism was reflected in the very title of the magazine, signifying its global purview.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the distinguishing features of *Broom* was its innovative layout and design. The pages were a visual feast, with daring typography and experimental layouts that reflected the avant-garde ethos of the magazine. The aesthetic sensibilities of *Broom* were inextricably linked to its content, and this synergy between form and substance was one of the hallmarks of the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The editorial helm of *Broom* was graced by Harold Loeb, who, along with his co-editors, had a discerning eye for groundbreaking works. Loeb’s stewardship was characterized by a commitment to pushing the boundaries of artistic expression.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'An important aspect of *Broom* was its role as a crucible for emerging talent. It was a platform where burgeoning artists and writers could showcase their works, often giving them their first taste of recognition. At the same time, *Broom* featured works by established figures, thus creating a tapestry that was both rich and diverse.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Broom* was not merely a magazine; it was a movement. It was an amalgamation of voices, styles, and forms that epitomized the spirit of modernism. In its pages, one could find the zeitgeist of an era, the restless energy of artists striving for new forms of expression.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though its run was brief, the impact of *Broom: An International Magazine of the Arts* was profound. It stands as a testament to the creative ferment of the early 20th century, and its legacy continues to inspire and enlighten. It is a treasured artifact of artistic history, a beacon that illuminated the path for generations of artists and writers.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Brownies' Book
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Brownies'' Book', N'the-brownies-book', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly publication aimed at African American children that featured stories, poetry, and articles about history, culture, and contemporary events during the early 20th century.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Brownies'' Book* was a pioneering monthly periodical intended for the edification and amusement of children of African descent. Conceived in the United States, this illustrious publication first graced newsstands in January 1920 and continued to be issued until December 1921. A labor of love, *The Brownies'' Book* was helmed by W.E.B. Du Bois, Jessie Redmon Fauset, and Augustus Granville Dill, esteemed figures who were also associated with the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP).{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the pages of *The Brownies'' Book*, young readers found a treasure trove of literature, including short stories, poems, biographies, and splendid illustrations. The literary compositions were remarkable in that they often featured African American protagonists, a rarity for the time, and sought to instill in young readers a sense of pride in their heritage. The magazine’s editorial mandate was to challenge the prevailing societal norms that marginalized the contributions of African Americans. It sought to provide children with stories that they could identify with, while also enlightening them about their ancestral heritage and cultures.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The Brownies'' Book* was a veritable celebration of the vibrancy and depth of African American culture. Its pages were adorned with the work of prominent African American authors and illustrators of the day. It was noted for its unapologetic embrace of the cultural heritage of its readership and its unwavering commitment to providing young minds with edifying content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the publication of *The Brownies'' Book* was relatively short-lived, its impact continues to resonate. It is revered as a trailblazing publication that not only celebrated the rich tapestry of African American culture but also paved the way for subsequent generations of writers and publications dedicated to representing diverse voices. *The Brownies'' Book* holds an indelible place in the annals of American literature and remains a testament to the fortitude and vision of its creators.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Business 2.0
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Business 2.0', N'business-2.0', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A defunct monthly magazine that covered business, technology, and innovation, and featured articles on emerging trends and startup companies during the dot-com era.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Business 2.0* was a heralded periodical that flourished during the zenith of the late 20th and early 21st centuries. This illustrious magazine was conceived in the bosom of the San Francisco Bay Area, an epicenter of technological innovation. Launched in 1998, *Business 2.0* stood as a sentinel and scribe, chronicling the bustling intersection between emerging technologies and the world of business.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As the digital age unfurled its wings, *Business 2.0* found its niche among the cognoscenti of the business and technology domains. The magazine’s pages were adorned with erudite analyses, astute insights, and forward-looking commentaries on topics spanning e-commerce, web services, venture capital, and the burgeoning dot-com industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s editorial slant espoused a contrarian and optimistic outlook toward the burgeoning technological landscape. It illuminated the labyrinthine pathways of the Internet economy, guiding readers through the volatile dot-com bubble and beyond.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2001, *Business 2.0* was acquired by Time Inc., marking the beginning of a new chapter. As part of the Time Warner conglomerate, the magazine expanded its purview, examining a broader spectrum of topics beyond the confines of the technology sector.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, the inexorable march of time and the ascent of online media precipitated the decline of print publications. In 2007, after nearly a decade of prodigious influence, *Business 2.0* published its final issue.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though *Business 2.0* has faded into the annals of history, it remains an emblem of a bygone era. The magazine’s indelible legacy endures in the annals of American publishing as a vanguard that illuminated the tumultuous and electrifying dawn of the Information Age. Through its pages, it captured the zeitgeist of a transformative epoch, in which humanity’s inexorable embrace of technology recast the contours of commerce and society.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Business Nashville
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Business Nashville', N'business-nashville', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Publication focused on covering business news, trends, and profiles of successful companies in Nashville, Tennessee.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Business Nashville* is an esteemed publication that holds a distinguished place among the business periodicals in the United States. With Nashville, Tennessee as its focal point, the magazine delves into the multifaceted dynamics of the city’s thriving business community. It disseminates insightful analyses on various sectors such as healthcare, technology, entertainment, and real estate, and seeks to keep its readers apprised of the latest developments and trends.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The editorial team, with its sagacious acumen, meticulously curates content that not only encompasses the breadth and depth of the business landscape but also engages the readership with its perspicacious writing style. Entrepreneurs, investors, and professionals alike find *Business Nashville* to be an invaluable resource for staying informed and making astute business decisions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine’s salient features is its proclivity for providing an in-depth portrayal of the local business community. Through interviews with luminaries and profiles of burgeoning companies, *Business Nashville* captures the essence of the city’s entrepreneurial spirit and innovation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition, the magazine often serves as a platform for discourse on pressing social and economic issues, rendering it an indispensable conduit for the exchange of ideas among Nashville’s business community. This reflective aspect of the magazine helps in forging a sense of unity and camaraderie among its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, *Business Nashville* has garnered accolades for its commitment to journalistic integrity and excellence. The quality of its content and the veracity of the information provided have cemented its status as a publication of repute.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In summation, *Business Nashville* is not merely a magazine; it is an institution that fosters knowledge, cultivates leadership, and epitomizes the essence of the Nashville business community through its incisive and eloquent chronicling of the city’s economic landscape.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Calico Print
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Calico Print', N'calico-print', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Features the latest trends, news, and opinions in the exciting world of textile and fabric design.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Calico Print* was a beloved magazine that found its niche amongst textile enthusiasts and individuals with an affinity for art and craft. Published in the United States, *Calico Print* provided readers with an in-depth look into the world of textiles. Its pages were filled with a plethora of captivating content, including the historical perspective of fabrics, interviews with artisans, and enlightening tutorials.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the most admirable qualities of *Calico Print* was its ability to seamlessly blend educational content with engaging storytelling. The magazine was known to have a loyal following, which can be attributed to its insightful articles and the passion it exhibited for the craft.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The historical significance of textiles was often brought to the forefront in *Calico Print*. The magazine’s pages delved into the rich tapestry of textile history, tracing the origins of various fabrics and the roles they played in different cultures. It was not uncommon for readers to find themselves immersed in articles that painted vivid pictures of ancient civilizations and their ingenious textile techniques.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, *Calico Print* was a wellspring of inspiration for aspiring artisans. It offered invaluable advice on textile art creation, from the selection of materials to intricate weaving techniques. Through its meticulously curated content, the magazine nurtured countless individuals’ creative spirits, paving the way for the birth of new ideas and innovative designs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Additionally, *Calico Print* wasn’t just about textiles; it harbored a deep appreciation for art and craft in all its forms. Readers were often treated to articles that explored the worlds of embroidery, dyeing, and more. Through this diverse content, the magazine fostered a community that was united by a shared love for creativity.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In essence, *Calico Print* was more than a magazine; it was a treasure trove of knowledge and inspiration for those enchanted by the world of textiles and crafts. It not only educated but also celebrated the rich heritage and boundless possibilities that the textile world holds. Through its pages, *Calico Print* weaved stories that transcended time, leaving an indelible mark on the hearts of its readers.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- California Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'California Magazine', N'california-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Provides comprehensive coverage of the top news, events, and lifestyle trends related to the vibrant culture and diverse communities within the state of California.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*California* was an American periodical that, during its tenure, served as a vibrant window into the culture and lifestyle of California. Launched in the golden state of California, the magazine’s pages were adorned with rich content ranging from art and entertainment to politics and social issues pertinent to California and beyond. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its publication, *California* was noted for its eclectic mix of articles, features, and op-eds that captured the essence of California’s diverse populace. The editorial team''s discerning eye for detail and commitment to journalistic integrity made the magazine a treasure trove for both casual readers and aficionados of California culture. With its glossy pages, *California* could often be seen gracing the coffee tables and bookshelves of the state''s residents.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A significant aspect of the magazine’s charm lay in its visual elements. *California* was a testament to the adage that “a picture is worth a thousand words,” employing photography that captured the state’s breathtaking landscapes, bustling cities, and vibrant communities. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, as with many print publications, *California* faced challenges. The advent of digital media and the changing preferences of readers ultimately led to its cessation in 1991. Though *California* is no longer in circulation, it remains an emblematic artifact of a bygone era. It serves as a nostalgic reminder of the ethos and zeitgeist of California during the years it was published. The magazine’s legacy is still cherished by those who had the privilege of leafing through its pages, and it continues to be a source of inspiration for contemporary publications that strive to capture the multifaceted spirit of California.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- California Farmer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'California Farmer', N'california-farmer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Documents the trends and developments in agriculture in California, featuring news, insights, and profiles of the state''s farmers and agribusinesses.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*California Farmer* is a venerable publication that has long held a place of prominence within the agricultural community of California. Established in 1854, it is one of the oldest continuously published magazines in the United States. The magazine’s primary focus is on agriculture and farming, providing invaluable insights into the myriad aspects of the industry.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over its long history, *California Farmer* has been a stalwart advocate for farmers and the agricultural sector. The magazine has chronicled the evolution of agriculture in California, from the early days of the state’s statehood to the modern era of technological innovations in farming. It has stood as an authoritative voice in reporting on crop production, livestock management, agricultural policies, and innovations in farming equipment and techniques.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the defining characteristics of *California Farmer* is its in-depth articles that explore the challenges and opportunities faced by farmers. These articles often offer practical advice and solutions that are grounded in years of experience and expertise. Furthermore, the magazine''s coverage is not limited to farming alone, as it also delves into issues concerning rural life, agricultural business, and the environment.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*California Farmer* has also played a significant role in highlighting the importance of sustainable and environmentally responsible farming practices. Through thought-provoking features and interviews with experts, the magazine has encouraged dialogue on how farming can be conducted in a manner that is both economically viable and ecologically sustainable.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its printed issues, *California Farmer* has embraced the digital age by providing content online. This has allowed it to reach a wider audience and to continue its mission of informing and supporting the agricultural community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In sum, *California Farmer* is not just a magazine, but an institution that has, for over a century and a half, been at the forefront of agricultural journalism. Through its unwavering commitment to the farming community and its insightful and pragmatic coverage, it has earned a place of respect and admiration among its readers and the wider agricultural sector.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 3rd Stone
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'3rd Stone', N'3rd-stone', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An enlightening exploration of archaeology, anthropology, and ancient civilizations, 3rd Stone magazine provides in-depth coverage and compelling insights.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'3rd Stone magazine is a notable magazine that explores the intersections of archaeology, anthropology, and ancient civilizations.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Origins and Publication' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'3rd Stone magazine was established with the goal of delving into the fascinating world of archaeology and anthropology. The magazine, renowned for its in-depth coverage and insightful articles, primarily focuses on ancient civilizations, cultural heritage, and the latest findings in the field.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'3rd Stone magazine offers a diverse range of content that appeals to both scholars and enthusiasts alike. The publication covers various topics such as archaeological excavations, anthropological research, historical discoveries, and scientific advancements in the field. Through well-researched articles and thought-provoking analysis, the magazine aims to bring the wonders of the past to life for its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Exploring Ancient Civilizations' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the key aspects of 3rd Stone magazine is its exploration of ancient civilizations from all corners of the world. The magazine showcases the cultural, social, and technological achievements of past societies, providing readers with insights into their traditions, art, architecture, and daily lives. Through detailed accounts and expert contributions, 3rd Stone magazine strives to deepen our understanding of humanity''s rich and diverse history.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Field Reports and Research Updates' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'To keep readers informed about the latest developments in archaeology and anthropology, 3rd Stone magazine regularly features field reports and research updates. These articles highlight ongoing excavations, new discoveries, and important breakthroughs that contribute to our knowledge of the past. The magazine aims to bridge the gap between academia and the general public, making archaeological and anthropological research accessible and engaging.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Visual Documentation and Photography' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'3rd Stone magazine recognizes the power of visuals in conveying the beauty and significance of ancient artifacts and archaeological sites. The publication showcases high-quality photographs and illustrations that bring readers closer to the remarkable artifacts, structures, and landscapes associated with ancient civilizations. This visual documentation adds depth and context to the articles, further enriching the reader''s experience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Interviews and Profiles' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its informative articles, 3rd Stone magazine features interviews with prominent archaeologists, anthropologists, and experts in related fields. These interviews provide readers with insights into the work and experiences of these professionals, offering a glimpse into their research methodologies and the challenges they face. By sharing these perspectives, the magazine encourages dialogue and fosters a deeper appreciation for the disciplines of archaeology and anthropology.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

