VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A sophisticated American magazine (1913–1936) showcasing literature, art, and satire, influencing culture and popularizing fashion.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Vanity Fair**, known as *Vanity Fair: A Weekly Show of the World''s Vanity* in its early years, was a prominent American magazine that was published from 1913 to 1936. The magazine focused on a blend of literature, art, culture, and fashion, catering to a sophisticated and affluent readership.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Establishment and Format' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Vanity Fair was established in New York City in 1913 by Condé Montrose Nast, with the publication''s format inspired by the British magazine of the same name. The magazine initially began as a humor publication but quickly evolved into a general-interest magazine covering a wide range of topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Content and Contributors' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Vanity Fair featured a combination of articles, editorials, fiction, and illustrations, showcasing the work of notable writers, artists, and photographers of the time. The magazine published literary works from renowned authors such as F. Scott Fitzgerald, Dorothy Parker, and Virginia Woolf, contributing to its reputation as a literary publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Cultural Commentary and Satire' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the distinctive features of Vanity Fair was its social commentary and satirical approach. The magazine employed a witty and critical tone in its coverage of societal issues, politics, and popular culture. It often featured cartoons and illustrations that cleverly satirized the world of the wealthy and influential.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Fashion, Art, and Photography' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Vanity Fair played a significant role in the promotion and coverage of fashion, art, and photography. The magazine showcased the latest trends, designers, and fashion icons of the time, contributing to its reputation as a style authority. Its pages also displayed the works of prominent artists and photographers, including Edward Steichen and Man Ray.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Vanity Fair''s unique blend of literature, art, and cultural commentary made it a significant influence on American media and popular culture during the early 20th century. It inspired and paved the way for subsequent magazines that focused on similar subjects and aesthetics. Although the magazine ceased publication in 1936 due to various factors, its impact on American journalism and culture endured.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

