VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A prominent American publisher of pulp magazines, comics, and novels during the 1930s to the 1950s, known for its diverse range of titles and high editorial standards.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Thrilling Publications was a publishing company that specialized in pulp magazines, comic books, and novels. The company was active in the United States from the 1930s to the 1950s and was one of the most important publishers of pulp fiction in the country.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Thrilling Publications was founded in 1931 by Ned Pines, a prominent figure in the publishing industry. The company began by publishing pulp magazines, which were cheaply produced periodicals that featured stories of adventure, crime, and romance.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Thrilling Publications quickly became one of the most successful publishers of pulp magazines in the United States. The company was known for its diverse range of titles, which included Westerns, detective stories, science fiction, and horror.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publications' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Thrilling Publications published numerous pulp magazines during its existence. Some of the most notable titles included:' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Thrilling Adventure Stories' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Thrilling Detective' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Thrilling Love' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Thrilling Mystery' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Thrilling Western' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its magazines, Thrilling Publications also published comic books and novels. The company was particularly successful in the comic book market, with titles such as The Black Hood, Blue Beetle, and Captain Midnight.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Thrilling Publications played a significant role in the development of pulp fiction in the United States. The company was known for its high editorial standards, and its magazines featured some of the most talented writers and artists of their time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its contributions to pulp fiction, Thrilling Publications also helped to shape the comic book industry. The company''s success with characters such as The Black Hood and Blue Beetle inspired numerous imitators and helped to establish the superhero genre.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Decline and Closure' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Thrilling Publications faced numerous challenges in the 1950s, including competition from television and the decline of the pulp magazine market. The company attempted to adapt to the changing market by shifting its focus to comic books, but was ultimately unsuccessful.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Thrilling Publications ceased operations in the early 1960s. However, the company''s magazines and comic books remain popular among collectors and fans of pulp fiction and comic book history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Tiger
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Tiger', N'tiger', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A British weekly boys'' adventure paper published from 1954 to 1985, known for its diverse range of content and iconic characters such as Roy of the Rovers.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger was a weekly boys'' adventure paper published in the United Kingdom by Amalgamated Press from 1954-1985. It was one of the most popular British comic books during its publication.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger magazine first appeared on September 11, 1954, and it was initially published by the Amalgamated Press, which later became Fleetway Publications. The magazine was created by Leonard Matthews, who also edited it until 1967. The first issue was 28 pages long and was priced at sixpence. The magazine was printed in a black-and-white format and featured numerous stories of adventure, sports, and war.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Contents' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger magazine was known for its wide range of content, which included stories about sports, war, and adventure. Some of the most popular characters in the magazine included:' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Roy of the Rovers' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Johnny Cougar' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Skid Solo' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- The Iron Man' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Robot Archie' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also featured informative articles about sports, such as football, rugby, cricket, and athletics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger magazine was an important part of British comics history and has had a lasting impact on the industry. The magazine was known for its high-quality storytelling and artwork, which inspired numerous other British comics. In particular, Roy of the Rovers became one of the most iconic and beloved characters in British comics history.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Decline and Closure' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the 1970s and 1980s, the popularity of Tiger magazine began to decline due to increased competition from other comic books and changing tastes among readers. In 1985, the magazine ceased publication, although some of its characters and stories were carried over into other publications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Revival' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger magazine has been revived several times in various forms over the years. In the 1990s, the character of Roy of the Rovers was given his own comic book title, and in 2005, a one-shot special titled "The Best of Tiger" was published. In 2011, Titan Books began publishing a series of collections featuring reprints of Tiger stories and characters.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Tiger Beat
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Tiger Beat', N'tiger-beat', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A long-running American teen magazine known for its coverage of celebrity news, interviews, and entertainment, shaping teen culture and launching the careers of many popular musicians.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger Beat is a teen magazine that focuses on celebrity news, interviews, and entertainment. It has been in publication for over 50 years and has become a staple of teen culture in the United States.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger Beat was first published in September 1965 by Charles Laufer, who later became the president and chairman of Laufer Media. The magazine was created to fill a gap in the teen magazine market, which at the time was dominated by publications aimed at girls. Tiger Beat quickly became popular among teenage boys and girls alike, providing coverage of pop and rock music stars.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Contents' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger Beat magazine has covered a wide range of topics over the years, but its main focus has always been on celebrity news and entertainment. The magazine has featured interviews with some of the biggest names in music, television, and film, including the Beatles, Elvis Presley, Michael Jackson, and Zac Efron.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to celebrity news, Tiger Beat also includes fashion and beauty tips, quizzes, and posters of popular celebrities.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger Beat has had a significant impact on teen culture in the United States. Its coverage of popular celebrities has helped to create and shape celebrity culture, inspiring young people to dress like their favorite stars, listen to their music, and follow their careers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has also been influential in the music industry, helping to launch the careers of many successful musicians. The Beatles, for example, were featured on the cover of Tiger Beat in 1966, and the magazine''s coverage of the band helped to increase their popularity with teenage fans in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Recent Developments' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger Beat magazine has faced increasing competition from other entertainment and celebrity news sources, as the internet has made it easier for fans to access information about their favorite stars. In response, the magazine has expanded its online presence, launching a website and social media channels in order to reach a wider audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tiger Beat continues to be popular among teenagers in the United States, and its coverage of celebrity news and entertainment remains a staple of teen culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Tips & Tricks
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Tips & Tricks', N'tips-and-tricks', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A popular US-based video game magazine that offered readers practical tips, cheats and strategies for popular video games during the 1990s and early 2000s, shaping gaming culture and influencing internet forums.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tips & Tricks was a video game magazine that focused on providing readers with tips and tricks for their favorite games. The magazine was published in the United States and was popular during the 1990s and early 2000s.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tips & Tricks was first published in 1994 by High Score Publications. The magazine quickly gained a loyal following among video game enthusiasts, who appreciated its in-depth coverage of games and its focus on providing readers with practical advice to improve their gaming skills.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Tips & Tricks published hundreds of issues, featuring articles on a wide range of games across all platforms, from the original Nintendo Entertainment System to the latest consoles and PC games.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Format' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tips & Tricks was organized into several sections, including features on popular games, strategy guides, and cheat codes. Each issue also included sections for letters to the editor, reader-submitted tips, and news and previews of upcoming games.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was known for its detailed and informative articles, which were often written by experienced gamers and industry insiders. Tips & Tricks also featured high-quality screenshots and artwork to accompany its articles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tips & Tricks had a significant impact on the video game industry, particularly among hardcore gamers. The magazine''s coverage of popular games and its detailed strategy guides helped to create and shape gaming culture, inspiring players to improve their skills and compete with others.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, Tips & Tricks played a critical role in the early days of the internet, where its cheat codes, tips, and strategies were often shared online on different forums and websites, making it an influential source of information in the gaming community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Demise' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tips & Tricks experienced a decline in readership during the early 2000s, due in part to the rise of the internet, which made it easier for players to find cheat codes and game guides online. The magazine experienced several ownership changes and was eventually shut down in 2007.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- To-Morrow
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'To-Morrow', N'to-morrow', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A literary magazine notable for its avant-garde content and role in the development of literary modernism in the US during the 1910s and 1920s.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'To-Morrow was a literary magazine founded and edited by Margaret Anderson and Jane Heap that was published in Chicago from 1917 to 1923. The magazine was known for its literary modernism and avant-garde content.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'To-Morrow was first published in March 1917, with Anderson and Heap serving as editors. The magazine was published out of Anderson''s apartment in Chicago and was initially funded by their personal savings.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'To-Morrow quickly gained a reputation for its avant-garde content, including works by writers such as Sherwood Anderson, Ezra Pound, T.S. Eliot, and James Joyce. The magazine was also known for its artistic layout, with contributions from notable designers and illustrators of the time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1920, To-Morrow changed its name to The Little Review and continued to publish literary modernism until it was forced to cease publication in 1929 due to legal troubles resulting from the serialization of James Joyce''s novel Ulysses.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Format' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'To-Morrow was a monthly magazine that was printed on high-quality paper with a distinct artistic layout. The magazine featured poetry, fiction, drama, and essays, as well as book reviews and art criticism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was committed to literary modernism and published works that were experimental and challenging, often featuring contributors who pushed the boundaries of traditional forms and styles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'To-Morrow played a significant role in the development of literary modernism in the United States. The magazine was a platform for experimental writers and artists, many of whom went on to become leading figures in the literary and artistic communities.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, To-Morrow was known for its engagement with important political and cultural issues of the time, such as feminism and activism, further cementing its reputation as a leading voice in the avant-garde.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'To-Morrow''s legacy can be seen in its influence on later literary and artistic movements, particularly in the development of modernism in the United States. The magazine paved the way for experimental literary works and helped to create a community of avant-garde writers and artists who would go on to have a profound impact on 20th-century culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Tokyopop
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Tokyopop', N'tokyopop', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An influential US-based publisher of manga and related media that popularized Japanese comics in the United States during the 2000s.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tokyopop was a US-based publishing company that focused on manga - or Japanese comics - and related media. The company was one of the leading publishers of manga in the United States during the 2000s and was instrumental in popularizing the genre.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tokyopop was founded in 1997 by Stu Levy, who was inspired by his experiences as an exchange student in Japan. The company initially focused on publishing Japanese manga in English, and quickly grew to become one of the leading manga publishers in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to publishing manga, Tokyopop was also involved in other aspects of the comic book industry, including creating graphic novels and producing animated television shows.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tokyopop ceased publishing new titles in 2011, and its assets were sold to another company in 2013.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Format' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tokyopop primarily published manga in English, including both series aimed at shonen (boys) and shojo (girls) audiences. The company is notable for popularizing the concept of "Original English-Language manga", publishing manga-style comics created by American writers and artists.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to publishing manga, the company also produced graphic novels and other related media, including animated television shows and feature films.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tokyopop played a significant role in the development and popularization of manga in the United States. The company introduced many popular manga series to American readers for the first time, including Sailor Moon and Cardcaptor Sakura.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, Tokyopop''s emphasis on OEL manga helped to create a market for American-made comics that imitated the style and storytelling techniques of Japanese manga.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tokyopop''s legacy can be seen in the continued popularity of manga in the United States and around the world. The company helped to popularize the genre and introduced many readers to works they might not have discovered otherwise.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Additionally, Tokyopop''s emphasis on OEL manga helped to create opportunities for American writers and artists by providing a platform for their work to be published and recognized.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Tomorrow
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
