VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American men''s magazine known for its provocative and controversial content, covering topics such as true crime, adventure, and the supernatural, published from 1927 to 1975.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'True was an American men''s magazine that covered a wide range of topics, including true crime, adventure, and the supernatural. The magazine was known for its lurid and controversial content and was published from 1927 until 1975.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'True was founded in 1927 by Bernarr Macfadden, a prominent publisher and health enthusiast. The magazine''s early content focused on adventure stories and real-life tales of exploration and survival.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the 1940s, True began to shift its focus towards true crime and other sensational topics, which helped to make it one of the most popular men''s magazines of the era. The magazine also gained notoriety for its provocative covers, many of which featured scantily clad women.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity, True faced a number of challenges throughout its history. The magazine was banned in several countries for its graphic content, and it also faced increased competition from other men''s magazines in the 1950s and 1960s. True ceased publication in 1975 after nearly 50 years in business.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'True covered a wide range of topics throughout its history, including true crime, adventure, and the supernatural. The magazine was known for its graphic and often lurid content, which included stories of violent crime, sex, and other controversial topics. True also featured articles on sports, politics, and other current events.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Editors and Contributors' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'True was edited by a number of individuals throughout its history, including visionary publisher Bernarr Macfadden, popular writer and editor Ken Purdy, and journalist Milton Helpern. The magazine also featured contributions from a variety of writers, photographers, and illustrators.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Impact and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'True had a significant impact on the landscape of American men''s magazines and helped to pave the way for other publications in the genre. The magazine''s lurid content and provocative covers helped to define the style of 1950s men''s magazines, and True remains a much-studied cultural artifact of that era.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition, True''s legacy can be seen in the modern true crime genre, which continues to thrive in books, movies, and television shows. The magazine helped to popularize the true crime genre and set a new standard for storytelling in that field.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'True was an American men''s magazine that covered a variety of topics, including true crime, adventure, and the supernatural. The magazine was known for its controversial content and provocative covers, and it helped to define the style of men''s magazines in the 1950s{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

