VALUES ( N'Surfing', N'surfing', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A historic American surf magazine showcasing surfing techniques, culture, and issues, with award-winning photography and a unique editorial style".}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Surfing was a magazine covering the sport and culture of surfing in the United States. The magazine was published from 1964 to 2017 and was the longest running surf magazine in the country.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Surfing was founded in 1964 by surfers Bruce Brown and Warren Miller, who were also famous for their surf and ski films, respectively. The magazine was based in Southern California and quickly became popular among surfers and enthusiasts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, Surfing featured articles and stories about surfing techniques, surf culture, and interesting destinations. The magazine also focused on environmental issues affecting the surfing community, including water pollution and coastal development.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2001, Surfing merged with another popular surf magazine, Surfer, but continued to be published as a separate title. However, in 2017, the magazine was discontinued due to the decline in print media circulation and changes in the surfing industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Surfing covered a wide range of topics related to surfing, including surf reports, interviews with professional surfers, and travel guides to popular surf destinations. The magazine also featured high-quality photography, with stunning images of waves and surfers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Surfing was known for its unique editorial style and for pushing boundaries in the surf media landscape. The magazine''s team of writers and editors were respected figures in the surf community and contributed to the development of the sport and lifestyle.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Reception and Significance' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Surfing was a significant publication in the history of surf media and had a loyal following among surfers and enthusiasts. The magazine won numerous awards over the years, including multiple honors from the Society of Publication Designers and the International Surfing Association.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Surfing also contributed to the development of the surf industry, with its coverage of professional surf contests and trends in surfboard design. The magazine played a role in creating a sense of community among surfers, connecting surfers around the world through its coverage and content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its discontinuation, Surfing remains an influential publication in the history of surf culture in the United States.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Survey Graphic
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Survey Graphic', N'survey-graphic', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American magazine that focused on social issues and played a crucial role in shaping public opinion on race, gender, and poverty in the United States".}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Survey Graphic was an American magazine that was published from 1921 to 1953. The magazine was known for its groundbreaking coverage of social issues, including race, gender, and poverty.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Survey Graphic was founded in 1921 by the Survey Associates, a group of social workers and scholars, with the goal of using a blend of academic and popular literature to raise awareness about social issues. The magazine was based in New York City and had a wide readership across the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, Survey Graphic published articles, photo essays, and art related to social issues affecting American society. The magazine was a strong advocate for social justice and as such, the topics covered in the publication were often considered controversial at the time. However, Survey Graphic''s coverage played a crucial role in raising awareness and promoting change on important issues. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1940, Survey Graphic underwent a name change and became the Journal of Social Issues. The publication continued to focus on social issues until its end in 1953.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Survey Graphic covered a wide range of topics related to social issues in the United States. The magazine featured in-depth articles about race relations, poverty, labor, and women''s issues, among others. The publication also had a strong focus on art, with commissioned works by famous artists and photographers, including Dorothea Lange, Rockwell Kent, and Jacob Lawrence.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Additionally, Survey Graphic featured a number of "case studies," in which the social problems affecting a particular region or community were analyzed and presented in a narrative format. These case studies were some of the most popular features of the magazine and gave readers an intimate look at the lives and circumstances of those directly affected by social issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Reception and Significance' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Survey Graphic was known for its groundbreaking coverage of social issues and was one of the first publications of its kind. The magazine played a crucial role in shaping public opinion and was instrumental in the passage of important social legislation. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Survey Graphic''s unique format, with its blend of academic and popular literature, was influential in establishing the genre of "intellectual journalism." The magazine also helped to launch the careers of many famous writers and scholars, including W. E. B. Du Bois and Langston Hughes.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Survey Graphic''s successor, the Journal of Social Issues, continued the magazine''s legacy of promoting social justice and was a respected publication until its end in 1953.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Swindle
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Swindle', N'swindle', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American independent magazine published from 2004 to 2010, known for its irreverent and provocative coverage of popular culture and counterculture.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Swindle was an American independent magazine that was published from 2004 to 2010. The publication was known for its irreverent and provocative coverage of popular culture and counterculture.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Swindle was founded in 2004 by writer and editor Roger Gastman and artist Shepard Fairey. The magazine was based in Los Angeles, California, and had a distinct DIY aesthetic, with a focus on street art, graffiti, and underground culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its run, Swindle published articles, interviews, and photo essays related to a wide range of topics, including music, fashion, art, and politics. The publication was characterized by its irreverent tone and willingness to cover controversial subjects.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print magazine, Swindle also maintained a significant online presence, with a number of related blogs, podcasts, and video series.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Swindle covered a wide range of topics related to popular and counterculture, with a particular focus on street art and graffiti. The magazine featured interviews with famous artists and cultural figures, including Banksy, Shepard Fairey, and Spike Jonze.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Swindle also had a number of regular features, including "In the Studio," which provided an inside look at artists'' workspaces, and "Crate Diggers," which profiled record collectors and their collections.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Additionally, Swindle was known for its design aesthetic, with each issue featuring unique layouts and graphic design. The magazine also included various inserts, such as posters and stickers, which added to the publication''s collectible appeal.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Reception and Significance' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Swindle was known for its irreverence and unique perspective on popular culture and counterculture. The publication played an important role in promoting street art and graffiti as legitimate forms of artistic expression and helped to elevate many of the figures associated with these movements.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Swindle''s provocative style and willingness to push boundaries made it a beloved publication among many readers, although it was not without its critics. Nonetheless, the magazine''s influence on popular culture and design cannot be denied, and its legacy can still be seen in the many publications and cultural movements that followed in its wake.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Synapse
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Synapse', N'synapse', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American electronic music magazine launched in 1992, known for its artist interviews, gear reviews, and festival coverage.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Synapse was an American publication that focused on the electronic music genre. The magazine was known for covering a wide range of topics related to the electronic music scene, including artist interviews, gear reviews, and music production techniques.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Synapse: The Electronic Music Magazine was launched in 1992 by editor-in-chief Tim Wilson. The magazine was based in San Francisco, California, and quickly gained a reputation for its comprehensive coverage of the electronic music scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its run, Synapse published features on a wide range of electronic music artists, both established and emerging. The magazine also featured gear reviews, production tutorials, and coverage of music festivals and events.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Synapse: The Electronic Music Magazine covered a wide range of topics related to the electronic music scene. The magazine featured interviews with electronic music artists from a variety of sub-genres, including techno, house, ambient, and IDM.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to artist interviews, Synapse also covered various aspects of electronic music production, including gear reviews, software reviews, and production tutorials. The magazine also featured coverage of electronic music festivals and events, with a particular focus on the San Francisco Bay Area scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Synapse: The Electronic Music Magazine was also known for its design aesthetic, with each issue featuring unique layouts and graphic design.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Reception and Significance' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Synapse: The Electronic Music Magazine was widely regarded as one of the premier publications covering the electronic music scene in the United States. The magazine played an important role in promoting the genre and educating its readers about the various artists and production techniques associated with electronic music.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s demise in the early 2000s was seen by many as a reflection of the challenges facing print publications in the digital age. Nonetheless, Synapse''s legacy can still be seen in the many online publications and resources dedicated to electronic music that have emerged since its closure.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Synapse: The Electronic Music Magazine was an important publication in the electronic music scene, providing comprehensive coverage of the genre and its associated production techniques and technologies. The magazine''s legacy can still be seen in the many online resources and publications dedicated to electronic music that are available today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Tactical Knives
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Tactical Knives', N'tactical-knives', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American knife enthusiast magazine covering gear reviews, survival techniques, and self-defense strategies.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tactical Knives (previously known as "Tactical Knives & Gear") is a US-based print and digital publication catering to the knife enthusiast community. The magazine features extensive coverage of knives and other cutting tools, outdoor gear, survival techniques, and self-defense strategies.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tactical Knives was first published in 2001 by Harris Publications, the same company responsible for numerous other print and digital publications in the firearms and outdoor industries. Today, Tactical Knives is part of the Athlon Outdoors Network, which also includes a number of other firearms, hunting, and outdoor publications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, Tactical Knives has featured a wide range of knife-related content, including knife reviews, industry news, and profiles of knife collectors and makers. The magazine has also published articles on topics such as outdoor survival skills, self-defense tactics, and first aid techniques.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the primary focuses of Tactical Knives is on knives and related gear. The magazine regularly publishes reviews of new knives, as well as discussions of knife design, materials, and construction. Tactical Knives also regularly features articles on knife collecting, custom knife makers, and other related topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to knife coverage, Tactical Knives also includes articles on outdoor gear such as backpacks, multi-tools, and flashlights. The magazine has also published articles on outdoor survival skills, including topics such as building shelter, finding food and water, and starting fires.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Finally, Tactical Knives has also published content related to self-defense. The magazine has included articles on various forms of self-defense, including unarmed techniques and the use of weapons such as knives and firearms.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Reception and Significance' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tactical Knives is widely regarded as one of the most authoritative publications in the knife enthusiast community. The magazine''s extensive coverage of knives, outdoor gear, survival techniques, and self-defense has made it a popular resource among a diverse range of readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite some criticism from those who argue that the magazine glorifies violence, Tactical Knives has remained a prominent publication in the outdoor and self-defense industries. Its coverage of these topics has helped to make it a valuable resource for knife enthusiasts and others interested in related fields.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tactical Knives is a highly regarded publication catering to the knife enthusiast community. With in-depth coverage of knives, outdoor gear, survival techniques, and self-defense, the magazine has become a valuable resource for readers interested in these topics.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Tales of the Unexpected
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Tales of the Unexpected', N'tales-of-the-unexpected', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A comic book series that specialized in supernatural and science fiction stories, and had a significant impact on the development of horror and adult-oriented comics.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tales of the Unexpected is a comic book series published by DC Comics that ran from 1956 to 1968. The series dealt with supernatural and science fiction stories.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first issue of Tales of the Unexpected was released in November 1956. It was created by Jack Schiff and Carmine Infantino. Schiff served as editor until 1960, when he was succeeded by George Kashdan. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The series was published bi-monthly until issue 10, after which it became a monthly publication. The series ended with issue #104, released in 1968.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tales of the Unexpected was known for its imaginative and often bizarre stories, mostly centered around supernatural or science fiction themes. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first few issues of the series featured stories drawn by Jack Kirby, while later issues included work from other famous comic book artists such as Steve Ditko and Neal Adams.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to the supernatural and sci-fi elements, Tales of the Unexpected also regularly included stories related to crime and mystery.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy and Significance' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tales of the Unexpected is regarded as one of the most important comic book series of the 1950s and 1960s. The series helped to establish the popularity of science fiction and horror comics, which influenced the development of numerous other comic book series in the following decades.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The series has also been viewed as an important precursor to DC Comics'' Vertigo imprint, which would specialize in adult-oriented comics featuring supernatural and horror themes.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Revivals and Adaptations' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tales of the Unexpected has been revived several times over the years by DC Comics. A new series with the same name was published from 2006 to 2007, which featured various writers and artists working on new supernatural and sci-fi stories.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to the comic book series, Tales of the Unexpected has also been adapted into various other media. In the 1970s, the series was the basis for a short-lived television show produced by Anglia Television. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The series has also been referenced in numerous other works of popular culture, including the song "Tales of the Unexpected" by prog-rock band Jethro Tull.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tales of the Unexpected is a famous comic book series published by DC Comics from 1956 to 1968. Known for its supernatural and science fiction stories, the series has had a significant impact on the development of horror and adult-oriented comics over the years.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Talk
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Talk', N'talk', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A glossy American magazine dedicated to celebrity, culture, and politics that struggled to find a consistent audience and ceased publication in 2002.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Talk was a glossy magazine covering celebrity, culture, politics, and high-end fashion. It was published in the United States from 1999 to 2002.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Talk was founded by journalist Tina Brown, who had previously served as the editor-in-chief of The New Yorker and Vanity Fair. The first issue of Talk was published in August 1999.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite high expectations and an initial circulation of over 600,000 copies, the magazine struggled to find a consistent audience. After losing money for several years, the magazine ceased publication in January 2002.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Talk magazine was known for its focus on celebrity culture, featuring interviews with famous actors, musicians, artists, and politicians. It also covered high-end fashion, politics, and other timely topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to regular columns and features, Talk also published several high-profile investigative articles. Notably, a 2001 article in Talk by Ron Suskind exposed a plot by the George W. Bush administration to undermine the credibility of White House reporter Jeff Gerth.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy and Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its relatively short lifespan, Talk magazine is viewed as a significant publication of the late 1990s and early 2000s. Its high-profile editor, unique design, and mix of pop culture and politics made it stand out in a crowded market.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, Talk''s early embrace of digital media and the internet has been viewed as forward-thinking. The magazine developed a companion website, which included additional stories and multimedia content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Revival Attempts' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Since its untimely demise in 2002, there have been several attempts to revive Talk magazine. In 2003, Miramax Films acquired the rights to the magazine and announced plans to relaunch it as a monthly publication. However, this never came to fruition due to financial difficulties.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2018, it was announced that Tina Brown would be launching a new iteration of Talk as a podcast. The new show, titled "TBD with Tina Brown," features interviews with high-profile figures from the worlds of entertainment, media, and politics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Talk was a short-lived but influential magazine founded by journalist Tina Brown. Known for its blend of celebrity culture, politics, and fashion, the magazine struggled to find a consistent audience and ceased publication in 2002. Despite this, Talk''s innovative design and approach continue to influence the world of media today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Talking Machine World
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Talking Machine World', N'the-talking-machine-world', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A trade publication focusing on phonographs and gramophones. Played a significant role in promoting the industry and was a pioneer in specialized trade publications.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Talking Machine World was a magazine dedicated to the phonograph and gramophone industry. It was published in the United States from 1905 to 1928.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Talking Machine World was launched in 1905 by H. H. Annis, who was a prominent figure in the early phonograph industry. The magazine was initially published on a monthly basis and featured advertisements, news, and reviews related to the phonograph and gramophone industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over time, the magazine became a leading trade publication for the phonograph industry, covering the latest developments in technology as well as providing business advice for phonograph dealers. The magazine was published until 1928, at which point it was absorbed by another publication, Music Trades.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As a dedicated trade publication, The Talking Machine World covered a wide range of topics related to the phonograph and gramophone industry. In addition to news and reviews, the magazine also featured analytical articles, interviews with industry leaders, and advertisements for new products.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notably, The Talking Machine World was one of the first magazines to cover the development of electrical recording technology, which revolutionized the industry in the 1920s.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Impact and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Talking Machine World played a significant role in the early phonograph industry, providing a valuable resource for manufacturers, dealers, and enthusiasts. The magazine helped to promote and popularize the phonograph as a cultural artifact and helped to spur innovation and competition within the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, The Talking Machine World was one of the first magazines to embrace the idea of a specialized trade publication. The success of the magazine helped to spur the growth of other trade publications in a variety of industries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Conclusion' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Talking Machine World was a influential magazine dedicated to the phonograph and gramophone industry. It was an early pioneer in the world of specialized trade publications and helped to promote and popularize the phonograph as a cultural artifact. While it ceased publication in 1928, its influence can still be seen in the world of music technology today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Tall Timber Short Lines
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Tall Timber Short Lines', N'tall-timber-short-lines', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A quarterly magazine focused on the logging and timber industry. Advocated for sustainable forest management and promoted scientific research in the field.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tall Timber Short Lines was a magazine for the logging and timber industry. It was published in the United States from 1958 to 1994.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tall Timber Short Lines was first published in 1958 by the Tall Timbers Research Station, a non-profit organization dedicated to the study and management of natural resources in the southeastern United States. The magazine was initially published on a quarterly basis and covered a wide range of topics related to the logging and timber industry, including new technologies, industry news, and articles on sustainable forestry practices.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over time, Tall Timber Short Lines became a leading publication in the logging and timber industry, with a particular focus on the southeastern United States. The magazine was published until 1994, at which point it was replaced by a new publication, The Longleaf Alliance Newsletter.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Tall Timber Short Lines covered a wide range of topics related to the logging and timber industry. In addition to news and reviews, the magazine also featured analytical articles, interviews with industry leaders, and advertisements for new products.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notably, the magazine was particularly focused on promoting sustainable forestry practices. It was a strong advocate for the conservation and management of natural resources, and regularly featured articles on scientific research related to the industry.' + C