VALUES ( N'Psychoanalysis', N'psychoanalysis', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription 1955 four-issue comic series from EC Comics emphasizing therapy and mental health narratives.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Psychoanalysis** is a noteworthy four-issue comic book series published by EC Comics in 1955 as part of their New Direction line. The exceptional series is widely respected for its themed narrative which centers on the therapy and internal struggles of its characters.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Release and Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The series, while short-lived, spanned four issues from June to December 1955. Each issue of Psychoanalysis introduced readers to three patients - Fred, Ellen, and Mark - each struggling with a distinct issue. Their therapies were overseen by the central character, an unnamed psychoanalyst.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Fred''s narratives explored his feelings of inadequacy, Mark''s delved into anger issues stemming from early-life traumas, and Ellen''s narratives comprehensively dealt with issues of self-doubt and lack of confidence.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Creative Team' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Psychoanalysis collected a highly proficient creative team, which included Al Feldstein as the writer and creator, the legendary artist Jack Kamen as the principal illustrator, and Bill Gaines as the editor.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Reception and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite the progressive and unparalleled focus on mental health and therapy, Psychoanalysis was commercially unsuccessful during its release. The reception was tepid, resulting in the discontinuation of the series after only four issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, the comics'' proactive approach of dealing with mental health issues has earned them considerable recognition and retrospection in the years following its initial release. Psychoanalysis has been discussed and analyzed by comic theorists and critics for its daring and unique narrative exploration of therapy and mental health, which was largely uncharted in the comic world during the 1950s.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Psychotronic Video
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Psychotronic Video', N'psychotronic-video', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Film magazine focused on exploitation, B-movies, and cult films, published in the United States from 1989-2006.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Psychotronic Video** was a film magazine published in the United States that focused on exploitation films, B-movies, and cult films. The magazine offered movie reviews, interviews, and commentaries on the lesser-explored genres of film in the popular media. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Origins and Publication' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Psychotronic Video was conceived by Michael J. Weldon in 1980 who, inspired by his fascination with unusual and subversive cinema, decided to establish a dedicated platform for these genres. Originally, it began as the *Psychotronic TV* show in 1980 before transitioning into a magazine format in 1989.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine covered a wide range of film genres that mainstream film criticism often sidelined, including horror, science fiction, action, grindhouse, and more. It was renowned for showcasing discussions and reviews on films typically deemed as ''trash cinema'', introducing them to a wider audience who revelled in the non-traditional.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Notable Contributors' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of Psychotronic Video offered readers a unique blend of reviews, retrospectives, interviews with directors, actors, and creators, and articles exploring themes and trends prevalent in cult classics and rarely-explored genres.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Michael J. Weldon served as the major contributor, editor, and critic in writing reviews, conducting interviews, and shaping the voice of the magazine. His contributions, combined with those of other B-movie enthusiasts and industry insiders, gave the magazine its unique identity and appeal.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Discontinuation' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After 41 issues, the magazine ceased production in 2006, leaving behind a stellar legacy. It is remembered for its extensive coverage of films from the periphery of mainstream cinema, thereby offering a platform for often overlooked genres and narratives.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Finished.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Ptolemaic Terrascope
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Ptolemaic Terrascope', N'ptolemaic-terrascope', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription British music magazine known for psychedelic rock content and hosting Terrastock festivals; active since 1989.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Ptolemaic Terrascope** is a British music magazine that has been catering to the interests of psychedelic rock enthusiasts since its inception in 1989. The publication is revered for its coverage of lesser-known bands and its affiliation with the Terrastock festivals.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Origins and Publication' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Ptolemaic Terrascope was founded in 1989 by Nick Saloman, the mainstay of the psychedelic band The Bevis Frond, and Phil McMullen. The magazine came into being as a platform to support several underground psychedelic and garage bands that didn''t get much attention in mainstream media. It was published on a roughly quarterly schedule, offering interviews, record reviews, and retrospective pieces on obscure bands of yesteryears.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Notable Contributors' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its run, the Ptolemaic Terrascope featured extensive articles, interviews, and reviews. It has covered an array of underground rock genres, including but not limited to psychedelic rock, acid rock, space rock, and garage rock. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Nick Saloman and Phil McMullen were the lead contributors to the content of the magazine, providing in-depth analyses and reviews, and conducting interviews with several musicians and bands while maintaining the grassroots ethos of the magazine.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Terrastock Festivals' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Beyond its publishing activities, the Ptolemaic Terrascope is well known for the Terrastock festivals, a series of music festivals that took place in various locations around the world. The festivals were an extension of the magazine''s promotion of lesser-known rock bands and were acclaimed for bringing together a wide range of underground rock bands in the spirit of psych music.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Change in Format' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After a brief hiatus, the print version of the magazine was discontinued, and it was relaunched as an online entity in 2005. It continues to serve its niche readership with an eclectic mix of rock music reviews, interviews, and articles.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Puck
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Puck', N'puck', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription First successful U.S. humor magazine, known for its political satire and colorful cartoons; published from 1871 to 1918.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Puck** was the first successful humor magazine in the United States that offered colourful cartoons, caricatures, and political satire of the issues of the day. It was published from 1871 until 1918 from its head office situated in St. Louis, before moving to New York City.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Ownership' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Established by Joseph Keppler, an Austrian-born cartoonist, Puck was initially published in German, with an English-language edition commencing two years later in 1877. The magazine was named after the character of Puck from William Shakespeare''s "A Midsummer Night''s Dream".' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The ownership of Puck eventually passed to Joseph Keppler, Jr., who continued the magazine''s traditions for almost a decade after his father''s death in 1894. In 1917, Puck was sold to William Randolph Hearst who chose not to maintain the magazine, ending its publication in September 1918.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Influence' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Puck is best known for its political cartoons and satirical humor. The cartoons played a critical role during the Presidential elections and other political events, providing commentary on issues relevant to the time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was composed of 16 pages of satirical articles and cartoons, and it used chromolithography to create vibrant, multi-color prints. It regularly featured artwork by noteworthy cartoonists of the day such as Louis Dalrymple, Bernhard Gillam, and Frank Nankivell.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the annals of American satire, Puck is renowned for its daring, incisive, humorous, and well-drawn cartoons. Its legacy lasted well into the 20th century as it influenced generations of American humor and satire publications that followed, effectively setting the stage for modern topical satire.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Puerto Rico Ilustrado
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Puerto Rico Ilustrado', N'puerto-rico-ilustrado', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Weekly Puerto Rican magazine promoting cultural and intellectual growth, featuring diverse content; published from 1910 to 1954.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Puerto Rico Ilustrado**, a weekly magazine from Puerto Rico, was in publication from 1910 to 1954. The magazine was instrumental in showcasing the artistic and cultural growth of Puerto Rico during those years.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Ownership' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was founded under the impetus of Ramón Alcalá Iglesias, José Coll Vidal, and Manuel Gómez Meléndez. They envisaged a space for literary, artistic, scientific, and popular works where Puerto Ricans could voice their thoughts. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine folded in 1954 due to the various modernizing political and cultural transformations happening on the island.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Influence' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Puerto Rico Ilustrado served as a platform for rich social, cultural, and intellectual exchange in Puerto Rico throughout its publication duration. The magazine regularly featured articles, essays, reviews, short stories, and poetry. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A significant portion of the magazine was also dedicated to graphic arts, popularizing caricatures and cartoons with political and social commentary. Many renowned authors and artists, like José de Diego and Julio L. de Vizcarrondo, contributed to the magazine, marking it as an essential chronicle of the island''s intellectual and cultural history.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Puerto Rico Ilustrado allowed various Puerto Rican thinkers, artists, and intellectuals to showcase their work over the span of nearly five decades. The magazine stands as an important record of Puerto Rico''s cultural and political history during the early to mid-twentieth century.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Pulp
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Pulp', N'pulp', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription US manga anthology showcasing adult-oriented Japanese comics and cultural content; in publication from 1997 to 2002.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Pulp**, also known as `Viz` or `Viz Comics`, was a manga anthology magazine issued in the United States from 1997 to 2002. Pulp was an influential platform in shaping western perception of manga and illustrating its potential as a medium for adult readers.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Ownership' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Launched by Viz Media, Pulp catered to mature readers with seinen manga (geared towards young adult men), josei manga (geared towards young adult women), and unique titles that went on to gain cult followings. The magazine was deemed a bold experiment in the US market, primarily focused on a younger audience, but it was eventually discontinued after 46 issues in August 2002.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Influence' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Pulp featured experimental and cutting-edge content, with series such as `Banana Fish`, `Dance till Tomorrow`, `Even a Monkey Can Draw Manga`, and `Uzumaki`. Several serialized series from the magazine have subsequently been published as standalone books.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to manga series, Pulp also included reviews, interviews, articles, and Japan-related features addressing topics such as the Yakuza, prostitution, and the popularity of Pachinko. Its tone was often irreverent and edgy, with a focus on the grittier, more adult side of Japanese popular culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its relatively short lifespan, Pulp played a significant role in introducing adult-oriented manga to the Western world. It paved the way for the distribution and acceptance of the wider spectrum of manga genres in the United States.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Pulp and Paper
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Pulp and Paper', N'pulp-and-paper', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription North American publication covering the pulp, paper, and allied industries with industry insights and tech updates since 1902.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Pulp and Paper** is a prominent North American magazine that caters to the pulp, paper, and allied industries. First established in 1902, the magazine offers a broad scope of coverage pertinent to the paper-making industry.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Ownership' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Pulp and Paper was created by R.R. Donnelley & Sons, an American company that is a global leader in communication and marketing solutions. The motivation was to streamline and unite the nascent pulp and paper industry by providing a space for professionals to share knowledge, research, and experiences.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Coverage' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine provides comprehensive coverage of the industry, with features on new technology, products, management techniques, research, and many of the critical issues affecting the pulp and paper industry. Regular columns include topics such as maintenance, safety, sustainability, energy, mill profiles, and industry insights from well-known experts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Pulp and Paper publishes both a print and online version, with the latter offering digital editions, industry news, and special reports to its global audience. The audience comprises mill management, corporate executives, paper and packaging buyers, and allied suppliers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Pulp and Paper has been a consistent source of knowledge and inspiration for industry professionals throughout its history. It continues to adapt with the sector''s growing needs, reflecting the shifts in industry practices, challenges, and innovations.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Pulse!
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Pulse!', N'pulse', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American music magazine from 1983 to 2002, featuring diverse genres, artist interviews, and record reviews from notable contributors.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Pulse!** was a significant American music magazine that was in print from 1983 through 2002. As part of the Tower Records brand, Pulse! played a crucial role in shaping American music journalism in the late 20th century.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Ownership' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Published by Tower Records, an international retail music franchise based in Sacramento, California, Pulse! began as a monthly periodical distributed freely at Tower Records outlets. The core idea was to stimulate interest and excitement about music amongst the public.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Coverage' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'At their peak, Pulse! printed 400,000 copies per month, discussing a broad spectrum of music genres including rock, pop, hip-hop, and electronic music. Each issue had a mix of record reviews, interviews with artists, feature pieces, and columns from in-house and freelance writers. The magazine became especially well known for its Editor''s Picks, a monthly review section presenting unique, often overlooked albums.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Notable Contributors' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Pulse! was notable for the quality of its contributors. Some of the celebrated music journalists who wrote for Pulse! include Gina Arnold, famous for her work on California rock and punk, and Dave Marsh, co-founded of Creem magazine and author of numerous books on rock and roll.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although Pulse! magazine ceased publication in 2002 when Tower Records filed for bankruptcy, the influence of the magazine lived on. It fostered a generation of music journalists, contributing significantly to the critique and appreciation of all music genres.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Punk
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Punk', N'punk', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Influential American music magazine (1976-1979), known for promoting and defining the punk rock movement through its raw imagery and critique.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Punk** was an influential American music magazine that played a pivotal role in the punk rock movement. Published from 1976 to 1979, Punk was both a reflection of and catalyst for the flourishing punk scene in New York City and beyond.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Ownership' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Launched by John Holmstrom, Ged Dunn, and Legs McNeil in 1975, Punk started as a homemade fanzine to channel their appreciation for music that was raw, gritty, and, above all, real. The name ''punk'' was chosen as a descriptive term to encapsulate this new wave of music.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Coverage' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Punk was renowned for its unpolished aesthetic and irreverent humor, blending elements of underground comic artwork with serious music criticism. It covered bands such as The Ramones, The Sex Pistols, and Blondie before they achieved mainstream success. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Along with band interviews and album reviews, Punk was distinctive for its unique comic book-like format, a nod to the underground comix that inspired Holmstrom. Holmstrom himself created many of Punk''s comics, while also contributing hyperbolic, often humorous album reviews.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Cultural Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The influence of Punk extended beyond its music coverage. Its raw aesthetic and irreverent tone became synonymous with the punk rock movement itself. Punk was instrumental in promoting punk bands and cultivating their image, thus playing a vital role in defining punk rock to a broader audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Revivals' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Punk''s publication ceased in 1979, but its spirit lived on through several revival efforts. In the late 1980s, Holmstrom relaunched Punk, printing two new issues. Yet again, in 2001 and 2007, two more issues were released, further establishing Punk''s lasting legacy in the music world.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Punk Planet
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Punk Planet', N'punk-planet', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American bi-monthly magazine (1994-2007) known for in-depth coverage of punk rock music, independent culture, and socio-political issues.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Punk Planet** was a distinctive American music and politics magazine that provided a platform for the voices of the underground punk scene. Published bi-monthly from 1994 until 2007, Punk Planet was more than just a music magazine; it was an integral part of the DIY (Do It Yourself) culture of the punk community.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Ownership' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Punk Planet was the brainchild of Daniel Sinker, who started the magazine in 1994 while still attending college. Based out of Chicago, Illinois, Punk Planet was an independently published zine run by a small team, emphasizing its dedication to the DIY ethos of the punk scene it served.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Coverage' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Punk Planet published 80 issues during its 13-year run, covering topics that stretched the boundaries of a traditional music magazine. Not only did it feature interviews with punk rock bands and reviews of independent records, but it also spotlighted lesser-known and unsigned bands, providing them a platform to gain recognition.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, Punk Planet did not shy away from political and social issues. The magazine frequently published pieces on gender issues, race relations, class struggles, and other socio-political topics that resonated with its readers'' attitudes and sensibilities.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Impact and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Punk Planet was highly regarded within the punk community and beyond for its unwavering commitment to independent music and its bold confrontations of societal issues. The magazine''s in-depth, critical coverage of the increasingly commercialized punk scene was particularly appreciated by its readers. While Punk Planet ceased publication in 2007 due to financial difficulties, its impact on punk culture and independent journalism endures.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Punk Rock Confidential
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Punk Rock Confidential', N'punk-rock-confidential', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American punk rock magazine (1998-2001), celebrated for comprehensive coverage of pop-punk music, art, fashion, and related counter-culture.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Punk Rock Confidential** was an influential American punk rock magazine that gained popularity during the late 90s and early 2000s. The magazine played an important role in chronicling the punk rock scene, specifically the pop-punk subgenre and its related counter-culture.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Operation' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Punk Rock Confidential was founded in 1998 by Shredder, a former columnist for Maximum Rock and Roll magazine, and Janelle Hessig, a well-known figure in the zine community. It was headquartered in San Francisco, California, and run by an enthusiastic team dedicated to punk''s DIY (Do It Yourself) ethos.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Coverage' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Punk Rock Confidential was characterized by its extensive coverage of pop-punk bands, both well-known and emerging. The magazine emphasized album reviews, band interviews, as well as reports from international punk scenes. More than just a music magazine, Punk Rock Confidential also featured articles focusing on punk culture, fashion, and art, significantly contributing to the discourse of the scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Cease of Publication' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its run, Punk Rock Confidential was highly respected for its meticulous coverage and passionate devotion to the punk rock scene. It was appreciated for fostering the pop-punk genre and providing a platform for punk artists. Unfortunately, despite its importance and popularity in the punk community, Punk Rock Confidential ceased publication in 2001 due to financial issues.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Purchasing
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Purchasing', N'purchasing', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American procurement-focused magazine (1933-2010), providing insight into purchasing trends, supply management, and market analysis.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Purchasing** was a key industry resource in North America that provided in-depth information and perspectives on the purchasing and supply management sector. Originally print-based, the magazine transitioned to an online format during its history to better serve a growing digital audience. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Operation' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Established in 1933, Purchasing Magazine was the go-to source for information on procurement trends, market trends, price indexes, and product news for supply managers and corporate executives. Its headquarters were located in Boston, Massachusetts, and it was published by Reed Business Information, a notable business-to-business communication services provider.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Coverage' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its years of operation, Purchasing Magazine provided thorough coverage of topics relevant to purchasing and supply chain professionals. It published articles of interest on subjects like strategic sourcing, supply chain management, global purchasing strategies, procurement technologies, and cost management techniques. It also delivered data about price movements, commodities forecasts, and other valuable procurement data.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Digital Transition and Ceasing of Publication' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In response to the changing media consumption habits of its audience, Purchasing Magazine transitioned from print to an online publication, Purchasing.com, in the early 2000s. The digital platform not only incorporated traditional magazine features but also added real-time news updates, webinars, and other digital resources for its readers. However, in 2010 Reed Business Information announced the closure of Purchasing Magazine/Purchasing.com due to strategic reasons.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Pyramid
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Pyramid', N'pyramid', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American gaming magazine (1993-2020) focusing on role-playing games, published by Steve Jackson Games, both in print and online.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Pyramid** was an American magazine focused primarily on recreational gaming, published by Steve Jackson Games. It encompassed a vast range of games including role-playing games (RPGs), card games, board games, and miniature games, among other game types.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Founding and Operation' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Pyramid was initiated by Scott Haring, then the managing editor of Steve Jackson Games, in 1993. The magazine’s main office was in Austin, Texas. For its first ten years, it was a print publication before transitioning to an online-only format in 2008.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Coverage' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its print era, Pyramid covered a wide variety of gaming topics. The magazine included game reviews, session reports, design tips, and industry news. Additionally, Pyramid often published exclusive content for popular Steve Jackson games such as GURPS, In Nomine, and the Illuminati card game.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After the switch to a digital format, Pyramid narrowed its focus more strongly on content relevant to Steve Jackson Games'' products, particularly GURPS. Each digital issue usually focused on a specific theme, such as horror gaming, superpowered gaming, or tactical gaming, providing articles, scenarios, and other game resources related to the theme.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Digital Transition and Ceasing of Publication' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After its transition to online publication in 2008, Pyramid continued as a monthly magazine, downloadable in PDF format. This digital version lasted for about twelve more years until Steve Jackson Games announced in July 2020 that Pyramid would no longer be published. This marked the end of a prominent chapter in the gaming community.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Quantum
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Quantum', N'quantum', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Scientific educational magazine (1990-2001), joint venture of NSTA and Russian Academy of Sciences, focusing on high school physics.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Quantum** is an educational, scientifically rigorous magazine for students and teachers of high school physics. It is a collaborative effort between the National Science Teachers Association (NSTA) in the United States and the Russian Academy of Sciences. Predatorially, it was a joint publication with Scientific American.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Origin and Mission' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Quantum was launched in 1990 as an initiative to make Russian physics readily accessible to American students and teachers. Educators quickly recognized the value in Quantum''s pedagogical approach, blending strict scientific accuracy with engaging educational materials. The magazine remains devoted to providing a deep understanding of physical phenomena and principles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Contributions ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s contents involve in-depth articles on physics topics, engaging illustrations, interactive puzzles, and discussions on modern research and discoveries in physics. Contributions integrated text from leading physicists, including several Nobel Prize-winners. Topics ranged from classical physics, quantum mechanics, to physics history and philosophy.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publishing details ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was published bi-monthly until 2001, when it shifted to a quarterly publication. The contents were peer-reviewed to ensure technical accuracy and pedagogical efficacy. The magazine existed in both English and Russian, yet the Russian version ceased publishing in 2002.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The detailed articles and extensive range of topics covered in Quantum have often been used in teaching curricula. Its legacy lives on through its significant influence on physics education, though the magazine ceased publication in 2001.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Quarterly Review of Wines
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Quarterly Review of Wines', N'quarterly-review-of-wines', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American wine publication (1977-2012), known for independent reviews and influence in the wine industry, founded by Richard Elia.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Quarterly Review of Wines** (QRW) was an American wine magazine acclaimed for its comprehensive coverage of international wines and wineries. Founded in 1977 by Richard Elia, it emphasized high-quality, independent wine reviews and served as a critical guide for both casual wine enthusiasts and industry professionals.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publishing History and Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded and headquartered in Massachusetts, the magazine was a pioneer in its field, enjoying a long-standing presence of over 35 years. Each issue of the QRW presented meticulous evaluations of wines, providing readers with trustworthy ratings and in-depth tasting notes.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Foregoing advertisements, it featured interviews with notable personalities in the wine industry, articles on wine-related travel, and discussions on emerging wine trends. Its acclaimed section, "Best of the Best", spotlighted exceptional wines that offered both high quality and value.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Distribution and Recognition' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The QRW reached a global audience with distribution across the United States and international locations. It was sold in bookstores and wine shops, and was also available through direct subscription.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'QRW enjoyed widespread recognition for its independence and quality of content. It was lauded by the New York Times and awarded ''Best Wine Publication'' by the James Beard Foundation in 1995.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Closing of Publication' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Quarterly Review of Wines ceased publication in 2012. Richard Elia attributed the termination to economic hardships and the changing media landscape. However, the legacy of QRW continues to influence the discourse of wine criticism and appreciation.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Race Traitor
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Race Traitor', N'race-traitor', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription US journal (1993-2005) advocating for the abolition of whiteness as a social construct, co-edited by Noel Ignatiev and John Garvey.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Race Traitor** was a periodical journal that pushed boundaries in the discussion of race and politics within the United States. First issued in 1993, and co-edited by Noel Ignatiev and John Garvey, it advocated for the elimination of the white racial category as a social construct, challenging traditional notions of race and identity.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Ideology and Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Race Traitor''s stated objective was "the abolition of whiteness". The editors proposed that whiteness was not based on skin color but was a social category established and maintained for the privilege of certain groups. The publication argued that ''treason'' to this racial category was a positive act - hence the provocative name: Race Traitor.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The journal spawned a movement and kindled discussion around these themes, inspiring scholarly studies and leading to courses in colleges and universities across the United States. It coined influential concepts such as "white privilege" and "white skin privilege."' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its academic leanings, Race Traitor was not a strictly scholarly journal, featuring a mixture of essays, articles, letters, reviews, and documentation. It claimed a new look at race, which carried political implications, leading it to occasionally draw controversy and significant critique.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Its unique perspective led to the Harvard Educational Review recognizing Race Traitor for ''Outstanding Contribution to Education'', and the Utne Reader naming it ''one of 15 publications that could shake the world''.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Published by Routledge, Race Traitor ceased putting out issues in 2005 but remained available online. Essays and select works from the journal were compiled into a book form titled ''Race Traitor'' published in 1996, also edited by Ignatiev and Garvey.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Radar Online
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Radar Online', N'radar-online', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American digital news platform known for celebrity gossip, entertainment news and investigative journalism pieces.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Radar Online** is a digital news platform based in the United States, providing an in-depth look into celebrity lives, gossip, and scandals. First launched as a print and online publication in 2003 by Maer Roshan, it was then re-launched solely as an online publication in 2008 under American Media, Inc.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content Focus' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With a strong emphasis on entertainment and celebrity news, Radar Online leans towards sensationalism and tabloid-style journalism. Its coverage spans pop culture topics such as celebrity scandals, Hollywood gossip, reality show controversies, and high-profile legal issues. The website also occasionally dives into hard news and features investigative journalism pieces.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Corporate and Ownership History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Radar Online started as a print magazine funded by Mortimer Zuckerman, billionaire owner of the *New York Daily News*. It produced three issues before ceasing print publications in 2005. In 2008, American Media, Inc acquired the brand, re-launching it as an online-only celebrity news outlet. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2019, American Media, Inc sold Radar Online to a company associated with digital publisher and broadcaster, TheMaven. As of 2021, the website continues to be operational.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Reception and Influence' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Radar Online has earned notoriety for breaking major celebrity-related scandals, such as the Mel Gibson tapes scandal and behind the scenes footage of the *Dog Whisperer* TV show. However, the site''s tabloid nature and its tendencies for overly-emphasizing the more scandalous aspects of stories have drawn criticism. Despite this, the website enjoys wide readership in the English-speaking world.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Radio & Records
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Radio & Records', N'radio-and-records', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American trade publication (1973-2009) focused on the radio and music industries, renowned for its music charts and analyses.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Radio & Records** (R&R) was an American trade publication providing news and information related to the radio and music industries. Founded by Bob Wilson, the magazine operated from 1973 until 2009. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content Focus ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Radio & Records covered a wide range of topics from industry news, trends, charts, new music reviews, to ratings and programming strategies. The publication had a significant influence, being viewed as an essential resource within the radio and record industries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Corporate and Ownership History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first issue of R&R was published in 1973. The founder, Bob Wilson, had a vision to create a platform that would unite radio programming and the record business in a synergistic medium. In 2006, VNU/Neilson Business Media, the parent company of Billboard magazine, acquired R&R. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Suspension & Legacy ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In June 2009, the final edition of the publication was released. The closure came alongside Nielsen Business Media''s decision to consolidate their music industry brands. After the discontinuation of the publication, the R&R''s features and data were integrated into the Billboard.biz website. Despite dissolution, the impact of Radio & Records on the American radio and music industries remains significant, as it contributed to the marketing and exposure of new music and influential programming strategies.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Radio Mirror
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Radio Mirror', N'radio-mirror', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription U.S. magazine (1933-1977) offering in-depth coverage of radio and television stars, shows, and behind-the-scenes stories.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Radio Mirror** was a prominent American magazine that focused on radio and later television stars and programs. Beginning its history in the early 1930s, the magazine offered listeners detailed insights into the lives of their favorite radio personalities and behind-the-scenes stories about popular radio shows.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Coverage and Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Known for extensive artist profiles, exclusive interviews, and in-depth reporting, Radio Mirror catered to audiences who were avid radio listeners. As television began to proliferate, the magazine adapted its content to include television stars and shows as well. The magazine was well-known for its pictorial features and candid photographs of prominent radio and television figures. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Radio Mirror was first published in 1933 by Macfadden Publications, an American publishing company specializing in popular magazine. Macfadden Publications was founded by Bernarr Macfadden, a notable figure in American journalism. The name of the magazine changed to **TV-Radio Mirror** in 1953 reflecting the rising popularity of television during that era. The magazine was later renamed **TV Mirror** in the 1960s.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Readership and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine held widespread appeal among an audience that was deeply engrossed in the entertainment industry, particularly radio and television. It notably played a part in shaping the public''s perception of radio and television programs, and their stars. Though the publication ceased operation in 1977, its contribution to the documentation of radio and television history remains significant.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Radio News
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Radio News', N'radio-news', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American publication (1919-1959) focused on radio technology, amateur radio operations, industry news, and advancements.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Radio News** was a leading American magazine dedicated to the amateur radio audience, with its content focusing on radio technology and its advancements. The publication, launched in 1919, served as an educational resource and news platform for radio enthusiasts and professionals alike. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content Orientation ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Published monthly, Radio News presented a plethora of articles, tutorials, and news on various aspects of radio technology. The magazine''s content included everything from detailed circuit diagrams and construction projects for amateur radio operators, to industry news, equipment reviews, and innovations in radio science.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Experimenter Publishing, owned by the pioneering publishing entrepreneur Hugo Gernsback, launched the first issue of Radio News. It was originally titled as "Radio Amateur News" but was shortly renamed to "Radio News". Gernsback''s passion for science and technology, especially radio and broadcasting, clearly reflected in the magazine''s content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1929, ownership of the magazine changed hands from Gernsback to John F. Rider Publisher, and subsequently, it was sold to Ziff-Davis in the mid-1950s. The magazine continued under Ziff-Davis until 1959, when it was absorbed into **Electronics World**.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy and Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Radio News played a crucial role in educating and informing the ever-growing community of radio enthusiasts during the first half of the 20th century. The magazine is recognized for its contributions to the popularization and understanding of radio technology. Despite its discontinuation, back issues of Radio News remain valuable resources for those interested in the history and evolution of radio technology.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Radio-Electronics
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Radio-Electronics', N'radio-electronics', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American publication (1929-1999) featuring topics on electronic theory, hardware reviews, projects, industry trends and news.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Radio-Electronics** was a significant American electronics magazine that was first published in 1929. The publication centered around electronic topics, providing comprehensive material for hobbyists, electronics enthusiasts, and professionals in the field.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Influence' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Radio-Electronics offered a plethora of information from fundamental electronics theory to advanced semiconductor technology. The magazine''s content arrayed from hardware and software reviews, detailed schematics and tutorials for a variety of electronics projects, to interviews with industry leaders and news on technology trends.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine played an instrumental role in significant electronics innovations, promising new designs and concepts to its readership. The most known among them is the first personal computer, the Mark-8, whose design was first introduced to the public in Radio-Electronics'' July 1974 issue.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Initially launched under the banner "Radio-Craft" by inventor and magazine publisher Hugo Gernsback, the magazine changed its name to "Radio-Electronics" in 1948, reflecting its expanded scope with ever-evolving electronics technologies.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication underwent another significant change in 1959, under the editorship of Oliver P. Ferrell, transitioning from a hobbyist''s guide to a professional electronics magazine. Ziff-Davis, a prominent publishing company, purchased Radio-Electronics in 1980.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'It continued its publication until 1999 under various titles, including **Electronics Now** and **Poptronics**, as it adapted to changing technological currents.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Ragtime Ephemeralist
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Ragtime Ephemeralist', N'the-ragtime-ephemeralist', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American periodical (1998-2012) dedicated to ragtime music history, musicians, criticism, and sheet music; crafted by Chris Ware.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Ragtime Ephemeralist** was a print-only periodical dedicated to the music, culture, and history of ragtime music. The endeavour was a solo project by the cartoonist and author, Chris Ware, further highlighting his diverse creative pursuits. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Influence' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Ragtime Ephemeralist covered various aspects of ragtime music and culture. It primarily presented thorough studies of prominent ragtime composers and musicians, reviving the oft-lost history of the music genre. The magazine also featured essays, criticism, and sheet music, expanding the depth of content offered to subscribers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Chris Ware himself contributed to a significant portion of the magazine''s editorials and graphical design, establishing the publication''s distinctive and acclaimed aesthetic. Additionally, Ware published a comic strip in the magazine titled "Quimby the Mouse."' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The inaugural issue of The Ragtime Ephemeralist was first released in 1998. Due to the nature of the publishing effort — essentially a one-man operation — the frequency of its release was sporadic, with only three issues released over a fourteen-year span. The second issue came out in 2002, and the third, which would turn out to be the final, appeared in 2012.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In terms of distribution, The Ragtime Ephemeralist was available for purchase mainly at cartoon and music conventions.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Raijin Comics
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Raijin Comics', N'raijin-comics', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American manga anthology (2002-2004) publishing English translations of Japanese manga; included video game and anime news.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Raijin Comics** was an American manga anthology that provided translated versions of various Japanese manga series to the English-speaking audience. The anthology was the cornerstone of the publication efforts of Raijin Comics'' parent company, Gutsoon! Entertainment.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Lineup' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The anthology''s lineup featured several popular manga series covering different genres, ranging from action to sports. Some of the more prominent titles included **Fist of the Blue Sky**, a prequel to the renowned manga series *Fist of the North Star*, and **City Hunter**, a popular action-comedy manga.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Raijin Comics also included a separate section, **Raijin Game & Anime**, which provided news and reviews on Japanese video games and animation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Raijin Comics was first launched in December 2002 by Gutsoon! Entertainment, a company founded by Horie Nobuhiko, former Editor-in-Chief of Japanese manga publisher Weekly Shōnen Jump.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication sought to emulate the Japanese manga magazine model by being a weekly anthology. However, due to insufficient demand, Raijin Comics switched to a monthly format in September 2003.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Unfortunately, declining sales led to Gutsoon! Entertainment discontinuing the print version of Raijin Comics in July 2004. For a brief period following this, Gutsoon! tried to keep the magazine alive digitally on their website, but this initiative also ended by the close of 2004.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Railroad Gazette
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Railroad Gazette', N'railroad-gazette', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American trade publication (1870-present) focused on railway operations and technology; now known as ''Railway Age''.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Railroad Gazette** was a prominent American trade publication focusing on railway operations and technology. Its targeted readership consisted of various professionals within the railway industry, from infrastructure engineers to train operators.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The core of the magazine focused on providing in-depth analysis and discussion about the latest railway techniques, technologies, and infrastructural developments. It offered features on topics like track layouts, railway construction projects, engine designs, timetabling, and other technical aspects. Profiles and interviews with leading figures in the railway industry also featured prominently within the publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Railroad Gazette was established in 1870 and published weekly. During its tenure, the magazine became a must-read for railway professionals due to its insightful coverage of the ever-evolving railway landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1908, the publication underwent a change in name to **Railway Age Gazette**, after having absorbed the competing magazine *The Railway Age*. This merger sought to consolidate the readership and strengthen the magazine''s standing in the railroad industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication continued operations under various names and publishers throughout the 20th century until it became today''s **Railway Age** magazine, still providing dedicated coverage of railway news, trends, and technological advancements in North America.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Railroads Illustrated
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Railroads Illustrated', N'railroads-illustrated', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American periodical focused on North American railroads, showcasing industry news, high-quality photography, and regional studies.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Railroads Illustrated** is a prestigious American magazine centered on railroading, particularly focusing on North American railroading photography and news.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine provides its readers with a thorough look at North American railroading by featuring comprehensive pictorial studies of individual railroads and the regions they serve. The main draw for many readers is the high-quality photography that provides an immersive view into the world of railroads.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Apart from featuring notable lines and locations, Railroads Illustrated continuously updates its readers with the latest news and developments in the railroad industry, and showcases the works of various railroad photographers, both professional and amateur.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Railroads Illustrated was initially launched under the name **CTC Board** in 1974 by Hundman Publishing. The name CTC Board was derived from Centralized Traffic Control, a signifying element of the railroads system. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2005, it underwent a branding change, taking on its current name, in an attempt to articulate more clearly the magazine''s photographic focus. The magazine, now published by White River Productions, has grown to become a respected and indispensable resource for railroading enthusiasts and professionals alike.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- R&R Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'R&R Magazine', N'r-and-r-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Former trade publication for broadcasting industry with radio news, music trends, promotion events coverage, and detailed airplay charts.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**R&R** (also known as **Radio & Records**) was a well-regarded trade publication in the broadcasting industry based in the United States.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'R&R was a veritable source of information and analysis for industry professionals, featuring content such as radio and music industry news, promotional events coverage, along with industry-specific research and analysis. The magazine was also recognized for numerous charts, based upon airplay data collected from radio stations in various formats across the country.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'R&R began its journey in 1973, founded by Bob Wilson, with the aim of providing radio programming and music decision-makers with a platform that served as a barometer of the industry. R&R''s charts quickly gained prominence for their accuracy and comprehensiveness, making it a key resource amongst radio professionals.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over its history, R&R has shed light on the ever-changing landscape of the radio and records industry up until its final print issue in 2009. On June 5 of that same year, R&R''s online services also met their end following the closure notice issued by its then-parent company, Nielsen Business Media.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Ray Gun Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Ray Gun Magazine', N'ray-gun-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American alternative music and style magazine known for avant-garde design and influential coverage of the 1990s cultural scene.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Ray Gun** was a trailblazing American magazine that primarily focused on alternative music and style. The publication was renowned for its avant-garde typographic design and its distinguished coverage of the alternative music scene.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ray Gun gave extensive coverage to a wide range of artists and bands from the alternative music universe, including rock, grunge, pop, and electronica. Furthermore, the magazine dived into realms that extended beyond just music, including fashion, design, film, and lifestyle, thereby creating a comprehensive cultural source for its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While its genre-specific coverage was compelling, Ray Gun was perhaps most known for its distinctive and highly experimental graphic design, spearheaded by the art director David Carson. The dynamic and often unconventional design made use of distorted images, non-standard layouts, and varied typography, challenging the traditional norms of magazine design.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Launched in 1992 by Marvin Scott Jarrett, Ray Gun quickly rose through the ranks in the publishing world, making a name for itself in a relatively short period. The innovative graphic design elements by Carson caused the magazine to stand out among its contemporaries and even inspired a spin-off typographical style known as ''grunge typography.''' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The peak of Ray Gun''s popularity was in the mid-1990s, mirroring the rise of alternative music. However, like many music publications of the time, Ray Gun struggled as the 20th century ended, facing a changing music industry and shifting reader preferences. The magazine ceased publication in 2000 after 74 issues, leaving behind a vibrant and influential legacy.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Rays from the Rose Cross
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Rays from the Rose Cross', N'rays-from-the-rose-cross', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Bi-monthly American magazine focusing on Rosicrucian teachings, mysticism, metaphysics, and aspects of Christianity and Western Mystery Tradition.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Rays from the Rose Cross** is a bi-monthly American magazine concentrated on promoting the teachings of the Rosicrucian Order. The publication holds a profound history and continuously serves as an essential source for individuals interested in the spiritual and philosophical aspects of the Rosicrucian movement.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The focal points of this magazine include various themes associated with the Rosicrucian spiritual and philosophical traditions, such as mysticism, metaphysics, and divine wisdom. The periodical features articles that explain the philosophies of Max Heindel, founder of The Rosicrucian Fellowship, combining the principles of Christian concepts and insights derived from Western Mystery Tradition. Beyond these topics, the publication frequently discusses theosophy, astrology, interpretations of Bible, along with principles of health and healing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The creation of the Rays from the Rose Cross can be traced back to 1913, the brainchild of Max Heindel, a revered spiritual leader known for his Christian mystic teachings and as the founder of The Rosicrucian Fellowship. The fellowship is an international fraternity that aims to disseminate the principles and teachings aligned with Rosicrucianism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Since its inception, the magazine continues to be published under the stewardship of The Rosicrucian Fellowship, headquartered at Oceanside, California. It acts as a means to forward the Rosicrucian teachings, offering insights into spiritual evolution, esoteric wisdom, and self-realization.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Finished.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- RCR Wireless News
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'RCR Wireless News', N'rcr-wireless-news', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American portal providing coverage of global wireless and mobile industry news, trends, technologies, and market analysis.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**RCR Wireless News** is an influential and leading news source dedicated to the wireless and mobile industry. The magazine is based in the United States and holds a prominent space in the sphere of telecommunication news. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The content of RCR Wireless News is predominantly related to telecommunications and wireless technology. The portal covers a myriad of topics such as network infrastructure, wireless technology, applications, carriers, along with market trends and projections. The magazine also provides analytical insights, feature articles, expert interviews, and industry reports, thereby serving as a comprehensive news source for professionals, analysts, and stakeholders in the wireless industry. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'RCR Wireless News began its journey in 1981, playing a crucial role over the years by providing robust coverage of every major wireless event globally. The magazine has retained its reputation for the analysis and conveyance of critical information related to the wireless technology industry. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its publication history, RCR Wireless News has adapted to the continual evolution of the telecommunication industry and has become a go-to resource for professionals seeking up-to-date industry news, deep dives into technological developments, and critical market trend analysis. The magazine''s headquarters are in Austin, Texas.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Read
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Read', N'read', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American educational publication for middle and high school students, promoting literacy through engaging literary works.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Read** is an American educational magazine aimed at middle school and high school students, established with the intent to foster and advance the habit of reading in young people.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Designed to engage young readers from grades 6–10, the content of Read magazine encompasses a broad array of literary works. It features a mix of well-known classics, contemporary fiction, non-fiction, drama, and verse. Each issue includes a number of accompanying activities, quizzes, and discussion points that foster comprehension, vocabulary expansion, and a deeper understanding of the literary content. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine goes beyond literary exploration, often featuring cross-curricular links to history, science, art, and culture. This fusion of subjects offers readers an immersive learning experience, challenging them to apply their reading and comprehension skills across a variety of topics. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Read magazine is a publication of Weekly Reader, a renowned educational publisher, established in 1928. With its inception, Read reinforced Weekly Reader''s mission to ''get students to read'' by providing a compelling and exciting resource explicitly tailored to their educational needs and interests.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The legacy of the magazine is rooted in supporting literacy and learning in the classroom and beyond, creating a platform where students can interact with a wide range of literary styles and genres while enhancing their language skills. The magazine''s editorial offices are based in Mankato, Minnesota.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- ReadyMade
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'ReadyMade', N'readymade', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Bimonthly lifestyle magazine focused on DIY culture and creative, sustainable home improvement projects.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**ReadyMade** was an innovative bimonthly lifestyle magazine catering to the Do-it-yourself (DIY) culture. Based in the United States, the magazine sought to inspire readers with creative and sustainable home projects.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Focusing primarily on home improvement projects, interior design, arts, and crafts, ReadyMade was a treasure trove for individuals interested in personalizing their living spaces. It highlighted ingenious ideas for transforming everyday items into functional and aesthetic elements of home decor. Each edition brought awe-inspiring, imaginative, and environmentally-friendly DIY projects, step-by-step guides, artist profiles, and lifestyle articles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to the home-oriented DIY content, the magazine encompassed a variety of features such as book reviews, opinion pieces, recipes, gardening advice, and travel tips. The unique blend of lifestyle and DIY articles made the magazine a favorite among individuals craving creative inspiration.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'ReadyMade was founded in 2001 by graduates of the University of California at Berkeley, Grace Hawthorne and Shoshana Berger, who saw a gap in the market for contemporary DIY enthusiasts. The magazine catered to young homeowners by blending pop culture, design, and DIY project ideas in an offbeat, aesthetically pleasing format.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2006, ReadyMade was acquired by Meredith Corporation, a leading media and marketing company catering to American women. Despite its popularity and a circulation of approximately 325,000, the magazine ceased publication in 2011 due to financial struggles within the parent company.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Realist
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Realist', N'the-realist', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American magazine featuring radical journalism and satire, influential in challenging social and political norms.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Realist** was a pioneer in alternative journalism in America. Established by Paul Krassner in 1958, this magazine featured a mix of satire and radical journalism, challenging prevailing social and political norms of the time.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Bobbing and weaving between satire and serious journalism, The Realist was unafraid to confront controversial topics or challenge the boundaries of acceptable discourse. The magazine featured articles covering various subjects such as politics, culture, and societal issues, often providing a contrarian viewpoint from the mainstream.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Realist''s nature for being unapologetically uncensored is highlighted through its display of cartoons and satirical pieces, often of an incendiary nature. Its unorthodox, thought-provoking content, played an instrumental role in influencing a generation of satirical publications like National Lampoon and The Onion.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History  ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Realist was not affiliated with any corporate interest or advertising, leading to a sporadic publication schedule dictated by donations from its readership. Its publication, though primarily monthly, varied greatly over its existence.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Started in the era of the nationally-condoned McCarthyism, The Realist began to reach broad audiences during the countercultural movements of the 1960s. The magazine served as a platform for numerous notable personalities, including Norman Mailer, Ken Kesey, and Lenny Bruce, among others.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite facing significant challenges throughout its lifetime, The Realist managed to remain in publication until 2001, covering four decades of tumultuous American history in its distinctly unabashed style.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Record World
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Record World', N'record-world', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American music industry trade magazine, renowned for its charts and influential coverage of popular music trends.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Record World** was an American music industry trade magazine, that played an influential role in the world of popular music during its existence.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Record World primarily focused on the strategies, implications, and aesthetics of selling music. Each issue provided comprehensive coverage of a diverse assortment of genres and was renowned for its sales charts, which got compiled based on radio play, jukebox selections, and sales.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Record World had its roots in "Music Vendor", a periodical launched in 1954 intended for jukebox operators. It was renamed to Record World in 1964. The magazine provided a platform for industry professionals, including artists, record label executives, and music store owners, to keep abreast of trends and developments in the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine became groundbreaking in its recognition and coverage of disco, contributing significantly to the genre''s rise in popularity during the 1970s.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Record World''s charts were considered an industry standard alongside Billboard and Cash Box, before the magazine ceased publication in 1982 due to financial problems.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Redtape
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Redtape', N'redtape', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Influential underground magazine from 1980s, focused on New York''s punk and No wave scenes, showcasing non-conformist views.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Redtape** was an influential underground magazine that focused on the punk and No wave scenes in New York City during the 1980s.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Format and Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Redtape embodied the raw aesthetic and confrontational attitudes that became synonymous with the underground music and art scenes of the time. Its intentionally unconventional format often featured disjointed typesetting, grainy black and white imagery, and a layout that would shift between issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Redtape was renowned for its exploration of controversial themes and progressive viewpoints. It served as a platform for a generation of artists, musicians, writers, and activists expressing their non-conformist views.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Established in the heart of New York City''s East Village in 1982, Redtape was a collective endeavor. It was published on an approximately bimonthly basis, always striving to mirror the avant-garde spirit and rebellious ethos of the downtown scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its existence, the magazine showcased a myriad of performing artists, writers, and visual artists who were pioneering the burgeoning punk and No wave movements. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Sadly, Redtape’s publication ceased in the late 1980s, signifying the end of an era of the raw artistic expression that the magazine had so vividly captured and promoted.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Reform Judaism
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Reform Judaism', N'reform-judaism', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Publication of the Reform Judaism movement, presenting a broad range of topics relevant to Reform Jews since 1972.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Reform Judaism** is a widely read magazine of the Reform Judaism movement in the United States and worldwide. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine presents a broad range of topics relevant to Reform Jews, such as Jewish theology, liturgy, Jewish history, Jewish ethics, and religious Jewish life. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Its content encompasses stories about innovative Jewish practices, community initiatives, personal experiences, social justice issues, cultural explorations, and highlights from Reform congregations and individuals making a difference in their communities.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Reform Judaism magazine was first published in 1972 by the Union for Reform Judaism (URJ). It initially aimed to both inform Reform Jews and stimulate discussion within the Reform Jewish community on a national level. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine maintained a strong focus on the beliefs, practices, and societal contributions of Reform Jews, deeply reflecting the principles of the Reform movement.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine transitioned from a quarterly print publication to an online-only format in 2014, continuing its mission to inspire, enlighten, and challenge readers and Reform Jews around the world.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Regardie's
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Regardie''s', N'regardies', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Influential business magazine (1981-1991), noted for penetrating coverage of Washington D.C.''s political and business landscapes.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Regardie''s** was an influential business magazine that covered the Washington, D.C. metropolitan area. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Created to penetrate the business landscape of Washington, Regardie''s magazine shined a spotlight on the capital''s power movers, business titans, and political figures. Its content straddled the line between business reporting and irreverent commentary, offering readers an unconventional view into Washington''s business and political scenes. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded in 1981 by Bill Regardie, a former editor at Washingtonian magazine, Regardie''s became known for its fearless approach to storytelling and lack of deference to the city''s power structure.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Through in-depth profiles, investigative pieces, and colorful commentary, Regardie''s sought to demystify the nexus of business and politics in the nation''s capital. It heavily focused on the real estate sector, which was the primary driver of the D.C. area''s economy, as well as local startups, major corporations, and the influential figures behind them.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its peak, the magazine was hailed as a must-read among Washington''s business and political elites. However, despite its influence and popularity, Regardie''s struggled financially, owing to the high cost of publishing and the competitive nature of the magazine business. The magazine eventually ceased publication in 1991, marking a significant end in the landscape of local media coverage.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Reggae Report
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Reggae Report', N'reggae-report', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Internationally renowned Reggae music magazine (1983-1998), recognized for in-depth interviews, reviews, and music industry coverage.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Reggae Report** was a significant international Reggae music magazine that operated from 1983 to 1998. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Reggae Report was dedicated to covering Reggae music in all its aspects, educating readers about the Reggae world, and promoting the music''s messages of peace, love, unity, and righteousness. The magazine was renowned in the music industry for its comprehensive interviews, in-depth reviews, and vivid photography.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Reggae Report was formed in 1983 by M. Peggy Quattro, a Reggae enthusiast and advocate for the music genre’s international recognition. The magazine began as a small, 4-page publication before metastasizing into the international print medium that it became known for, boasting a readership in more than 35 countries worldwide. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In covering artists from the legendary to the unknown, Reggae Report was unique in its commitment to the comprehensive representation of the Reggae universe. The artists and musicians of the Reggae music genre considered being featured in Reggae Report as a significant achievement in their careers. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its success and influence in the Reggae music industry, Print publication ceased in 1998 due to financial strains. However, the magazine''s legacy continues online, where its archives serve as a vital record of Reggae music''s development and global impact during critical years of the genre''s expansion.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Relief Society Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Relief Society Magazine', N'relief-society-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Official periodical of LDS Church''s women auxiliary (1915-1970), providing spiritual content, cultural insights, and authorship platform.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Relief Society Magazine** was a periodical managed by the Relief Society, the women''s auxiliary of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church). {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The periodical catered to LDS women and provided a range of content including spiritual messages, LDS Church news, fiction, and non-fiction writings, homemaking advice, and other subjects specific to female church members. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Relief Society Magazine began publication in 1915 under the title "The Relief Society Bulletin". It was rebranded as the "Relief Society Magazine" in 1917 and continued circulation under that title, serving as the official voice and publication of the Relief Society as the organization grew and extended its reach globally.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication was pioneering for its time, granting women a platform and promoting female authorship within the church, thereby offering a unique perspective on LDS theology and culture. It played a significant role in shaping the identity and understanding of LDS women and their roles in the church and society at large.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to delivering spiritual content and news, the magazine covered a myriad of women’s issues including education, healthcare, and social welfare matters. Additionally, the periodical included poems, recipes, inspirational stories, and lesson outlines for local Relief Society meetings.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its enduring popularity and influence within the LDS Church, the magazine’s publication came to an end in 1970 as part of a consolidation of LDS Church magazines. Its legacy, however, continues to impact generations of LDS women.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Remix
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Remix', N'remix', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American magazine (1999-2009) focusing on music production, DJing, and electronic music culture; transitioned to digital in 2009.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Remix** was an influential American magazine focused on music production, DJing, and electronic music culture.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Remix was committed to exploring the convergence of technology and music, offering information and insights on digital music creation, DJ culture, and technology-based music. The magazine was filled with reviews of the latest music hardware and software, interviews with leading music producers and DJs across various genres, and detailed tutorials that assisted readers in the art of music production and remixing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Remix magazine came into existence in 1999, created by SpinMedia as a platform for DJs, music producers, and electronic music enthusiasts. It was unique in its dedication to the electronic music scene, quickly becoming a beacon of knowledge for those involved in the industry or looking to break into it.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine primarily targeted professionals and hobbyists within the electronic music industry, including producers, engineers, and DJs. Its immersive and extensive content provided in-depth knowledge on technology, trends, and artists, making it an invaluable resource in its field.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity and influence in the music production industry, Remix ceased its print publication in 2009 and transitioned to an entirely digital medium; focusing on its website and e-newsletters.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- RES
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'RES', N'res', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American publication (1996-2006) dedicated to digital film making, visual culture and digital arts; ceased print edition in 2006.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**RES** was an esteemed American magazine dedicated to digital film making, visual culture, and the digital arts.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'RES showcased an array of digital media content, such as various forms of digital arts, music, film, and design. The magazine profiled innovative and groundbreaking artists, filmmakers, designers, and musicians who were pushing boundaries in their respective mediums. Apart from profiling digital art’s pioneers and emerging talents, the magazine often included reviews on cultural events, film festivals, art shows, and product reviews relative to digital media.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Launched in 1996, RES was a bimonthly publication that endeavored to document and catalyze the evolution of digital media, especially in film making. The magazine was born at a time when digital arts were gaining popularity and offered an exclusive platform that mirrored the steady rise of this innovative form of art.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'RES brought the digital arts and culture scene to its readers in a comprehensive manner that was both accessible and informative to beginners, enthusiasts, and professionals alike. Its contents ranged from instructional articles on animation, special effects, editing and other aspects of digital film production, to features about artists in the digital world across various mediums – film, music, design, and more.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Unfortunately, the print edition of the RES magazine ended in 2006. However, its impact on the evolving world of digital media remains significant.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Restaurants & Institutions
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Restaurants & Institutions', N'restaurants-and-institutions', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American trade publication (early 20th century-2010) for foodservice professionals, known for industry rankings and Ivy Award.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Restaurants & Institutions** was an American trade magazine servicing foodservice professionals, especially those working in the field of restaurant management.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine covered a vast scope of topics pertinent to the foodservice industry. This ranged from trends in cuisine, information on food safety and regulations, operational best practices, technological advancements in the industry, to marketing strategies and case studies. Its mission was to equip its readership with insights, ideas, and information essential for decision-making in their field.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Restaurants & Institutions magazine was launched in the early 20th century and had a rich history of providing the restaurant industry with quality content for almost a century. It was a highly respected source of information within the industry, counting executives, chefs, food and beverage directors, purchasing managers, and other foodservice professionals among its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine prided itself on its credible reporting, exhaustive research, and in-depth analysis of various sectors within the foodservice industry. It also became well-known for its annual industry rankings and awards that celebrated excellence and innovation in foodservice. This included the coveted Ivy Award, which recognized exceptional restaurants and was awarded based on feedback from peers in the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its immense popularity and recognition, Restaurants & Institutions went out of publication in 2010 due to financial difficulties. Its closure marked the end of an era in trade publications for the foodservice industry.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- REVUE Mid Michigan
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'REVUE Mid Michigan', N'revue-mid-michigan', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Free monthly publication focusing on arts, entertainment, dining, and lifestyle in the Mid Michigan region.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**REVUE Mid Michigan** is a locally focused publication servicing the Mid Michigan region in the United States.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine delivers comprehensive coverage specific to Mid Michigan''s communities, featuring local arts, entertainment, dining, and lifestyle. It provides readers, both locals and visitors, with in-depth features on local artists, and continuous updates on the region''s live music, theatre, dining establishments, and craft beverages scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'REVUE Mid Michigan is a niche publication with a mission focused on illuminating the vibrancy of the Mid Michigan region and uplifting local businesses and artists. The content primarily includes insightful interviews with local figures, thoroughly researched articles, event listings, and critical reviews.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Within the local community, REVUE Mid Michigan is respected for its commitment to maintaining a distinctive and genuine voice. It embodies a dedication to community engagement and local culture showcasing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication is free and widely distributed throughout the area, making it accessible to a broad range of readers. It is also available digitally, reaching an extensive online audience.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Rhapsody
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Rhapsody', N'rhapsody', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Luxury lifestyle and literary publication for first-class passengers on United Airlines, focusing on travel, culture, and business.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Rhapsody** is a luxury lifestyle and literary magazine tailored towards first-class passengers on United Airlines. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Rhapsody provides creative content covering a wide range of topics, including travel, art, culture, fashion, and business. The publication seeks to engage with seasoned travelers through high-quality features and exclusive interviews. Over time, Rhapsody has built its reputation as a platform for award-winning writers and leading journalists.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N' ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Rhapsody magazine was first published in 2013 by Ink Global, an international leader in travel media, in conjunction with United Airlines who desired to create an exclusive reading experience for their first-class customers. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The monthly magazine is distributed to an audience that includes first-class and premier-class fliers on United Airlines, in United Clubs and the airline’s broader premium lounges network. As such, it provides its advertisers access to a high net worth, global clientele.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As a testament to the quality of its editorial content, Rhapsody magazine has featured the work of several acclaimed authors and journalists, and has boasted stories penned by literary powerhouses such as Joyce Carol Oates and Anthony Doerr.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Rhapsody’s access to this select audience and commitment to high-caliber content has secured it a unique position in the media landscape of the airline industry.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Right On!
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Right On!', N'right-on', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American magazine focused on African American teens, spotlighting popular African American musicians and actors since the 1970s.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Right On!** is an American magazine first established in the early 1970s. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine primarily targets African American teenagers and young adults, with a primary focus on popular African American musicians and actors. Content featured in Right On! includes in-depth celebrity interviews, music album reviews, behind-the-scenes reports, and candid photographs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Right On! was first published by Dorchester Media, marking its position in the print media as a pioneering platform for Black teenage culture in the United States. Throughout the 1970s and 1980s, the magazine was the leading and most influential publication in acknowledging and celebrating the successes of African American artists and actors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Primarily focusing on music genres such as soul, funk, and R&B, Right On! quickly gained popularity for its inclusivity, providing Black teenagers with relatable and culturally resonate content that was largely absent from mainstream teen magazines of the time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Right On! developed a devoted readership and became iconic for its posters of popular musicians and actors, which often adorned the bedroom walls of its dedicated readers. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As of the 2000s, the magazine has broadened its editorial scope to incorporate profiles of up-and-coming talent from diverse cultural backgrounds, reflecting the dynamic and multicultural demographic of modern American youth.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Ring En Español
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Ring En Español', N'the-ring-en-español', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Spanish-language sports magazine with comprehensive boxing coverage for the Spanish-speaking fans and boxers worldwide.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Ring En Español** is a Spanish-language sports magazine widely known for its focus on the sport of boxing.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ring En Español is renowned for its comprehensive coverage of boxing, targeting largely Spanish-speaking fans of the sport. The magazine features an array of in-depth interviews, match previews, analytical articles, historical insights and fight reports, all centered around both international and local Spanish-speaking boxers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Dating back to its inception, Ring En Español was birthed as a sister publication to The Ring magazine, an iconic American boxing magazine. The objective was to cater to the passionate and large Latino population that followed boxing in both the United States and wider Latin America.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine played an essential role in championing and highlighting Latin American and Spanish-speaking boxers in a time where English-speaking media largely dominated sports journalism. Its coverage extended from established champions to promising up-and-comers, providing a platform for these athletes within the boxing community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the popularity of Ring En Español has grown not only in the United States but also in Boxing-passionate Latino countries, becoming an essential source of information and insight relating to the sport in the Spanish-speaking world.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Rip Off Review of Western Culture
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Rip Off Review of Western Culture', N'the-rip-off-review-of-western-culture', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Underground American magazine of the late 60s and early 70s, noted for countercultural commentaries and contributions.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Rip Off Review of Western Culture** is an American underground magazine best known for its run during the late 1960s and early 1970s.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was focused on presenting an underground and countercultural perspective on the conventional western civilization. Its pages included a mix of works from fresh, independent artists, literary figureheads of the countercultural movement, and trenchant social and political commentary. The Rip Off Review of Western Culture also featured music, art, poetry, and graphic stories, embodying the free-spirited ethos of its time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded by Peter Stafford and John Bryan in San Francisco, California, The Rip Off Review of Western Culture became an influential voice within the counterculture movement of the late 60s and early 70s. It was recognized for its bold and unapologetic exploration of alternative viewpoints, challenging the mainstream norms and societal conventions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine featured contributions from notable figures in the counterculture, including comix artists Greg Irons and Jim Osborne, poet and painter Lawrence Ferlinghetti, and author and psychedelic proponent Timothy Leary.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Rip Off Review of Western Culture published a total of three issues between 1969 and 1972. Despite its short-lived existence, it left a lasting mark on the counterculture scene and underground press movement.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Robot
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Robot', N'robot', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription US-based publication focused on robotics, providing reviews, interviews, tutorials and updates on latest advancements.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Robot** is an American publication with a primary focus on the field of robotics, showcasing a blend of informative and educational content.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The core content of Robot Magazine is rooted in the exploration of both hobbyist and professional aspects of robotics. The magazine encompasses reviews on robotic kits and components, interviews with leading individuals in the field, instruction-based content for robotic enthusiasts and features on the latest robotic innovations and applications. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Furthermore, it provides tutorials, how-to articles, and project ideas to cater to a broad spectrum of readers, from the novice builder to the more experienced engineer.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded in the United States, Robot Magazine quickly positioned itself as an authority figure in the niche yet rapidly growing robotics industry. The publication took it upon itself to demystify the complexities of robotics, making it accessible to a wider audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has continuously evolved with the progressions in the field, showcasing the recent advancements, emerging technologies, and newfound applications of robotics in diverse industries. Its mix of educationally rigorous and entertaining content continues to capture the interest of readers of varying degrees of engagement with the field, from high school students and hobbyists to industry professionals and academics.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Rock N Roll Experience
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Rock N Roll Experience', N'rock-n-roll-experience', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American music-focused publication, featuring album reviews, artist interviews, news in rock and related genres.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Rock N Roll Experience** is a music-focused publication based in the United States, which caters predominantly to fans of rock music and its numerous sub-genres.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Rock N Roll Experience Magazine''s principal content is fashioned around the world of rock music, encompassing album and concert reviews, interviews with artists, and news concerning up-and-coming and established bands. It provides in-depth feature stories on a range of topics, from intriguing backstories of beloved rock anthems to the evolution of rock sub-genres. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also serves as a platform for photographers and writers specializing in rock music, showcasing their work throughout its pages. Over the years, it has covered a multitude of bands and artists, crossing the spectrum from all-out rock to alternative, indie, punk, metal, and beyond.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded in the United States, Rock N Roll Experience Magazine has successfully carved its niche in the competitive landscape of music journalism. It appeals primarily to passionate rock music fans, showcasing an authentic and personalized approach to its coverage, which stands it apart from other mainstream music publications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In acknowledgment of the digital age and changing reading habits, besides physical copies, the magazine maintains a robust online presence with a website that mirrors its print content and includes exclusive web-only features.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Rocket
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Rocket', N'the-rocket', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Former Pacific Northwest-based free music magazine, known for early coverage of grunge and local music scene.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Rocket** was a free biweekly music magazine based in Seattle, United States, covering the music and culture scene of the Pacific Northwest.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Rocket''s content was an eclectic blend reflecting the vibrant music and arts scene of the Pacific Northwest. It featured local music news, band interviews, reviews for albums and live shows, and extensive event listings. It also showcased content covering film, fashion, comics, and culture, mirroring the varied interests of its readership.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notable for its support of local music, The Rocket was one of the first publications to cover the burgeoning Seattle music scene in the 80s and 90s, including bands like Nirvana, Pearl Jam, and Soundgarden before their rise to global fame.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Rocket further distinguished itself with its striking cover art, often featuring work from prominent local and national artists.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Launched in 1979 by Robert McChesney, The Rocket became a periodical fixture in the burgeoning music scene of Seattle and the larger Pacific Northwest. Its significance in documenting the rise and evolution of the ''grunge'' movement has made it an integral part of rock music history.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its publication run till 2000, The Rocket had various owners and saw highs and lows in its circulation, but its influence on the music scene remained unabated.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Rogue Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Rogue Magazine', N'rogue-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Philippines-based luxury lifestyle and culture magazine, focusing on art, fashion, travel, and high-end living.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Rogue Magazine** is a luxury lifestyle and culture magazine from the Philippines, focusing on arts, culture, and the finer elements of high living.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The content of Rogue caters predominantly to the cosmopolitan, cultured readers. Its broad coverage encompasses topics such as art, culture, travel, gourmet food, high-end fashion, and luxury products. It is known for its in-depth features, thoughtful narratives, and distinctive visual aesthetics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Rogue features articles and interviews with both local and international figures from the art, entertainment, fashion, and business worlds, providing insight into their lives and craft. Its cultural reportage extends from Philippine society''s extravagances to chronicling the country''s history and heritage.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also includes critical reviews and previews of upcoming events, restaurant launches, and travel destinations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded in Manila in 2007, Rogue has carved a niche in the luxury lifestyle segment amongst a discerning readership. With its high-end production, glossy pages, compelling features, and top-notch photography, it has positioned itself as a magazine of substance and style catering to the modern, affluent Filipino.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As part of its progressive approach to the changing media landscape, Rogue also maintains a dynamic online presence, extending its print content to digital platforms, which has allowed it to reach a broader and more diverse audience.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Rookie
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Rookie', N'rookie', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription American online publication for teenage girls, with focus on fashion, culture, feminism, and self-empowerment.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Rookie** was an American online magazine created by fashion blogger Tavi Gevinson in 2011 when she was just 15 years old. The magazine, directed towards teenaged girls, focused on themes of fashion, culture, feminism, and self-empowerment. {{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'With a fresh take on teenage subculture, Rookie emerged as a platform that encouraged its readers to develop their own unique voices. Editorially, it was consisted of written articles, illustration, photography, and DIY guides, curated around monthly themes. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Recognizing the evolving interests of teenagers, the magazine featured articles on a range of subjects such as sexuality, social activism, pop culture, fashion, and beauty. It became known for thoughtfully addressing topics that mattered to young women beyond just fashion and beauty. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The platform gained recognition for its ambition to contribute to the cultural conversation around teenage female experiences, providing a space for the articulation of their perspectives and concerns.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Rookie was officially launched in September 2011, with a team comprising mostly teenage girls, and Gevinson serving as editor-in-chief. The content remained relevant and evocative, with an impressive lineup of high-profile interviewees and contributors over the years, including longstanding fashion icons, renowned musicians, and influential authors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also published four print editions, Rookie Yearbooks One through Four, each compiling selected content from each year of the website.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its notable success, Rookie ceased publishing in November 2018 due to financial constraints, marking an end to one of the most influential platforms for young women of the decade.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Rural Cooperatives
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Rural Cooperatives', N'rural-cooperatives', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Bi-monthly USDA magazine on cooperative business and economic development in rural and agricultural areas.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Rural Cooperatives** is a bi-monthly magazine published by the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA). The publication focuses on issues related to cooperative business in agricultural and rural areas across the country.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine delivers in-depth information about the cooperative model as it applies to rural and agricultural businesses. Topics typically covered within its pages include cooperative development and best practices, economic impacts, financial results of co-ops and how their business structure is designed to support rural economies and improve the livelihood of rural citizens.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Interviews with agricultural industry leaders are often featured, along with stories highlighting successful co-op models, and case studies that provide readers with tangible examples of cooperative business success.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Articles range from advice for those wanting to start a co-op, to stories of established co-ops creating a significant impact in their communities. The magazine underscores the role of co-ops in strengthening rural economies by creating jobs and appealing to new markets.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Publication History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The USDA has published Rural Cooperatives since the mid-20th century. Its readership consists of cooperative members and directors, cooperative researchers and educators, rural economic development professionals, and agriculture industry stakeholders.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s editorial team is based at the Cooperative Programs division of USDA''s Rural Development department. The aim is to provide a platform for exchanging knowledge and strengthening the role of cooperative businesses in the rural economy.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

