azines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Our Women and Children
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Our Women and Children', N'our-women-and-children', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly magazine addressing issues and concerns of mothers and young women in the United States during the 1890s to 1930s. Featured educational and literary works by notable writers and contributions from feminist journalists.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Our Women and Children was a monthly magazine targeting mothers and young women in the United States and published from the 1890s to the 1930s. The magazine was founded in 1891 by Sarah Weeks Vann, and it aimed to address topics that were of concern to women.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine tackled various issues that women faced at the time, including child-rearing, education, cooking, household management, and fashion. Our Women and Children also included educational and literary works, with contributions from leading writers and journalists, such as Jack London, Ida Tarbell, and Nellie Bly.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its serious content, the magazine also included popular features such as short stories, fashion illustrations, and puzzles. Our Women and Children also organized various contests, such as essay competitions and recipe contests, with prizes for the winners.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Our Women and Children experienced significant success during its publication and was widely read by women across the country. The magazine''s focus on education and social issues helped to shape attitudes towards women''s roles in society during the progressive era.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, by the 1930s, the magazine faced stiff competition from new publications targeting women, and it eventually ceased publication. Today, Our Women and Children remains an important publication in the history of women''s magazines, and its legacy continues to inspire new generations of feminist writers and publishers.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Our Young Folks
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Our Young Folks', N'our-young-folks', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly literary magazine for children and young adults published in the United States from 1865 to 1873. Featured short stories, poems, articles, and illustrations by leading authors and illustrators of the time and focused on uplifting and wholesome content for middle-class children.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Our Young Folks was a monthly literary magazine aimed at children and young adults, published in the United States from 1865 to 1873. The magazine was founded by Howard M. Ticknor and John T. Fields, who were also the founders of the publishing firm Ticknor and Fields.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Our Young Folks featured a mix of short stories, poems, articles, and illustrations, with contributions from some of the leading children''s authors and illustrators of the day, including Louisa May Alcott, Mark Twain, and John Greenleaf Whittier. The magazine also included puzzles, games, and other educational material.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s target audience was primarily middle-class children who were interested in adventure stories and tales of morality and virtue. Our Young Folks generally avoided controversial topics and focused on uplifting and wholesome content that parents could approve of.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its relatively short run, Our Young Folks became a popular publication and was widely read by children and young adults across the United States. The magazine''s success paved the way for future children''s publications, and it remains an important publication in the history of American children''s literature.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1874, Our Young Folks was merged with the children''s magazine Wide Awake, also published by Ticknor and Fields, to form St. Nicholas Magazine, which became one of the most influential children''s publications of the late 19th century.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

