VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Monthly trade magazine focused on the phonograph and recording industries, published from 1902 to 1906, providing information on new technologies and equipment, artist performances, and record releases.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Phonograph Record** was a monthly trade magazine focused on the phonograph and recording industries, published from 1902 to 1906. The magazine was one of the earliest publications to cater to the growing demand for information on sound recording technology and music distribution.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Phonograph Record covered topics related to the phonograph industry such as new technologies and equipment, available music records, and artist performances and releases. The magazine also featured advertisements for phonograph equipment and records.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication of Phonograph Record coincided with the growth of the early commercial music recording industry. During this period, the phonograph industry was developing rapidly, and the magazine was an important resource for professionals in the industry as well as for serious collectors and enthusiasts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Phonograph Record was published by the Phonograph Belles-Lettres Company, which was headquartered in New York City. The magazine featured articles and illustrations written by leading experts and professionals in the phonograph industry at the time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its relatively short run, Phonograph Record was an important publication in the history of the recording industry, providing a valuable resource for professionals and enthusiasts alike. The magazine helped to shape the direction of the phonograph industry during its formative years.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Photo
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Photo', N'photo', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Monthly photography magazine published in the US from 1941-1953, covering a broad range of photographic styles, techniques, and notable photographers.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Photo** was a monthly photography magazine published in the United States from 1941 to 1953. The magazine was noted for its coverage of a wide variety of photographic styles and techniques, and for its contributions to the development of photography as an art form.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Photo covered a broad range of photographic topics, including photojournalism, portraiture, nature and landscape photography, and experimental techniques. The magazine also featured articles on photographic equipment and technologies, as well as profiles of notable photographers and their work.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its run, Photo published the work of many important photographers, including Edward Weston, Ansel Adams, and Dorothea Lange. The magazine served as a forum for the discussion and debate of photographic styles and techniques, and helped to shape the direction of photography as an art form in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Photo was published by the American Photography Institute, which was headquartered at the New York Institute of Photography. The magazine was printed on high-quality paper and featured a range of photographic reproductions and illustrations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its relatively short run, Photo was an important publication in the history of photography in the United States, offering a unique perspective on the art form at a time of significant change and innovation.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Photo District News
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Photo District News', N'photo-district-news', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly trade publication and resource for professional photographers, covering various aspects of the photography business, and organizing annual competitions and events.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Photo District News**, commonly known as *PDN*, is a monthly trade publication for professional photographers and others involved in the photography industry. Founded in 1980, PDN covers the full spectrum of the photography business, including photojournalism, commercial photography, advertising, fine art photography, and photographic equipment.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'PDN also runs a number of annual competitions and events aimed at recognizing and promoting the work of professional photographers. These include the PDN Photo Annual, the PDN PhotoPlus International Conference and Expo, and the PDNedu Student Photo Contest.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has won numerous awards for its photojournalism and design, including numerous Folio Awards and Eddie Awards. PDN is owned by Emerald Expositions, which also owns a number of other major trade publications and events in the photography, fashion, and consumer electronics industries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'PDN is published in print and online, and also produces a variety of e-books, webinars, and other digital content aimed at photographers and photography professionals.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Photo-Era
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Photo-Era', N'photo-era', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly photography magazine published in the United States from 1898 to 1927, targeting amateur photographers and featuring works from notable contributors like Weston, Stieglitz, and Adams.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Photo-Era** was a monthly photography magazine published in the United States from 1898 until 1927. Initially named American Amateur Photographer and then American Photography, the magazine was renamed Photo-Era in 1911.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication was aimed at amateur photographers and covered various aspects of photography, including techniques, equipment, and the work of photographers. Notable contributors to the magazine included Edward Weston, Alfred Stieglitz, and Ansel Adams.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Photo-Era also organized an annual photography contest that was widely regarded as one of the most prestigious amateur photography competitions in the United States. The contest attracted thousands of entries each year and awarded cash prizes and medals to the top winners.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to the magazine, Photo-Era also published a number of photography books and manuals aimed at amateur photographers. The company was eventually acquired by the New York Institute of Photography, and the magazine ceased publication in 1927.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, back issues of Photo-Era are highly collectible among photography enthusiasts and historians, providing a valuable window into the history of amateur photography in the early 20th century.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Photoplay
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Photoplay', N'photoplay', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A popular American film magazine published from 1911 to 1980 known for its coverage of the film industry and exclusive photos of Hollywood stars.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Photoplay** was a popular American film magazine published from 1911 to 1980. Originally started as a motion picture fan magazine, Photoplay became one of the most influential and widely circulated movie magazines in the United States.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine covered various aspects of the film industry including news, interviews, reviews, and feature articles on actors and filmmakers. Photoplay also published exclusive and often controversial photos of Hollywood stars, frequently sparking rumors and gossip about their private lives.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During the 1920s and 1930s, Photoplay routinely published reader polls for selecting the most popular actors and actresses, known as the "Photoplay Medal Awards". The awards were highly coveted by Hollywood stars and helped to cultivate public interest and fan engagement in the film industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the 1940s, Photoplay shifted its focus from movie news to romantic fiction, publishing serialized stories with headshots of actors on the cover. The magazine''s popularity continued to decline in the following decades and it eventually ceased publication in 1980.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its controversial reputation, Photoplay is remembered not only for its contributions to popular celebrity culture, but also as a valuable historical resource for understanding the evolution of Hollywood and the film industry in the 20th century.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Physique Pictorial
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Physique Pictorial', N'physique-pictorial', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A quarterly magazine with explicit content that showcased the male body in a daring and controversial way, and served as an important agent in the sexual liberation movement.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Physique Pictorial** was a quarterly magazine focused on male physique photography and art, first published in 1951. The magazine was produced by Athletic Model Guild, a company founded by photographer Bob Mizer. It was intended for a gay male audience and became known for its daring and sometimes explicit content.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was unique for its time in that it showcased the male body in a way that had previously been considered taboo in mainstream society. Many of the photos featured in the magazine were of amateur models, and the photos showcased the male physique in poses that were considered daring and controversial.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Physique Pictorial''s content was not limited to photography, as it also featured essays on the male physique in both popular culture and art. The magazine served as an important agent in the sexual liberation movement, which helped to remove the social stigma attached to the male physique.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s popularity waned during the 1970s and it ceased publication in 1990. However, its influence can be felt in the many contemporary publications and art forms that showcase the male physique, which have become more mainstream as attitudes towards sexuality have evolved.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, Physique Pictorial is considered a landmark piece of LGBTQ+ history, which celebrated the male physique and helped to usher in a new era of sexual expression.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Picture Play
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Picture Play', N'picture-play', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A popular American fan magazine from the early to mid 20th century providing coverage of Hollywood and the stars of the era, with a focus on young adults.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Picture Play** was a popular American fan magazine published from 1915 to 1941. It was founded by Judge magazine editor Arthur H. Folwell and was initially focused on the film industry, providing coverage of Hollywood and the stars of the era.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Picture Play became known for its exclusive photos and interviews with Hollywood stars, which were a major draw for readers. At its peak in the 1920s and 1930s, the magazine had a circulation of over one million copies per month. Its readership included both men and women, with a focus on young adults.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to interviews and photos of celebrities, Picture Play featured articles on the film industry, including reviews of movies and previews of upcoming releases. The magazine also included fashion and beauty advice, making it a one-stop-shop for entertainment and lifestyle content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its run, Picture Play was home to a number of prominent journalists and film critics, including Louella Parsons and Hedda Hopper, both of whom would go on to become Hollywood gossip columnists.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Picture Play ceased publication in 1941, as the United States entered World War II and wartime restrictions made publishing difficult. Today, it is remembered as an important piece of Hollywood history, which helped to establish the celebrity culture that we know today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- PiQ
