VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly magazine covering Japanese pop culture topics like anime, manga, video games, and comics, aimed at young adults, known for its unique design.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**PiQ** was a monthly magazine that covered a variety of topics, including anime, manga, video games, and comics. The magazine was published by ADV Manga, a division of ADV Films, and was aimed at a young adult audience.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'PiQ''s content was largely focused on Japanese pop culture, with a particular emphasis on anime and manga. The magazine featured news and reviews of the latest anime and manga releases, as well as interviews with voice actors and creators in the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to anime and manga, PiQ also covered video games and comics. The magazine featured reviews and previews of the latest video game releases, as well as articles on the comic book industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'PiQ was known for its unique design and layout, which included colorful fonts and graphics. The magazine also featured fan art submitted by readers, and encouraged reader participation through contests and giveaways.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity among fans, PiQ struggled financially and ceased publication after just four issues. The final issue was published in October 2008.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, PiQ is remembered as an important piece of anime and manga history, providing coverage of the industry during a time when it was still relatively niche in the United States.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Pitchfork Review
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Pitchfork Review', N'the-pitchfork-review', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A quarterly music magazine covering various genres with strong online presence, praised for high-quality writing, art, and photography.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Pitchfork Review** was a quarterly music magazine published by Pitchfork Media. The magazine covered a wide variety of music genres, with a particular focus on indie rock, hip-hop, and electronic music.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Pitchfork Review''s content included reviews of albums, interviews with musicians, and in-depth articles on music culture and history. The magazine also featured artwork and photography from both established and up-and-coming artists.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print edition, The Pitchfork Review also had a strong online presence, with additional articles, reviews, and multimedia content available on its website.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was known for its high-quality writing and editorial style, and was highly regarded by both musicians and music fans. However, despite its critical success, The Pitchfork Review struggled financially, and was ultimately discontinued in 2018 after just 18 issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, The Pitchfork Review is remembered as an important piece of music journalism history, which helped to push the boundaries of what was possible in the realm of music criticism.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Pizzazz
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Pizzazz', N'pizzazz', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A short-lived biweekly children''s magazine featuring comics, puzzles, and celebrity interviews, known for its colorful design.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Pizzazz** was a short-lived biweekly magazine for children featuring comics, puzzles, and celebrity interviews, among other things. The magazine was published by Marvel Comics from 1977 to 1979.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Pizzazz''s content catered to children of both genders, and included articles on diverse topics like music, movies, and television shows. The magazine was known for its colorful design, including hand-drawn illustrations and collages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of Pizzazz''s most popular features was the "Pizzazz Posterzine," a pull-out poster featuring photos and interviews with celebrities of the time, which young readers could hang up in their bedrooms.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While Pizzazz''s publication run was brief, the magazine left a lasting impression on its readers. The magazine helped launch the careers of a number of comic book artists and writers, including Jim Salicrup, Jo Duffy, and Eliot Brown.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, Pizzazz is remembered fondly as a unique piece of children''s publishing history, combining comics, celebrity interviews, and colorful design into a distinctive package.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Plain Truth
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Plain Truth', N'the-plain-truth', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly religious magazine covering world news, prophecy, and self-improvement with controversial content challenging traditional Christian teachings.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Plain Truth** was a monthly religious magazine published by the Worldwide Church of God (WCG) from 1934 to 1990. The magazine primarily focused on religious and world news, as well as prophecy and self-improvement.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Plain Truth was originally conceived by Herbert W. Armstrong, founder of the WCG, as a way to spread his religious teachings and interpretations of biblical prophecy. The magazine was printed in multiple languages and had a worldwide audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Notably, The Plain Truth challenged traditional Christian teachings on subjects like the afterlife, the nature of God, and the observance of religious holidays. This often put the magazine and its publisher at odds with other religious organizations.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its controversial content, The Plain Truth was widely read and had a devoted following, with a circulation that reached millions in the 1960s and 1970s. The magazine also had a significant impact on popular culture, inspiring parodies and even an episode of The Simpsons.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Following the death of Armstrong in 1986, the WCG underwent significant changes, including a shift in its religious teachings and the discontinuation of The Plain Truth in 1990. Today, The Plain Truth is remembered as an important part of religious publishing history, which challenged traditional Christian teachings and inspired a passionate following.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Planet Muscle
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
