VALUES ( N'The Presbyterian Guardian', N'the-presbyterian-guardian', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A former monthly publication of the Orthodox Presbyterian Church in the United States, providing conservative news, commentary, and analysis on theological and social issues.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Presbyterian Guardian** was a monthly publication of the Orthodox Presbyterian Church (OPC), a conservative Reformed denomination in the United States. The magazine was founded in 1935 by J. Gresham Machen, a prominent theologian and founder of the OPC.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Presbyterian Guardian served as the official magazine of the OPC, providing news, commentary, and analysis on issues relevant to the denomination and the broader Christian community. The magazine was known for its conservative stance on theological and social issues, and often addressed controversial topics in the church.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, The Presbyterian Guardian became an important voice within the OPC and the wider Reformed community, with contributions from prominent theologians, pastors, and scholars. The magazine also played a significant role in shaping the OPC''s theological identity and preserving its historic confessional standards.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1980, The Presbyterian Guardian merged with the magazine *New Horizons* to form the current publication *New Horizons in the Orthodox Presbyterian Church*, which continues to serve as the official magazine of the OPC.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its discontinuation, The Presbyterian Guardian played a significant role in the OPC''s history and development, and its legacy can still be seen in the current publication. The magazine''s archives remain a valuable resource for researchers, theologians, and historians of the Reformed tradition.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Present Age
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Present Age', N'present-age', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A former progressive Catholic magazine in the United States, covering a range of topics including social justice, theology, politics, and culture.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Present Age** was a Jesuit-run Catholic magazine in the United States, founded in 1952. The magazine was created as a platform for Catholic laypeople to engage with social and political issues of the day, particularly as they related to the Catholic Church''s teachings on social justice.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine covered a wide range of topics, including theology, politics, social justice, and culture. Present Age was known for its progressive stances on social and political issues, and often tackled controversial topics within the Catholic Church.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Present Age published articles by many notable Catholic writers and scholars, including John Courtney Murray, Thomas Merton, and Dorothy Day. The magazine also addressed issues related to the Second Vatican Council, and played an important role in shaping the direction of the Catholic Church in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its reputation and influence, Present Age struggled financially in the 1970s and 1980s, and ceased publication in 1987. Its archives remain an important resource for scholars of Catholic history and social justice.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, the legacy of Present Age can be seen in the continued importance of social justice within the Catholic Church, as well as in the work of many Catholic laypeople, scholars, and organizations that share the magazine''s commitment to progressive social and political change.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Print Collector's Quarterly
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Print Collector''s Quarterly', N'the-print-collectors-quarterly', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A magazine focused on historical and contemporary printmaking, featuring renowned scholars and high-quality reproductions.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**The Print Collector''s Quarterly** was a magazine focused on historical and contemporary printmaking, published quarterly between 1911 and 1993. The magazine featured articles on various types of printmaking, such as etching, lithography, woodcuts, engravings, and screenprints.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was founded in 1911 by Frank Weitenkampf, an American librarian, art historian, and print collector. It was intended to serve as a resource for print collectors, curators, and scholars, as well as a way to promote and elevate the art of printmaking.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, The Print Collector''s Quarterly published articles by some of the most renowned print scholars and collectors of the time, including Campbell Dodgson, A.M. Hind, and H.P. Bowie. The magazine also featured high-quality reproductions of prints, often in full color, providing readers with a detailed look at the techniques and materials used in the printing process.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While The Print Collector''s Quarterly was primarily focused on historical printmaking, the magazine also covered contemporary printmaking trends and artists. The inclusion of articles on print portfolios and print editions made the magazine particularly useful for art dealers and collectors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After a run of over 80 years, The Print Collector''s Quarterly ceased publication in 1993. However, the magazine remains an important resource for scholars and collectors of print art, providing a comprehensive look at the history and evolution of printmaking as an art form.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Print Connoisseur
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Print Connoisseur', N'print-connoisseur', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A quarterly American magazine dedicated to the art of printmaking with high-quality production values and expert contributors.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Print Connoisseur** was an American magazine, dedicated to the art of printmaking. The magazine was published quarterly for a total of 26 issues between 1988 and 2009.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine covered many aspects of printmaking, including historical and contemporary topics, techniques, and artists. Every issue featured in-depth articles, reviews of exhibitions and books, interviews with artists and collectors, and illustrations of rare prints.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Print Connoisseur was known for its high-quality production values, featuring lavish color illustrations and high-quality printing. The magazine was a favorite among collectors, scholars, artists, and print enthusiasts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was founded by Nadine F. Orenstein, a curator of prints and drawings at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City. Print Connoisseur''s editorial staff included a number of renowned experts in the field, such as David Acton, Ann Landi, and Susan Tallman.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2009, Print Connoisseur ceased publication due to financial difficulties caused by the 2008 financial crisis. Despite its relatively short run, the magazine left a lasting impression on the world of printmaking, providing a valuable resource for collectors, curators, scholars, and anyone interested in the art of printmaking.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Print
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Print', N'print', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American magazine covering all aspects of visual culture, including graphic design, typography, and advertising, with a rich history and respected reputation.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'**Print** is an American magazine, founded in 1940 by William Edwin Rudge. The magazine covers topics related to visual culture, including graphic design, illustration, typography, and advertising.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Print has grown to become a leading voice in the graphic design and visual culture community. The magazine has published articles by and interviews with some of the most influential designers of the 20th century, including Paul Rand, Milton Glaser, and Saul Bass.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Print has also been recognized for its coverage of important historical events, such as the Vietnam War and the 9/11 attacks. In addition to its print publication, the magazine has an online presence, featuring daily news updates, podcasts, and an extensive archive of past articles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has won numerous awards for its design and editorial content, including the National Magazine Award for General Excellence in 2014. Print has also been listed among the "100 Best Magazines Ever" by the American Society of Magazine Editors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'As of 2021, Print is published by PRINT Holdings LLC. While the magazine has experienced some financial difficulties over the years, it remains an important resource for designers, illustrators, and anyone interested in the history and evolution of visual culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Printers' Ink
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
