VALUES ( N'In the Family', N'in-the-family', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly magazine focused on family-oriented articles and faith-promoting editorials for members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the Family was a magazine aimed at the parents and families of the members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church). The magazine was published from 1970 to 1998.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the Family was first published in 1970 as a replacement for The Instructor, which had been in circulation since 1922. The magazine was published monthly and was aimed at providing parents and families of the LDS Church with resources and information to strengthen their family relationships and their faith.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, In the Family featured a number of notable writers and columnists, including James E. Faust and Sheri L. Dew.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1998, In the Family was replaced by a new magazine, "The Ensign" which also featured family-oriented articles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the Family covered a wide range of topics related to family life and the LDS Church. The magazine featured articles on parenting, marriage, family relationships, and faith. In the Family regularly included editorials by Church leaders encouraging parents, youth, and families in their spiritual efforts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also had features such as Book of the Month Club, Family Travel, and Home Cooking recipes. It also included poetry, fiction, and artwork from LDS Church members.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the Family had a large readership among members of the LDS Church. The magazine was seen as an important resource for parents and families to help create stronger bonds within their families.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, In the Family received a number of industry awards for its content and layout.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although In the Family ceased publication in 1998, its influence on the LDS Church members and families continues to this day. Its focus on family life and spiritual development influenced generations of parents and families and continues in the Church''s emphasis on family activities and programs to strengthen the family unit within the Church.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Index
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Index', N'index', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A counterculture publication based in Montreal, featured alternative perspectives on arts, culture, and politics.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Index *Magazine* was a publication based in Montreal, Quebec, Canada, covering arts, culture, and politics. It was in circulation from 1991 to 2009 and was known for its coverage of counterculture.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Index was founded in 1991 by a group of Montreal activists and artists. The magazine was initially produced on a shoestring budget and featured a DIY aesthetic that reflected its counterculture roots.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine grew in popularity and gained a reputation as a leading voice in Montreal''s arts and culture scene. It was particularly well-known for its coverage of independent arts events, music, and underground politics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2009, Index ceased publication, citing financial difficulties.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Index covered a wide range of topics related to arts, culture, and politics. The magazine featured articles on music, film, literature, and visual arts. It also covered politics, human rights, and social justice issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Index was known for its alternative perspective and willingness to challenge the status quo. The magazine often gave a voice to marginalized communities and featured articles on topics that were otherwise overlooked by mainstream media.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Index had a devoted readership in Montreal and beyond. The magazine was seen as an important resource for those interested in alternative arts and culture in the city.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Index received a number of awards for its content and layout. The magazine was also praised for its commitment to independent journalism and the arts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although Index ceased publication in 2009, its influence on Montreal''s arts and culture scene continues to this day. Its legacy is seen in the city''s vibrant independent arts scene. The magazine''s archives are also available online, providing a valuable resource for those interested in Montreal''s cultural history.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Industry Standard
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Industry Standard', N'the-industry-standard', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A now-defunct technology industry publication that rose to prominence during the dot-com boom and bust.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Industry Standard was a weekly magazine that covered the technology industry during the dot-com boom and bust of the late 1990s and early 2000s.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Industry Standard was founded in 1998 by John Battelle, and quickly became a leading voice in the tech industry. The magazine was based in San Francisco, California, and covered technology news and trends from Silicon Valley and beyond.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'At the height of the dot-com boom, The Industry Standard became a symbol of the tech economy''s excesses. The magazine was known for its lavish parties and extravagant spending. However, as the tech bubble burst, The Industry Standard''s fortunes began to decline.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2001, The Industry Standard ceased publication, citing financial difficulties.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Industry Standard covered a wide range of topics related to the technology industry. The magazine featured articles on emerging trends and technologies, as well as profiles of industry figures and analysis of market trends.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was known for its in-depth reporting and analysis of the tech industry. It was also praised for its design and layout, which was considered innovative for its time.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Industry Standard had a devoted readership in the tech industry and was widely respected for its reporting and analysis. The magazine received numerous awards for journalism and design, including a National Magazine Award in 2000 for General Excellence.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, The Industry Standard also faced criticism for its role in promoting the dot-com bubble. The magazine was accused of glossing over the risks and challenges facing the industry, and of contributing to an atmosphere of hype and speculation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its relatively short run, The Industry Standard had a significant impact on the technology industry. The magazine helped to define the culture of Silicon Valley during the dot-com era, and its coverage of emerging technologies and trends was influential in shaping the direction of the industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, The Industry Standard is remembered as a symbol of the dot-com era, and its legacy serves as a cautionary tale about the risks of hype and speculation in the technology industry.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Indy Men's Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Indy Men''s Magazine', N'indy-mens-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A lifestyle magazine for men focusing on fashion, style, health, fitness, and entertainment, founded in 1999 and ceased publication in 2009 due to the decline of print media and the effects of the Great Recession.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Indy Men''s Magazine, also known as Independent Men''s Magazine, was a lifestyle publication in the United States. It catered to men and covered topics such as fashion, style, health, fitness, and entertainment.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Indy Men was founded in 1999 by Mark A. Zappa in Tampa, Florida. It was initially launched as a regional magazine focused on the Tampa Bay area, but later expanded to cover a broader audience.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Indy Men showcased exclusive interviews from prominent figures, including actors, musicians, and other celebrities. The magazine also covered local events, reviews on latest gadgets, and sports activities.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2009, due to the decline of print media and the effects of the Great Recession, Indy Men ceased publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Indy Men Magazine was targeted at the modern man who was looking for an independent and resourceful outlook towards life. The publication featured profiles of successful businessmen and entrepreneurs, along with articles on cars, technology, and travel.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Indy Men also featured interviews with musicians, athletes, actors, and other prominent figures. The magazine had numerous columns, including "The Rules," which offered tips on fashion and style, and "Man Cave," which covered the latest in gear and gadgets.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Indy Men had a relatively small readership but was respected for its focus on men''s lifestyle topics. The magazine''s distinctive voice and unique content helped it stand out in a crowded market.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, Indy Men faced challenges competing with larger, more established men''s publications like Maxim and GQ. The magazine''s decline and eventual closure were one of many casualties of the print media industry''s upheaval in the 2000s and 2010s.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Indy Men magazine was a unique and independent voice in the men''s publishing world. Its focus on lifestyle topics and interviews with prominent figures set it apart from its competitors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, Indy Men is remembered as a publication that challenged traditional notions of masculinity and provided a fresh perspective on what it meant to be a modern man in the twenty-first century.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- InformationWeek
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'InformationWeek', N'informationweek', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A weekly magazine and online publication that focused on information technology news, analysis, and research, including software, hardware, security, cloud computing, mobile devices, and industry trends.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'InformationWeek was a weekly print and online magazine in the United States that focused on information technology (IT). It provided news, analysis, and research on various topics related to IT, including software, hardware, security, cloud computing, mobile devices, and industry trends.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'InformationWeek was founded in 1985 by CMP Media, a company that specializes in media and marketing. It was first published in print as a bi-weekly magazine and later shifted to a weekly publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print publication, InformationWeek launched a website in 1995 to complement its print publication and provide content to its growing readership. The website provided news, blogs, interactive features, and whitepapers on various IT topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2013, InformationWeek merged with CRN, an IT industry magazine, to form CRN Tech. The InformationWeek website was retained as a separate site under the CRN Tech umbrella.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'InformationWeek provided its readers with a mix of news, analysis, and research on IT topics. The publication covered a wide range of issues related to software, hardware, security, cloud computing, mobile devices, and industry trends.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also featured articles on best practices for businesses, including strategies for managing IT projects and advice on how to maximize the return on investment (ROI) of IT initiatives.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'InformationWeek was known for its annual ranking of the top 500 technology companies in the United States, as well as its InformationWeek 500 award, which recognized the most innovative users of IT.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'InformationWeek had a large readership among IT professionals, including CIOs, CTOs, and other IT executives and managers. The magazine was respected in the industry for its comprehensive coverage of IT topics and its focus on providing practical guidance and strategic advice to its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, InformationWeek received numerous awards for its content, including the Neal award, which recognizes excellence in business journalism, and the Webby award, which honors excellence on the internet.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'InformationWeek was a significant player in the IT industry for over three decades. Its comprehensive coverage of IT topics and its focus on providing strategic advice and practical guidance to its readers helped it become a trusted resource for IT professionals.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, InformationWeek is remembered as a publication that helped shape the IT industry and provided insights and guidance to its readers on how to leverage technology to support their businesses.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Innerloop
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Innerloop', N'innerloop', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly video game magazine that covered news, reviews, and culture related to video games, including consoles and computer games, published by Ziff Davis.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Innerloop was a monthly video game magazine in the United States that covered news and reviews on various video game consoles and computer games. The magazine was published by Ziff Davis and was in circulation from 1995 to 1998.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Innerloop was first published in 1995 as a monthly video game magazine. It was published by Ziff Davis, a company known for its computer-related publications. The magazine was headquartered in San Francisco, California, and had a circulation of approximately 100,000 copies at its peak.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Innerloop provided its readers with game reviews, previews, and news on consoles, including the PlayStation, Saturn, and Nintendo 64, as well as computer games. The magazine also covered video game culture and technology.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Innerloop''s content was divided into several sections, including "Reviews," "Previews," "News," "Technology," and "Culture." The "Reviews" section provided in-depth reviews of the latest video games and was complemented by a rating system that used a five-star scale.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The "Previews" section featured exclusive looks at upcoming video games that had not yet been released. The "News" section covered the latest video game industry news, including game announcements, release dates, and industry trends.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The "Technology" section of Innerloop focused on emerging video game technologies, including virtual reality and online gaming, among other topics. The "Culture" section covered video game events, personalities, and the growing popularity of video games in mainstream culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Audience and Reception' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Innerloop had a loyal readership among video game enthusiasts and was known for its honest and thorough reviews of video games. The magazine was also respected in the industry for its in-depth coverage of emerging video game technologies.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Innerloop received several awards for its content, including the Computer Press Award for "Best New Magazine of the Year" in 1995 and "Best Gaming Magazine" in 1997.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Innerloop''s focus on video game culture and technology helped it become a trusted resource for video game enthusiasts in the mid-1990s. The magazine''s in-depth reviews and exclusive previews helped shape the video game industry and influence the purchasing decisions of many players.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, Innerloop is remembered as a pioneering video game magazine that helped shape the way video game journalism is conducted and brought video game culture into the mainstream.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

