INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An online magazine that provided daily news and commentary on Jewish culture, history, literature, and philosophy from secular, religious, and academic perspectives.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Jewish Ideas Daily{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jewish Ideas Daily was an online magazine that provided readers with daily news, commentary, and reviews on Jewish culture, history, literature, and philosophy. The magazine was founded in 2009 by Avi Shafran and Daniel Septimus and was based in New York City, United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jewish Ideas Daily''s content focused on Jewish thought and ideas, including those of secular, religious, and academic perspectives. The magazine''s mission was to present Jewish ideas and their relevance to contemporary issues in a thoughtful and accessible manner.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Jewish Ideas Daily covered a wide range of topics related to Jewish culture, knowledge, philosophy, and history, including debates around Torah interpretation, Jewish law, the role of Israel in Judaism, and the relationship between Jews and non-Jews. The magazine also regularly featured book reviews, art and culture pieces, and thought-provoking essays and articles.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The online magazine released a weekly newsletter, and its website offered free online access to a comprehensive archive of articles. The website was available in both English and Hebrew, making the magazine''s content accessible to international audiences.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its initial popularity and comprehensive approach to Jewish thought, Jewish Ideas Daily eventually saw a decrease in readership and was shut down in 2017. However, the magazine remains an important resource for anyone interested in in-depth discussions and analyses of Jewish culture and ideas.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Jewish Observer
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Jewish Observer', N'the-jewish-observer', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly magazine that served as a leading voice of the Orthodox Jewish community in the United States, featuring articles on Jewish law, contemporary issues, history, and profiles of leaders.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## The Jewish Observer{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Jewish Observer was a monthly Orthodox Jewish magazine published by Agudath Israel of America from 1963 to 2008. The magazine was based in Brooklyn, New York, and was edited by an editorial board led by Rabbi Nosson Scherman.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Jewish Observer featured articles on Jewish law, contemporary issues in Judaism, Jewish history, and profiles of Jewish leaders. The magazine was known for its editorial stance, which was firmly rooted in Orthodox Judaism, and often published articles defending traditional Jewish positions on issues like Torah study, the role of women in Judaism, and Jewish education.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Jewish Observer was particularly active in the 1970s and 1980s, during which time it developed a reputation as a leading voice of the Orthodox Jewish community in the United States. The magazine often published articles on controversial issues within the Orthodox community, including debates over the legality of certain Jewish customs and the role of women in Jewish religious life.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its monthly print publication, The Jewish Observer also published an annual yearbook that featured articles on Jewish holidays, Israel, and profiles of prominent Jewish leaders. The magazine''s content was also made available online at its website.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity and importance within the Orthodox Jewish community, The Jewish Observer faced financial difficulties in its later years, which led to its eventual closure in 2008. However, the magazine remains an important historical document of the Orthodox Jewish community in the United States and its concerns and debates.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- John Martin''s Book
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
