 online, however, and its articles continue to be cited as influential in the field of legal journalism.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Liberty
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Liberty', N'liberty', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription An American weekly magazine that covered politics, culture, and sports, known for its influence in investigative reporting and striking cover art.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Liberty magazine was a weekly American magazine published from 1924 to 1950. The magazine was a general-interest publication that covered a wide range of topics, including politics, culture, sports, and entertainment.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Originally founded by Joseph Patterson, the publisher of the New York Daily News, Liberty became one of the most popular magazines of its time and had a circulation of over two million in the mid-1930s. The magazine was known for its high-quality writing and notable contributions from well-known authors, including Ernest Hemingway, William Faulkner, and H.L. Mencken.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the 1930s, Liberty began to focus on investigative reporting, breaking several major stories on political corruption and criminal activity. The magazine''s investigative journalism played an important role in shaping public opinion and exposing wrongdoing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its serious articles, Liberty also featured cartoons, fiction, and photographs. The magazine was known for its striking cover art, which often featured attractive women and dynamic action scenes.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During World War II, Liberty became a leading publication for war-related news and analysis, and was recognized for its balanced reporting and patriotic spirit. The magazine also became a major force in promoting American propaganda and supporting the war effort. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Following the war, Liberty faced significant financial challenges and declining circulation, and the magazine ceased publication in 1950. Despite its demise, Liberty remains an important part of the history of American journalism, known for its pioneering investigative reporting and influential cultural coverage.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Lies of Our Times
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Lies of Our Times', N'lies-of-our-times', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly political magazine that offered a left-wing perspective and critical analysis of US foreign policy, known for its fearless investigative reporting.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Lies of Our Times (LOOT) was a monthly political magazine first published in 1990. The magazine''s tagline was "The Corporate Watchdogs Who Don''t Bite," and it was known for its criticism of the media and its investigative reporting.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded by John Hanrahan, a former Washington Post reporter, LOOT aimed to provide an alternative perspective to mainstream media. The magazine focused on exposing political and corporate corruption, advocating for social justice, and providing analysis of current events from a left-wing perspective.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'LOOT was particularly critical of U.S. foreign policy, exposing what it saw as the government''s lies and propaganda. The magazine consistently spoke out against American military interventions and criticized the mainstream media for its coverage of international affairs.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its limited circulation, LOOT gained a reputation for its hard-hitting journalism and fearless approach to reporting on controversial issues. Notable writers for the magazine included Howard Zinn, Noam Chomsky, and Alexander Cockburn.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2001, LOOT ceased publication due to financial difficulties and declining readership. Despite its relatively short run, the magazine left a lasting impact on alternative media and political activism, inspiring a new generation of independent journalists to challenge the status quo.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While LOOT received criticism from some for its extreme left-wing views and perceived bias, it remains a significant example of a magazine that challenged mainstream media narratives and was unafraid to speak out against power and authority.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Life
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Life', N'life', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A historic American magazine known for its iconic photojournalism, human interest stories and coverage of World War II.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Life was an American weekly magazine published from 1883 to 1972 and again from 1978 to 2000. The magazine was known for its photojournalism and human interest stories, and has been described as one of the most popular and influential magazines in U.S. history.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded by John Ames Mitchell, Life initially focused on literature, theater, and humor. After several failed attempts to revitalize the magazine with different themes, it was relaunched as a pictorial magazine in 1936. From then on, Life showcased some of the most iconic photographs of the 20th century, featuring prominent figures such as Marilyn Monroe, John F. Kennedy, and Martin Luther King Jr.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During World War II, Life became known for its coverage of the war and its impact on soldiers and civilians. The magazine''s images of war-torn Europe and the Pacific gained widespread recognition and helped shape Americans'' view of the conflict. Life continued to cover politics, culture, and social issues throughout the 1950s and ''60s, providing a snapshot of American life during a time of significant change.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, the rise of television and other forms of media contributed to declining readership and financial difficulties, leading to the magazine''s demise in 1972. The name was later purchased and used for special editions and book series before being briefly revived as a monthly from 1978 to 2000.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Overall, Life Magazine remains a celebrated publication in media history, noted for its cultural impact and groundbreaking photojournalism. The magazine inspired imitators and successors alike, and its aesthetic and storytelling approach continue to influence media today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Life with Archie
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Life with Archie', N'life-with-archie', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A comic book series that explores alternate futures for Archie and his friends, tackling mature themes and breaking new ground in comic storytelling.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Life with Archie was a comic book series published by Archie Comics from 2010 to 2014. It was part of Archie Comics'' main continuity and focused on the adult lives of Archie, Betty, Veronica, and the other characters from the Archie Comics universe.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The series was launched in response to changing reader demographics and to tackle social issues such as marriage equality, gun control, and the #BlackLivesMatter movement. Life with Archie depicted alternate futures for Archie and his friends, one in which he marries Betty, and another in which he marries Veronica.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The series featured a diverse cast of characters and explored issues such as interracial marriage, disability, and political corruption. Life with Archie gained praise for its progressive themes and mature storytelling, breaking new ground in the world of comic books.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'However, the series was short-lived, ending with issue #36 due to low sales. The final issue depicted Archie''s death while saving the life of his friend, Senator Kevin Keller. The issue generated significant media attention and was the subject of much debate among fans.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its brief run, Life with Archie remains a significant moment in the history of Archie Comics and comic book storytelling as a whole. The series tackled important social issues and demonstrated the power of comics to engage with difficult topics with sensitivity and nuance.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Little Corporal
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Little Corporal', N'the-little-corporal', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly children''s magazine published in the United States from 1865 to 1877, known for its mix of fiction, poetry, educational articles, and illustrations by notable artists.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## The Little Corporal{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Little Corporal was a monthly children''s magazine published in the United States from 1865 to 1877. The magazine was aimed at children between the ages of six and sixteen, and focused on education and entertainment.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Little Corporal was founded and edited by Alfred O. Tate, an educator and writer from Illinois. The magazine was named after Napoleon Bonaparte, who was known as "The Little Corporal" during his youth.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was notable for its mixture of fiction, poetry, puzzles, and educational articles. It also featured illustrations by noted artists of the time, such as Thomas Nast and Winslow Homer.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the most popular features of The Little Corporal was the "Letter-Box," in which readers could submit questions, poems, and essays for publication. The magazine also encouraged readers to form "Little Corporal Clubs," which were groups of children who met to discuss the magazine and its contents.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Little Corporal ceased publication in 1877 due to financial difficulties, but its legacy lived on. The magazine was influential in shaping children''s literature in the United States, and helped to popularize the concept of children''s magazines and publications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, The Little Corporal is remembered as an important part of American literary history, and its impact on children''s literature continues to be studied and celebrated.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Little Folks
