VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A former British men''s lifestyle magazine covering fashion, fitness, and sports, with a readership primarily composed of urban, affluent men.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Men was a British men''s lifestyle magazine published between 1985 and 2012. The magazine was initially published on a monthly basis before transitioning to bi-monthly and quarterly publications.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s content was focused on men''s fashion, fitness, health, and lifestyle. It regularly featured articles on grooming, style, and fashion, as well as covering topics such as travel, motorsports, and gadgets.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Men also had a reputation for its coverage of sports, particularly football, and included regular features on the Premier League and other sporting events. The magazine''s readership was primarily composed of affluent, urban men between the ages of 20 and 40.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In its later years of publication, Men shifted its focus towards digital content and online publishing. The magazine''s website, MenStuff.co.uk, continues to feature lifestyle, fashion, and travel content for men.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Men ceased publication in 2012 following a decline in print media sales and widespread changes in the media industry. The magazine''s legacy remains as a testament to British men''s lifestyle and fashion trends throughout the late 20th and early 21st centuries.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Men's Fitness
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Men''s Fitness', N'mens-fitness', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A former monthly US-based health and fitness magazine focused on men''s physical and mental wellbeing, featuring workout routines and articles on current health trends.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Men''s Fitness was a US-based health and fitness magazine focused on men''s physical and mental wellness. The magazine was published by American Media, Inc. and had a monthly circulation of over 600,000 readers.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Men''s Fitness was initially launched in 1987 as a men''s health and lifestyle magazine but underwent a rebranding in the 2000s to focus more on fitness and exercise. The magazine''s content included workout routines, healthy meal plans, and articles on mental health and wellbeing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also covered current trends in health and fitness, including the rise of CrossFit and other popular workout programs. Additionally, Men''s Fitness regularly featured interviews with professional athletes and fitness experts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2018, American Media, Inc. sold Men''s Fitness to American Media LLC, which merged the magazine with Muscle & Fitness to form a new publication called Muscle & Fitness Hers and renamed Men''s Fitness as Men''s Journal.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Men''s Fitness ceased print production in 2017, with subsequent issues only being available in digital formats. Though the magazine is no longer in print, its legacy remains as a testament to the importance of physical and mental fitness in men''s health.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Mental Floss
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Mental Floss', N'mental-floss', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A US-based magazine and website focused on trivia, pop culture, and general knowledge featuring articles, quizzes, and videos, founded in 2001.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Mental Floss is an American magazine and website focused on trivia, pop culture, and general knowledge. The magazine was founded in 2001 by Will Pearson and Mangesh Hattikudur and is currently owned by Minute Media.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Mental Floss publishes ten issues each year, and its content is primarily composed of lists and articles on history, science, language, and culture. The magazine is known for its unique, humorous approach to trivia and fun facts.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print magazine, Mental Floss also has a strong online presence. The magazine''s website features additional articles, quizzes, and videos on various topics, as well as an online store selling books, games, and other merchandise.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Mental Floss has a loyal readership and is recognized for its engaging and educational content. In addition to its regular magazine issues, the publication has also released several books, including "Condensed Knowledge" and "The Mental Floss History of the World."' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2011, Mental Floss was acquired by Felix Dennis''s company, Dennis Publishing. In 2021, the magazine was sold to Minute Media, a global sports media and technology company headquartered in Tel Aviv.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Merry's Museum
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Merry''s Museum', N'merrys-museum', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A mid-19th century American children''s magazine featuring stories, poems, puzzles, and educational articles, known for its high-quality illustrations and contributions from well-known writers.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Merry''s Museum was an American children''s magazine published from 1841 to 1877. The magazine was founded by Samuel Griswold Goodrich, who also wrote under the pseudonym Peter Parley.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Merry''s Museum was intended to be both entertaining and educational. The magazine contained a mix of stories, poems, puzzles, and educational articles, often with an emphasis on moral values and good behavior.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was popular among children and families in the mid-19th century, and its circulation grew rapidly in the years following its launch. In addition to its regular magazine issues, Merry''s Museum also produced several books, including "Peter Parley''s Tales About America" and "The Children''s Scrap-Book."' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Merry''s Museum was known for its high-quality illustrations and engravings, which were done by some of the leading artists of the day. The magazine also featured contributions from many well-known writers, including Louisa May Alcott and Horatio Alger Jr.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over time, Merry''s Museum faced increased competition from other children''s magazines, as well as changing tastes among its readership. The magazine ceased publication in 1877, after nearly four decades in print. Despite its relatively short lifespan, Merry''s Museum played an important role in the development of children''s literature and publishing in America.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Metal Edge
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Metal Edge', N'metal-edge', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A music magazine focused on heavy metal and hard rock music, featuring coverage of bands, interviews with musicians, album reviews, and more.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Metal Edge was an American music magazine that specialized in heavy metal and hard rock music. The magazine was founded by Gerri Miller and Paul Sacks and was published from 1985 to 2009.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine gained a reputation for its in-depth coverage of heavy metal and hard rock bands, and its annual readers'' poll, the "Metal Edge Readers'' Choice Awards" was a highly anticipated event among metal fans. In addition to this, the magazine also published special issues surrounding subjects like the best albums of the year and the history of heavy metal music.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Metal Edge included interviews with many famous music personalities from the heavy metal and hard rock genres, such as Ozzy Osbourne, Metallica, Kiss, and Guns N'' Roses among others. Concert listings, tour dates, and album reviews were a regular feature of the magazine. The magazine was often considered a vital source of information for metal fans in the pre-internet era.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to the print edition, Metal Edge also had a popular online presence and had multimedia features on the website. The magazine produced several video and audio programs, including online radio programs and video interviews with bands and musicians.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'When the magazine was at its peak of popularity, it faced a few financial difficulties in the early 2000s, which was said to have been attributed to the rise of the internet and the decline of print media. In 2009, Metal Edge ceased publication, leaving behind almost a 25-year legacy of successful and influential music journalism.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Metal Maniacs
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Metal Maniacs', N'metal-maniacs', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly heavy metal magazine that focused on underground and independent bands, featuring in-depth interviews, concert and album reviews, and an annual readers'' poll.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Metal Maniacs was a monthly heavy metal magazine that was published in the United States from 1989 to 2009. It was founded by Walter O''Brien and Kathiryn Petersen, and was considered one of the most influential metal magazines of its time.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its 20-year run, Metal Maniacs covered all sub-genres of metal music including death, black, thrash, power, and progressive metal. The magazine was known for its focus on underground and independent bands, as well as for featuring in-depth interviews with influential musicians, including Slayer, Metallica, Sepultura, and Iron Maiden.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Metal Maniacs also included features such as concert reviews, CD reviews, and columnists who shared their insights and opinions on the scene. The magazine was also known for its annual "Readers'' Poll Awards," which allowed readers to vote for their favorite bands and albums.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print publication, Metal Maniacs had a strong online presence, with its website featuring exclusive content and interviews. The magazine also produced several compilation CDs, each featuring songs by independent and underground bands within the metal genre.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its popularity, Metal Maniacs faced financial difficulties in the late 2000s and ceased publication in 2009. The magazine left behind a legacy as a respected voice within the metal community and played a significant role in shaping the landscape of metal music journalism.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Metaphysical Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Metaphysical Magazine', N'the-metaphysical-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly magazine focused on spirituality and metaphysical topics, featuring contributions from well-known philosophers and spiritualists.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Metaphysical Magazine was a monthly publication that focused on spirituality and metaphysical topics. It was published in the United States from 1895 to 1905.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine was founded by Leander Edmund Whipple and William James. It covered a range of topics related to spirituality, including mysticism, psychic phenomena, and the study of esoteric philosophies. The magazine was known for featuring articles from both well-known and obscure writers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Metaphysical Magazine also featured contributions from philosophers and spiritualists such as William James, Ada V. Dwyer, Thomas Troward, William Walker Atkinson, and many others. It provided a platform for readers to explore and discuss spiritual topics, with a focus on spiritual growth and development.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its publication, the magazine underwent several changes to its name, merging at one point with another publication, "Mind," to become "Mind and Metaphysics." During its run, The Metaphysical Magazine covered a broad range of spiritual topics that were considered progressive and forward-thinking for its time, influencing the evolution of the spiritual and metaphysical movements.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Magazine ceased publication around 1905, but its impact on the spiritual community was far-reaching. The publication of The Metaphysical Magazine marked the beginning of a new era of spirituality and helped pave the way for a growing interest in the study of the human mind and consciousness.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Metronome
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Metronome', N'Metronome', 1, 'en' );
