 coverage of important issues affecting the Hispanic community, such as immigration and social justice.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has also been recognized for supporting emerging Latino artists and musicians, providing a platform for up-and-coming talent on the Hispanic entertainment scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Awards and Recognition' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'H magazine has received numerous awards and accolades for its work over the years. In 2004, the magazine won the National Association of Hispanic Publications Award for Best Magazine for its coverage of the September 11 attacks.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has also received recognition for its coverage of the Latin Grammy Awards, including a nomination for Best National Publication in 2015.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## References' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- "H Magazine." Telemundo. Created on 12 December 2009, Accessed 1 August 2023. https://www.telemundo52.com/especiales/5-cosas-que-no-sabias-sobre-la-revista-h/1860229/.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- "About H Magazine." H Magazine. Accessed 1 August 2023. https://www.hmagazine.com/about-us/.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- H. P. Lovecraft's Magazine of Horror
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'H. P. Lovecraft''s Magazine of Horror', N'h-p-lovecrafts-magazine-of-horror', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A bi-monthly horror fiction and literature magazine published in the United States between 1979 and 1985, aimed at showcasing new authors and promoting the horror fiction genre.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'H. P. Lovecraft''s Magazine of Horror was a bi-monthly publication dedicated to horror fiction and related topics, published in the United States between 1979 and 1985. The magazine was named after H. P. Lovecraft, a prominent author of horror fiction in the early 20th century.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'H. P. Lovecraft''s Magazine of Horror was first published in 1979 by George H. Scithers, Darrell Schweitzer, and John M. Ford. The magazine was published out of Philadelphia and aimed to publish high-quality horror fiction, scholarship, and criticism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first issue included stories by well-known authors such as Ramsey Campbell, Thomas Ligotti, and Manly Wade Wellman. In addition to stories, the magazine also published reviews, interviews, and essays on horror literature and related topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'H. P. Lovecraft''s Magazine of Horror published a wide variety of horror fiction, ranging from traditional ghost stories to modern psychological thrillers. In addition to fiction, the magazine also published non-fiction articles on horror literature and related topics. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine''s recurring features was "The Eyrie," a letters column which included commentary on horror literature and fan culture, as well as responses from the editorial team.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although H. P. Lovecraft''s Magazine of Horror was only published for six years, it had a significant impact on horror literature and fan culture. The magazine helped to revive interest in horror fiction and played a role in the emergence of the "weird fiction" subgenre.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also provided a platform for new authors to showcase their work, including some who went on to achieve significant acclaim in the horror and fantasy genres.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## References' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Schweitzer, Darrell. "H.P. Lovecraft''s Magazine of Horror." Encyclopedia of Fantasy, edited by John Clute and John Grant, Orbit Books, 1997, p. 477.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Lovecraft, H. P. The Complete Fiction of H. P. Lovecraft, edited by S.T. Joshi, Barnes & Noble, Inc., 2008, pp. 995-996.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Ham Radio Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Ham Radio Magazine', N'ham-radio-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A monthly publication catering to amateur radio enthusiasts in the United States, featuring technical aspects, news and opinions, construction projects, and equipment reviews.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ham Radio magazine was a monthly publication established in 1968 to serve amateur radio enthusiasts in the United States. The magazine was dedicated to the technical and practical aspects of amateur radio communication, as well as news and opinions related to the hobby.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ham Radio magazine was first published in June 1968 by Wayne Green, W2NSD. The magazine was published out of a small office in New Hampshire, with Green serving as editor and publisher.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine primarily focused on technical aspects of amateur radio, including construction projects, antenna design, and equipment reviews. However, it also included news and opinion pieces related to the amateur radio community, including regulatory and legal issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ham Radio magazine''s content was divided into several sections, including features, construction projects, equipment reviews, and letters to the editor. The magazine also featured a regular column titled "Never Say Die," which focused on troubleshooting and problem-solving in amateur radio communications.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, the magazine included interviews with prominent figures in the amateur radio community, as well as coverage of major events and contests in the hobby.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Ham Radio magazine played an important role in the growth and development of the amateur radio hobby in the United States. The magazine helped to spread knowledge and information about the technical aspects of amateur radio, and provided a platform for enthusiasts to share their experiences and opinions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also helped to build a sense of community among amateur radio operators, by providing a forum for discussion and debate about the hobby and its future.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## References' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Green, Wayne. "Ham Radio." 73 Magazine, October 1970, pp. 70-76.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- "Ham Radio Magazine." QST, August 1968, p. 102.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

