VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A bi-monthly American magazine covering news, analysis, and commentary on issues and topics of interest to the Latino community in the United States.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic magazine is a bi-monthly publication that focuses on delivering news, analysis, and commentary about and for the Latino community in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic magazine was founded in 1987 by Jesus Chavarria and Kirk Whisler. The magazine''s goal was to provide an authoritative voice for the Latino community in the United States, covering issues and topics of interest to the Hispanic-American population.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine has evolved its coverage, expanding into areas such as education, politics, entertainment, and finance.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic magazine covers a wide range of topics related to the Latino community, including immigration, politics, culture, and education. The magazine features in-depth coverage of current events and trends affecting the Hispanic-American population, as well as profiles of notable individuals and businesses in the community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print publication, Hispanic magazine maintains a strong online presence, featuring exclusive content and multimedia features for its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic magazine has won numerous awards for its journalism and its dedication to representing the interests of the Hispanic-American community. In 1994, the magazine was awarded the National Hispanic Hero Award for its outstanding contributions to the Latino community. In 2008, it received the Chispa Award for its coverage of Hispanic issues.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine has also been featured in major media outlets, including The New York Times, The Washington Post, and CNN.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## References' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- "National Hispanic Hero Award Recipients." Hispanic Heritage Foundation. Accessed September 23, 2021.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Hispanic magazine. Hispanic Publishing Corporation. Accessed September 23, 2021.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- "Hispanic Magazine: A Voice for a Growing Community." The New York Times. Accessed September 23, 2021.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Hispanic Enterprise Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Hispanic Enterprise', N'hispanic-enterprise', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A bimonthly American publication providing news, analysis, and success stories for the Hispanic business community in the United States.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic Enterprise, also known as Hispanic Enterprise Magazine, was a bimonthly publication established in Los Angeles, California in 1982 and focused on the Hispanic business communities in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic Enterprise was founded by Peter Villegas in 1982 to provide a platform for Hispanic business owners and professionals to exchange ideas and share experiences. The magazine was headquartered in Los Angeles, California, and distributed throughout the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'During its publication, the magazine provided news related to Hispanic-owned businesses in the US as well as analysis of the Hispanic business community. It aimed to be a source of inspiration and success stories for emerging entrepreneurs, by featuring in-depth profiles of successful Hispanic business owners, executives, and professionals.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic Enterprise provided extensive coverage on a variety of topics that are relevant to the Hispanic business community including finance, entrepreneurship, marketing, politics, and management. The publication''s articles, interviews, and profiles highlighted both challenges and opportunities faced by Hispanic professionals in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print publication, Hispanic Enterprise maintained an active website which also included multimedia features and exclusive content for its readers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic Enterprise was widely recognized as a significant player in the Hispanic business community and was awarded various accolades for its journalism and service to the community. In 2005, it was awarded the Best Magazine award from the National Hispanic Publications Association (NHPA).' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'According to the publication''s website, Hispanic Enterprise published its last magazine issue in 2015 as it merged with sister publication, Hispanic Executive to form "Hispanic Executive" with the aim of providing more extensive coverage of Hispanic business communities in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## References' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- "Hispanic Enterprise Magazine". Hispanic Enterprise. Accessed September 25, 2021.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- National Association of Hispanic Publications. "NAHP now accepting entries for the 2005 José Marti Publishing Awards". October 17, 2005. Accessed September 25, 2021. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- Hispanic Enterprise Magazine, California State University, Dominguez Hills, September 25, 2021.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Hispanic Link Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Hispanic Link', N'hispanic-link', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A weekly American publication reporting on issues and events affecting the Hispanic community in the United States, from politics to culture and entertainment.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic Link, also known as Hispanic Link Weekly Report, was a weekly newspaper established in 1981 and focused on news, information, and commentary related to the U.S. Hispanic community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic Link was founded in 1981 by Charlie Ericksen, a journalist and former newspaper editor who recognized the need for a publication to report directly on events and issues affecting the Hispanic community in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The newspaper located its offices in Washington, D.C., and established its presence in the region by covering the proceedings of the United States Congress, the White House, and other government agencies with a focus on issues of concern to the Hispanic community. Hispanic Link quickly became a leading source of news and information for the Hispanic community in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The first edition of the newspaper was printed on October 8, 1981, as a weekly publication known as the Hispanic Link Weekly Report. The newspaper derived its name from its early days when it was distributed through a network of communications links established among various Hispanic organizations and activists throughout the country.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic Link provided in-depth news coverage of the U.S. Hispanic community, with a focus on highlighting the important issues and concerns faced by Hispanic Americans. Its reporting spanned a wide range of topics, including politics, immigration, education, business, culture, and entertainment.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, Hispanic Link was known for its commitment to producing high-quality journalism that accurately represented the diverse Latino community in the United States. Its editorial content was written by a team of experienced journalists and columnists, who provided original reporting, analysis, and commentary on issues of relevance to the Hispanic community.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The newspaper also produced special issues focused on specific topics of importance to the Hispanic community, including immigration reform, civil rights, and voting rights.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hispanic Link quickly became one of the most respected and widely-read sources of news and information for the U.S. Hispanic community. Over the years, it was awarded numerous accolades for its journalism, including multiple awards from the National Association of Hispanic Publications (NAHP).' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2010, the newspaper ceased print publication due to financial constraints, but continued as an online publication until 2016. Its legacy as a leading voice for the U.S. Hispanic community lives on, and its reporting and commentary continue to be cited by journalists, policymakers, and scholars interested in the issues that impact the Latino community in the United States.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## References' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'- "About Hispanic Link". Hispanic Link. Accessed September 29, 2021{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- HM Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'HM Magazine', N'hm-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A defunct American music magazine catering to the Christian metal and alternative music scene, featuring news, reviews and interviews with popular bands and artists.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HM Magazine (formerly known as Heaven''s Metal) was a monthly periodical that covered the Christian metal and alternative music scene. The magazine was known for featuring news, reviews, and interviews with popular bands and artists, and had a circulation of roughly 15,000 readers at its peak.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HM Magazine was first published in 1985 under its original name, Heaven''s Metal. The magazine was founded by Doug Van Pelt, a Christian musician and journalist who wanted to create a publication that would cover the growing Christian metal scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Initially, Heaven''s Metal was a small publication that focused on heavy metal bands with Christian themes or messages. However, as the Christian alternative music scene grew and diversified, the magazine began to cover a wider range of genres, including punk rock, hardcore, and alternative rock.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1995, the magazine changed its name to HM Magazine, reflecting its coverage of a wider range of genres beyond metal. The magazine continued to be a leading voice in the Christian alternative music scene throughout the 1990s and 2000s, featuring interviews with popular bands like Switchfoot, Flyleaf, and Underoath.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2010, HM Magazine ceased print publication and shifted its focus to an online-only format. The website continued to feature news, reviews, and interviews with Christian bands and artists, but the magazine''s influence and readership declined in the subsequent years.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HM Magazine covered a wide range of musical genres over the years, including heavy metal, punk rock, hardcore, and alternative rock. The magazine''s content typically included reviews of new albums, concerts, and music-related products, as well as interviews with musicians and industry professionals.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, HM Magazine maintained a focus on Christian music and its intersection with popular culture. The magazine often explored the religious themes and messages of popular bands and artists, offering a unique perspective on the role of religion in the music industry.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although HM Magazine is no longer published, its legacy continues to be felt in the Christian alternative music scene. The magazine was a leading voice in the scene for over two decades, and played a major role in helping to promote and popularize Christian alternative music.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Many bands and artists were featured in the pages of HM Magazine early in their careers, and the magazine helped to introduce a wide range of Christian musicians to a broader audience. In this way, HM Magazine had a long-lasting impact on the Christian alternative music scene, and its influence is still felt by musicians and fans alike today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Hobby Directory
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Hobby Directory', N'the-hobby-directory', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A comprehensive hobby magazine with features on popular pastimes and directories of hobby-related businesses and services.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Hobby Directory was a monthly magazine that covered a wide variety of hobbies and interests. The magazine was known for its comprehensive directories of hobby-related businesses, as well as its features on a range of popular pastimes.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Hobby Directory was first published in 1978, with the aim of providing hobbyists with a comprehensive guide to businesses and services related to their interests. The magazine quickly became popular with hobbyists of all kinds, and its directories were considered an essential resource for anyone interested in pursuing a hobby.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, The Hobby Directory covered a wide range of hobbies and pastimes, including photography, gardening, woodworking, model building, and more. The magazine also ran regular features on hobby-related topics, with articles on everything from bookbinding to stamp collecting.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the early 2000s, The Hobby Directory saw a decline in readership and revenue, as more hobbyists turned to the internet for information and resources. In 2007, the magazine ceased publication, marking the end of an era in hobby journalism.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Hobby Directory was known for its extensive directories of hobby-related businesses and services. Each issue included listings of hobby shops, suppliers, clubs, and events, organized by geographic location and type of hobby. These directories were considered an essential resource for hobbyists looking to connect with others who shared their interests, or to find specialized products and services.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its directories, The Hobby Directory also featured regular columns and features on a range of hobbies and pastimes. The magazine''s content covered a wide range of interests, from traditional hobbies like stamp collecting and model building, to more niche pursuits like metal detecting and genealogy.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Hobby Directory also included reviews of new products and books related to various hobbies, as well as profiles of notable hobbyists and hobby-related businesses.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although The Hobby Directory is no longer published, its legacy lives on through its many devoted readers and fans. The magazine played a significant role in the hobby world for nearly three decades, and its directories and features helped to connect hobbyists across the country and around the world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, many hobbyists still consider The Hobby Directory to be an essential resource for finding hobby-related businesses and services, and the magazine''s back issues are still prized by collectors and enthusiasts alike.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Hollywood Star Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Hollywood Star', N'hollywood-star', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A popular US entertainment magazine featuring news, gossip, and interviews with Hollywood''s biggest stars.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hollywood Star was a celebrity gossip and entertainment magazine that was published in the United States from 1988 to 2004. The magazine was known for its coverage of Hollywood''s biggest stars and for its eye-catching covers and headlines.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hollywood Star magazine was founded in 1988 by Hudson News and Publishing, a company that also published the National Enquirer and other tabloid magazines. The magazine was designed to compete with other celebrity gossip magazines like People and Us Weekly.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, Hollywood Star became known for its sensationalist headlines and coverage of the most salacious celebrity gossip of the day. The magazine published stories about celebrities'' personal lives, often featuring rumors and speculation about marriages, divorces, and scandals.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hollywood Star also featured interviews with celebrities and coverage of Hollywood events, such as movie premieres and award shows. The magazine''s photographers often captured exclusive photos of celebrities in candid moments or at private events.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2004, Hudson News and Publishing announced that it would be ceasing publication of Hollywood Star due to declining sales and competition from other celebrity gossip magazines.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hollywood Star magazine''s content focused largely on celebrity gossip and scandal. The magazine''s stories often featured juicy details about the personal lives of Hollywood''s biggest stars, including rumors about relationships, affairs, and other scandals.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to celebrity gossip, Hollywood Star also featured coverage of Hollywood events and interviews with celebrities. The magazine''s photographers often captured exclusive photos of celebrities in candid moments or at private events.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hollywood Star''s covers were designed to grab readers'' attention, often featuring provocative headlines and eye-catching photos of celebrities. The magazine was known for its sensationalist style, which sometimes led to criticism from other media outlets.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although Hollywood Star magazine is no longer published, its influence on celebrity gossip culture continues to be felt. The magazine played a significant role in the development of celebrity gossip as a lucrative industry, and its sensationalist style helped to shape the tone of other celebrity gossip magazines that followed.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, celebrity gossip remains a popular topic in both print and online media, and many publications continue to use tactics pioneered by Hollywood Star to grab readers'' attention. Despite its controversial reputation, Hollywood Star helped to establish celebrity gossip as a significant force in popular culture.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Hooey Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Hooey', N'hooey', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A satirical monthly magazine known for its biting political humor and influential cartoons, published in the United States from 1905 to 1917.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hooey is a monthly satirical magazine that was published in the United States from 1905 to 1917. The magazine was known for its sharp political satire and featured cartoons, caricatures, and humorous articles.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hooey was founded in 1905 by cartoonist and writer Frederick Burr Opper. The magazine was published by the National News Company and was priced at 10 cents per issue.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hooey gained a following for its biting political satire, which targeted politicians and public figures of the time. The magazine also featured cartoons, caricatures, and humorous articles on a variety of topics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1908, Hooey published a controversial cartoon that depicted African Americans as subhuman creatures. The cartoon caused outrage among civil rights groups and led to calls for the magazine to cease publication. Although Hooey continued to publish in the years that followed, its popularity waned and the magazine ceased publication in 1917.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Style' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hooey was characterized by its sharp political satire and irreverent humor. The magazine''s cartoons and caricatures were particularly influential, and many of its contributors went on to have successful careers in the cartooning and animation industries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hooey''s humor was often aimed at the political and social issues of the time, and the magazine was known for its criticism of government corruption and corporate greed.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although Hooey had a relatively short publication run, it had a significant impact on the development of American humor and satire. The magazine helped to establish the tradition of political satire in American media, and its influence can be seen in the work of later satirists such as Mort Sahl and Jon Stewart.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Hooey''s legacy also extends to the world of cartoons and comics, with many of its contributors going on to work for influential publications such as The New Yorker and The Saturday Evening Post.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The Horticulturist Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The Horticulturist', N'the-horticulturist', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A 19th-century American monthly magazine focused on gardening and horticulture, known for its high-quality articles and illustrations.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Horticulturist was a monthly magazine that focused on gardening and horticulture. Originally published in the United States in the mid-19th century, the magazine was known for its high-quality articles and illustrations.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Horticulturist was founded in 1846 by horticulturist and author P. Barry. The magazine was published in New York and was priced at $3 per year.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Horticulturist became known for its high-quality articles and illustrations, which covered a wide range of topics related to gardening and horticulture. The magazine also provided information on new varieties of plants and seeds, and offered advice on garden design and cultivation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its high-quality content, The Horticulturist also became known for its distinctive layout and design. The magazine featured a mix of text and illustrations, with color plates and engravings interspersed throughout its pages.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Horticulturist continued to publish for nearly four decades, until it ceased publication in 1881.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Style' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Horticulturist was known for its high-quality articles and illustrations, which were written and produced by leading horticulturists and garden designers of the period. The magazine''s content covered a wide range of topics related to gardening and horticulture, including plant cultivation, garden design, and landscape architecture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its informative content, The Horticulturist was prized for its high-quality illustrations and prints. The magazine employed skilled artists and engravers to produce color plates and engravings that captured the beauty and diversity of the natural world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The Horticulturist had a significant impact on the development of gardening and horticulture in the United States. The magazine helped to popularize gardening as a pastime and a profession, and provided a valuable resource for garden enthusiasts and professionals alike.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its impact on gardening and horticulture, The Horticulturist also helped to establish the tradition of illustrated magazines in the United States. The magazine''s distinctive layout and design influenced the development of other illustrated periodicals of the period, and helped to establish the importance of high-quality printing and illustration in American publishing.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

