VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Online publication and pioneering website that focused on technology, culture, and the internet, known for its innovative content and groundbreaking advertising.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HotWired was an online magazine and pioneering web site that focused on technology, culture, and the internet. Launched in 1994, it was one of the first online publications to feature original content and to experiment with new forms of online advertising.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HotWired was launched in 1994 by Wired Ventures, a media company that was founded by Louis Rossetto and Jane Metcalfe. The magazine was created as a spin-off of Wired magazine, an influential print publication that focused on digital culture and technology.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HotWired was originally designed by the digital agency CKS Partners, which was known for its work on other groundbreaking web sites such as the LucasArts Entertainment Company web site and the Sega Channel.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HotWired quickly established itself as a leading online publication, featuring original content from some of the most influential writers and thinkers of the period. The site also experimented with new forms of online advertising, including the iconic "banner ad" that became a ubiquitous feature of the internet in the years to come.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its innovative content and advertising, HotWired was also known for its bold design and experimental use of multimedia. The site featured interactive graphics, animations, and sound, and was one of the first web sites to feature streaming audio and video.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HotWired published on a near-daily basis for several years, establishing itself as an influential voice in the emerging world of online media. The site also helped to establish Wired Ventures as a major force in the media landscape of the 1990s.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HotWired had a significant impact on the development of online media and advertising, helping to establish the norms and conventions that would shape the internet in the years to come. The site''s bold design and innovative use of multimedia influenced countless other web sites and online publications, while its experimentation with new forms of online advertising helped to establish the internet as a major platform for commercial activity.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, HotWired is remembered as a pioneering publication that played a key role in the early years of the internet and helped to shape the digital culture of the 1990s. While the site is no longer online, its legacy continues to inspire and influence the world of online media and advertising.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- House & Garden Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'House & Garden', N'house-and-garden', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Monthly publication focused on interior design, gardening, and lifestyle, known for its high-quality photography and authoritative editorial voice.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'House & Garden was a monthly magazine that focused on interior design, gardening, and lifestyle. Published by Condé Nast, the magazine was known for its high-quality photography, stylish layout, and authoritative editorial voice.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'House & Garden was first published in the United Kingdom in 1901 as a monthly magazine focused on architecture and interior design. The magazine quickly established itself as a leading voice in the world of design and expanded to cover gardening and lifestyle topics in later years.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 1922, House & Garden launched a U.S. edition, which quickly became one of the most influential home and design publications in the country. The magazine featured some of the most stylish and inspiring interiors of the era, showcasing the work of leading designers and architects such as Frank Lloyd Wright and Elsie de Wolfe.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, House & Garden was known for its unique blend of content, which combined authoritative editorial coverage with stunning photography and innovative layout design. The magazine was also a platform for some of the most influential voices in interior design and gardening, with regular contributions from experts such as Edith Wharton, Gertrude Jekyll, and Vita Sackville-West.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2007, House & Garden ceased publication as a standalone magazine in the United States and United Kingdom. Its content was merged into sister publications Architectural Digest and Vogue, respectively.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its history, House & Garden was an influential voice in the world of interior design, gardening, and lifestyle. The magazine helped to shape popular tastes in home design and was a key platform for some of the most talented and innovative designers and architects of the day.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, House & Garden is remembered as a pioneering publication that helped to shape the world of home and design media. Its legacy continues to inspire and influence the world of interior design and gardening, and its archives remain an invaluable resource for anyone interested in the history of design and decorating.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- House of Mystery Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'House of Mystery', N'house-of-mystery', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Iconic horror comic book series known for its eerie storytelling, striking artwork, and cast of memorable host characters.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'House of Mystery was an American horror comic book series that was published by DC Comics from 1951 to 1983. The series was known for its blend of horror, supernatural elements, and mystery, and featured a rotating cast of creative talent.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'House of Mystery was first published in 1951, as one of DC Comics'' first forays into the horror genre. The series was initially edited by Whitney Ellsworth, and featured a rotating cast of creative talent, including writers such as Jack Oleck and David Michelinie, and artists such as Bernie Wrightson and Neal Adams.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The series featured a recurring framing device, in which the story would be introduced by a host character known as Cain. Cain was a mysterious figure with a sinister sense of humor, who would set up each story with a foreboding introduction. Over time, other host characters were introduced, including Abel, Eve, and Goldie the Gargoyle.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Throughout its run, House of Mystery featured a wide range of horror and supernatural themes, including ghosts, witches, monsters, and otherworldly creatures. The series was also known for its striking cover artwork, which often featured eye-catching and provocative imagery.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the 1970s, House of Mystery shifted towards more socially conscious and politically oriented stories, reflecting the changing cultural landscape of the era. The series became a platform for some of the most talented and innovative writers and artists of the time, and continued to push the boundaries of the horror genre.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'House of Mystery ceased publication in 1983, after more than 30 years in print. The series was later revived in the 2000s, with a new iteration that drew on the legacy of the original series.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'House of Mystery was an important and influential series in the history of horror comics, and helped to establish many of the conventions of the genre. The series was known for its innovative storytelling, striking artwork, and memorable host characters, and has inspired generations of comic book creators.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Today, House of Mystery is remembered as a classic comic book series that pushed the boundaries of the horror genre and helped to pave the way for future generations of horror comics. Its legacy continues to resonate with fans of horror and comic book enthusiasts around the world.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- HOW Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'HOW', N'how', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A design-focused publication providing resources and inspiration for graphic design, typography, and other creative fields, established in 1985.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HOW is a design magazine that covers the latest trends, techniques, and inspiration in graphic design, typography, photography, and other creative fields. The magazine has been published since 1985 and is one of the most respected and widely read publications in the design community.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HOW was founded in 1985 by F+W Media, a media and e-commerce company based in Cincinnati, Ohio. The magazine was initially focused on the business side of graphic design, with articles and features aimed at helping designers run successful businesses.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, HOW has evolved to include a broader range of topics, including design inspiration, creative techniques, and trends in the industry. The publication also expanded to include digital editions and online resources for designers around the world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In 2014, HOW was acquired by F+W''s new parent company, New Track Media. The magazine''s editorial team has remained committed to its mission of providing designers with the resources, information, and inspiration to succeed in their careers.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HOW covers a wide range of topics related to graphic design, typography, photography, illustration, and other creative fields. Each issue of the magazine includes feature articles, profiles, interviews, and tutorials, as well as regular columns covering topics such as branding, packaging design, and web design.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication also produces a variety of special issues throughout the year, including "HOW''s International Design Annual," which features the best of the world''s design work, and "HOW''s Interactive Design Awards," which recognizes the best in digital design.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In addition to its print publication, HOW maintains a robust online presence, including a website that features exclusive content, resources, and job listings for designers. The magazine also hosts a variety of design conferences and events throughout the year, including the annual HOW Design Live conference, which brings together designers, industry experts, and thought leaders from around the world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Impact' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HOW has been an important and influential voice in the design community for over 35 years. The magazine has helped to shape the conversation around design, providing designers with the resources and inspiration to create innovative and effective work.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Through its coverage of trends and techniques in the industry, as well as its focus on the business side of design, HOW has helped designers to grow their careers and achieve success in their fields. The magazine has also played an important role in highlighting the value and impact of design on society as a whole.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- HuH (magazine)
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'HuH', N'huh', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A satirical and alternative humor magazine that flourished in the 1990s, covering pop culture and politics aimed at Gen-Xers.}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Introduction' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH, short for "Here''s How" was a monthly satirical and alternative humor magazine that flourished in the 1990s. The magazine covered topics such as pop culture, politics, and scathing commentary, primarily aimed at Gen-Xers.{{Image image:magazine-cover-not-available.png|Type=PrimaryArticleImage}}' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH was founded in 1986 by Michael Shore and was established as a response to the mainstream media''s lack of coverage for Generation X. It quickly gained popularity for its irreverent editorial style, unique layout, and the inclusion of innovative interactive elements.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine grew rapidly and expanded its readership to a loyal base of Gen-Xers. Through the 1990s, the magazine became an icon of alternative culture, finding a place in coffee shops and independent bookstores across the country.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Different from other alternative publications, which started on fringes and aimed to be counter-culture, HuH became a respected establishment of sorts. It featured notable writers, illustrators, and photographers, who consistently produced witty and thought-provoking content for the publication.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After an impressive 14-year-long career, the magazine was closed in 2000 and turned into an online media outlet. However, in recent years, the magazine has remained inactive, leaving an iconic void in alternative humor publishing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH covered a variety of topics, including music, film, television, and politics. The magazine was known for its irreverent and unique sense of humor, as well as its satirical take on pop culture and current events.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s layout incorporated interactive elements that allowed readers to engage with the content in new ways, such as pop-out letters, hidden messages, and secret codes. HuH also included cartoons, comics, and illustrations alongside its written content.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine featured notable writers, illustrators, and photographers, such as David Foster Wallace, Mark Leyner, Ben Katchor, Bruce McCall, and Roz Chast.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH had a notable impact on the publishing industry and the culture at large, particularly among Gen-Xers. The magazine helped to establish the alternative humor genre and define the aesthetic of 1990s counterculture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'HuH''s influence can still be seen in contemporary publications like The Onion and McSweeney''s, which carry on the tradition of biting satire and originality. HuH magazine further helped to establish alternative media as a way of capturing niche audiences, paving the way for influential publications like Vice and Pitchfork.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

